<SLUG> BC-BBO-NOTEBOOK-GOMEZ-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STEWART BELONGS IN HIS UNIFORM 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By PEDRO GOMEZ  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   As much as  &UR; Dave Stewart pines to wear an Italian suit and sit
in the front office of some club, he needs to reconsider that
notion.
</P>
<P>
   Some people belong in a uniform and Stewart, San Diego's
first-year pitching coach, is at the top of that list.
</P>
<P>
   The scene before the start of Game 1 of the World Series was a
keeper: Here were five of San Diego's pitchers, each of them
wide-eyed with the whole Bronx scene and Stewart was in the middle,
telling war stories from one of the five World Series he pitched
in.
</P>
<P>
   Suddenly,  &UR; Andy Ashby, the antithesis of a big-city guy, was
hop-scotching in the outfield, having the time of his life.
Stewart's strength lies is making his pitchers achieve more than
they thought imaginable.
</P>
<P>
   Ashby, who won a career-high 17 games this season, is a perfect
example of what Stewart accomplished this season. Stewart simply
belongs in a uniform, no ifs, ands or buts. &QL; 
Take this job, please &QL; 
The Los Angles Dodgers are having one heck of a time finding
someone willing to become their manager. It's almost become a
running joke within baseball how they would be willing to take
anyone who will fill the post.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Jim Leyland twice turned down the opportunity for an interview.
 &UR; Felipe Alou had agreed to the job before being overwhelmed by a
counteroffer from Montreal. It now appears (in no particular order)
 &UR; Kevin Kennedy,  &UR; Davey Johnson or  &UR; Jim Fregosi will replace  &UR; Glenn
 &UR; Hoffman, who held the job the last three months on an interim
basis.
</P>
<P>
   The pair of high-profile turndowns has made the FOX folks, who
now own the Dodgers, slightly embarrassed. After all, the Dodgers
are supposed to stand as one of the marquee franchises in baseball.
</P>
<P>
   Now people are wondering what's wrong, why can't they get their
man to manage. New General Manager  &UR; Kevin Malone and club president
 &UR; Bob
 &UR; Graziano are simmering on a bit of a hot seat.
</P>
<P>
   ``Certainly, just like Bob and Kevin, we would be happier if we
were about to be announcing Felipe as the manager,'' said Fox
executive  &UR; Peter Chernin. ``Felipe decided to stay in Montreal, but
that doesn't mean that we blame someone for that. You can't run
these businesses blaming your management every time something goes
wrong. It's just not a realistic way to run things, and I certainly
don't feel like anyone has done anything wrong.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sure, we would prefer to be sitting here with Felipe today,
but he's not here. So we just have to move on.'' &QL; 
No more battling &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Texas Rangers will no longer have to battle their All-Star
catcher,  &UR; Ivan Rodriguez, over playing winter ball. The
commissioner's office took the Rangers' annual headache away from
them last week.
</P>
<P>
   Citing an ``overuse'' clause in the working agreement between
Major League Baseball and the Latin American winter leagues,
players who have at least 250 at-bats in a big-league season are
ineligible to play winter ball.
</P>
<P>
   Rodriguez routinely went against the Rangers' wishes by
submitting himself to 40 or so additional games a year while
playing winter ball in his native Puerto Rico.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Roy Krasik, director of baseball operations for the
commissioner's office, said the clause was included to ensure
needed playing time for younger players and also eliminate demand
on older and more established players to participate in the
leagues.
</P>
<P>
   Veteran stars of the majors are often subjected to intense local
pressure to participate for their country in winter ball.
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers constantly battled their star catcher, wanting him
to drop his winter ball games in order to rejuvenate for the
upcoming season. &QL; 
Mad dog or puppy? &QL; 
In his final post-season starts during his six-year career with
Atlanta,  &UR; Greg Maddux, generally considered the best pitcher of
this era, has yet to win in five attempts. (There were no playoffs
in 1994).
</P>
<P>
   In order, Maddux lost Game 6 of the 1993 NLCS to Philadelphia
and
 &UR; Tommy Greene; in '95 he lost Game 5 to  &UR; Orel Hershiser and
Cleveland before the Braves came back to win it all in Game 6; in
'96 Maddux lost the deciding Game 6 at Yankee Stadium, beaten by
 &UR; Jimmy Key.
</P>
<P>
   Last year Maddux lost to  &UR; Livan Hernandez and the Florida
Marlins in Game 5 and this season it was  &UR; Sterling Hitchcock and
San Diego beating Maddux in Game 3 of the NLCS. &QL; 
Lidle-ing on low &QL; 
The first player to be with both the Diamondbacks and Tampa Bay
Devil Rays, pitcher  &UR; Cory Lidle, didn't necessarily leave Arizona
with a good taste in his mouth.
</P>
<P>
   Lidle, who may never pitch for either club, was claimed by the
Devil Rays two weeks ago when the Diamondbacks tried to slide him
through waivers to their minor league roster, not an uncommon move
with an injured player.
</P>
<P>
   The Diamondbacks wanted Lidle, who first suffered through
shoulder pains before succumbing to ligament damage in his pitching
elbow.
</P>
<P>
   Everything was fine, he said, until he decided to go for the
more radical approach to fix his elbow, ligament replacement
surgery or as it's become more commonly known, `` &UR; Tommy John''
surgery. The Diamondbacks, he said, wanted him to take a more
conservative approach.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was kind of weird because I had some negative vibes from
the Diamondbacks organization once I made the decision to have
surgery,'' Lidle said. ``Before that I felt like part of the team.
But after the surgery they made me feel like I wasn't part of the
team. It was a 100 percent turn and I'm happy to get away from
there.'' &QL; 
THE HIT LIST &QL; 
 &UR; Strap yourself in for some wild times: New Colorado Manager  &UR; Jim
 &UR; Leyland has a career 5-18 record as a visiting manager at Coors
Field. His depleted Marlins won just one of six games at Coors
Field this season.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; From the useless information department.: The San Diego Padres
are the only professional club in the U.S. whose name is entirely
made up of Spanish words.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Flashback (World Series umpire edition): Larry Barnett.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; What happened?: Cleveland outscored its opponents, 101-63, in
the first inning during the regular season. In 10 post-season
games, the Indians were outscored, 17-3, in the first inning. &QL; 
EXTRA BASES &QL; 
Because San Diego has advanced to the World Series, the Colorado
Rockies will receive an additional player from the Padres in
exchange for pinch-hitter  &UR; John Vander Wal, who helped the Padres
quite nicely down the stretch and in the postseason.
</P>
<P>
   Cleveland was attempting to become the first club since the
1922-'23 New York Giants to oust the New York Yankees in
consecutive postseasons. The Giants did it to the Yankees in the
first two of their record 35 World Series appearances.
</P>
<P>
   New York Mets Manager  &UR; Bobby Valentine now trails only  &UR; Jimmy
Dykes (2,962 games),  &UR; Paul Richards (1,837) and  &UR; Jimmy
 &UR; McAleer (1,658) on the all-time list of managed games without ever
having his club finish in first place. Valentine, who moved into
fourth on the list, has managed 1,541 games for Texas and the Mets
without winning a title.
</P>
<P>
   Toronto's former Cy Young Award winner,  &UR; Pat Hentgen, received
wonderful news last week during his visit to Alabama orthopedist
 &UR; James Andrews: No surgery is needed on Hentgen's ailing right
shoulder. He will continue rehabilitating the shoulder.
</P>
<P>
   The Cincinnati Reds coaching staff will remain the same for the
1999 season with one small, but not insignificant, change.  &UR; Ken
Griffey Sr., will switch from hitting coach to bench coach,
swapping spots with  &UR; Denis Menke, who most of the hitters
gravitated toward anyway. Griffey wants to manage and this should
help him get there quicker.
</P>
<P>
   Of the 30 pitching coaches only two are non-pitchers. St. Louis'
 &UR; Dave Duncan, generally considered among the very best, has been
joined by Colorado's  &UR; Milt May, who like Duncan is a former
catcher. &QL; 
THE RUMOR MILL &QL; 
The Chicago Cubs are mulling their biggest questions of the
off-season, what to do with closer  &UR; Rod Beck and outfielder
 &UR; Henry &UR; Rodriguez. Beck has the right to refuse his option and
Rodriguez is a free agent. Both want to be Cubs in 1999.
</P>
<P>
   In an attempt to keep the sharks away, sources indicate Seattle
has made a three-year offer to reliever  &UR; Mike Timlin worth
somewhere between $9-$10 million. So far, there has been no
response from Timlin's side.
</P>
<P>
   The Mariners have apparently also made a multiyear deal offer to
former Rockies Manager  &UR; Don Baylor, who would become Seattle's
hitting coach. Baylor is also mulling offers to remain in Colorado
as a vice president or join San Francisco's coaching staff, where
he would be teamed with longtime friend  &UR; Dusty Baker.
</P>
<P>
   Expect the San Francisco Giants to have the smallest payroll in
the NL West, which is quickly becoming the closest division to the
spend-like-crazy American League East. Los Angeles could be around
$75 million with Colorado ($60 million), San Diego ($55 million)
and Arizona ($45 million) all ahead of San Francisco, which says it
will be in the $40 million range.
</P>
<P>
   It should become official within a matter of months, but
Cincinnati managing general partner  &UR; Marge Schott should be
completely out of the Reds organization soon. Schott plans to sell
her piece of the Reds and the current limited partners are expected
to snatch up her stake.
</P>
<P>
   If  &UR; Joey Amalfitano, who spent the past 18 years coaching third
base for Los Angeles, is not asked to return, he figures to retire
rather than take a job in another organization. &QL; 
Includes information from other media sources. Pedro Gomez can be
reached at 602-444-2364 or at pedro.gomez(at)pni.com via e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
