<HEADLINE>
HOW THE DAILY EXPERIENCES STUDY WAS CONDUCTED
</HEADLINE>
   (SIDEBAR to DAILYLIFE) 
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   To better understand life in our times, researchers for the
National Study of Daily Experiences called 1,500 Americans in 48
states, including 20 Arizonans, and asked them to talk about their
day.
</P>
<P>
   The participants were paid a token $20 each to do interviews on
eight consecutive evenings.
</P>
<P>
   Previous research on daily stress has relied on small samples of
subjects who kept daily diaries.
</P>
<P>
   The telephone surveys were designed to last 10 minutes, but they
often lasted longer because people had so much to say and wanted to
talk.
</P>
<P>
   Participants were asked about stressful events, feelings and
moods, achievements, health, habits, patterns of giving and
receiving help, and perceptions of daily productivity at home and
work.
</P>
<P>
   Some interview questions:
</P>
<P>
   Did you have an argument or disagreement with anyone today?
</P>
<P>
   Did anything happen at work or home that most people would
consider stressful?
</P>
<P>
   Did anything happen to a close friend or relative that turned
out to be stressful to you?
</P>
<P>
   Did you have any health problems?
</P>
<P>
   How much time, money or emotional support did you give to others
today?
</P>
<P>
   Did you have a productive day at home? At work?
</P>
<P>
   At the end of the week, they were asked, ``In the past week, how
of the time were you sad or blue?''
</P>
<P>
   The interviewers were 20 graduate students in social work from
the University of Michigan. The interviews were conducted in 1996
and 1997, and extensive analysis was performed during 1998 by 20
University of Arizona students and researchers.
</P>
<P>
   The National Study of Daily Experiences is part of a larger
10-year study on midlife by the MacArthur Foundation Research
Network on Successful Middle Adulthood. It is backed by the
Chicago-based John D. and Catherine T. MacArthur Foundation, which
is funding a series of studies on the stages of human development.
</P>
<P>
   The MacArthur Foundation is one of the nation's 10 largest
foundations, funding research and education programs on a wide
variety of subjects. It is popularly known for its ``genius
grants.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
