<SLUG> BC-OUT-ARIZONA-BURKHART-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COOL OPENING WEEKEND BENEFITS QUAIL HUNTERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BARRY BURKHART  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - Cooler weather has made an already good quail season
more attractive to hunters.
</P>
<P>
   Hunter reports from last weekend's opening of the Mearns and
scaled quail seasons indicate generally good results.
</P>
<P>
   As predicted by Arizona Game and Fish biologists, some of the
best quail populations were found in slightly higher elevations on
either side of a line drawn from Prescott to Payson to Globe to
Safford and then to Willcox.
</P>
<P>
   Hunters found good numbers of quail in those areas, although the
populations were spotty in others.
</P>
<P>
   Good reports came from the Tonto Basin and Oracle area.
</P>
<P>
   The Kingman area or the west also produced some good reports,
and hunters shouldn't forget the lower desert.
</P>
<P>
   Hunters reported some good shooting to the north and west of
Phoenix. Those heading north should be aware that no shooting is
allowed around Lake Pleasant. Lake Pleasant Regional Park, now part
of Peoria, is a no-hunting area.
</P>
<P>
   Nearby areas, though, have good populations of quail, according
to hunter reports received by phone calls and e-mail.
</P>
<P>
   As the daytime temperatures continue to fall, hunters won't be
confined to morning and evening shooting. Quail also will be more
active during the middle of the day.
</P>
<P>
   Many of the quail are small because some were hatched into
August. Later in the season these birds will be larger, thanks to
good seed crops, and should make hunting even better.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, that won't make walking the draws and foothills
any easier for those who aren't in shape. &QL; 
Fall colors slow &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Those who drive the mountains each fall to see the fall colors,
especially the spectacular aspens, should be aware that fall is
arriving late.
</P>
<P>
   Two weekends ago, some aspens in the coldest areas had begun to
turn red, but in lower areas, huge numbers of flowers still were
blooming.
</P>
<P>
   Large quantities of precipitation last winter and spring has
kept everything lush for the time being.
</P>
<P>
   There also has been good production of acorns and pinon nuts, a
boon to wildlife.
</P>
<P>
   Black bears usually come to lower elevations to eat prickly pear
fruit at this time of year. But biologists said the food supply is
so good at higher elevations in such places as Tonto Basin that the
bears have had no need to seek prickly pears. &QL; 
Poaching in mountains &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Game and Fish officers are seeking information regarding the
poaching of two bull elk in late September just north of Williams
near Espee Road.
</P>
<P>
   Officers said one elk was shot and left. The quarters and
backstraps had been removed.
</P>
<P>
   ``Someone knows who did this, and where the meat is,'' said
officer
 &UR; Bob Birkeland. ``These are just the kinds of acts that take elk
permits away from the sportsmen.''
</P>
<P>
   A reward of up to $350 is being offered for information leading
to the arrest of those responsible. Call the Operation Game Thief
hotline at (800) 352-0700. Callers can remain anonymous and still
receive the reward.
</P>
<P>
   Game and Fish also is setting up roadblocks through October and
November in the Flagstaff area during the big-game hunts.
</P>
<P>
   The roadblocks will be established on secondary roads to check
for wildlife violations. The department hopes the blocks also act
as deterrents. &QL; 
Barry Burkhart can be reached at 602-444-8454 or at
barry.burkhart(at)pni.com via e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
