<HEADLINE>
ARIZONA FINDS ITS FOOTING AGAINST OREGON STATE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By NORM FRAUENHEIM  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   CORVALLIS, Ore. _ Arizona re-discovered an old friend Saturday.
It wasa happy re-union. A timely one, too.
</P>
<P>
   The Wildcats found some old traction after several weeks of an
aerial dance that had gone from dynamic to dangerous to
one-dimensional.
</P>
<P>
   For a while, it was fun. But gravity finally came knocking, and
the Wildcats were smart enough to heed its call. If they hadn't,
there would have been only a fall.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, the Wildcats landed firmly on their feet with a 28-7
victory over Oregon State.
</P>
<P>
   Arizona's victory came on Parker Stadium's plastic turf. But
there was nothing artificial about the way the No. 16 Wildcats (6-1
overall, 3-1 Pac-10 Conference) accomplished it.
</P>
<P>
   It was almost old-fashioned. It wasn't exactly grounded in
pre-flight, fear-of-flying fashion. With receivers Jeremy McDaniel
and Dennis Northcutt, theWildcats' roster is always engineered for
aeronautics.
</P>
<P>
   And, sure enough, both McDaniel and Northcutt figured in a
21-point victory that halted Arizona's traumatic tumble nine days
ago in the 52-28 loss to UCLA days.
</P>
<P>
   But more about them later. Probably much more. Their impact
promises to be heightened later in the season by what Arizona
displayed against the Beavers (4-3, 1-3 Pac 10).
</P>
<P>
   Believe it or not, Arizona's aerail circus has a running game.
No clowns, either. Leon Callen, Trung Canidate and Kelvin Eafon are
a three-sided package of speed, misdirection and power.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was pivotal that we establish a running game,'' said
Arizona coachDick Tomey, who before this season had been known for
a ground-first, air-maybe philosphy ``I was very concerned about
this game.''
</P>
<P>
   Tomey's worries were justified. In some rival scouting reports,
the Wildcats were being written off as a one-play act. Stop the
pass, stop them.
</P>
<P>
   But against the Beavers, Arizona had more rushing yards than
passsing, 228-to-140. It was the first time this season that the
Cats have gained more on the ground than through the air.
</P>
<P>
   ``We knew going in that running was our challenge,'' said
Arizona quarterback Keith Smith, who added that all of last
Tuesday's practice was devoted to re-establishing a ground attack.
``If we couldn't run the ball, this game and the rest of the season
might have been trouble.''
</P>
<P>
   Arizona's intent was most evident in the game's only scoring
drive of the second half. The Wildcats covered 74 yards in nine
plays with the touchdown capper a 36-yard dash by world-class
sprinter Callen, who finished with 107 yards.
</P>
<P>
   Only one play was a pass attempt _ an incompletion from Smith to
Nortcutt. For the only time in the game and the season, neither
Northcutt nor McDaniel played a promint role in an Arizona scoring
drive.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was almost strange, just standing there with Jeremy,''
Northcutt said. ``It was like: `Wow, we're scoring while me and
Dennis haven't caught a big pass.'
</P>
<P>
   ``But it was as good as it was strange. Down the line, it's
going to pay dividends for me and Jeremy. When defenses have to pay
more respect to our running game, we'll have more room to
operate.''
</P>
<P>
   Fact is, McDaniel and Northcutt operated often and everywhere
throughout the rest of the Arizona victory, which was also a result
of some fundamental defense.
</P>
<P>
   Led by linebacker Scooter Sprotte and defensive end Mike
Robertson, Arizona forced the Beavers were into four turnovers, all
fumbles.
</P>
<P>
   Early in the first quarter, Sprotte forced Beavers tailback Ken
Simonton into a fumble that was recovered by Rafell Jones.
</P>
<P>
   Arizona capitilized when the versatile McDaniel threw a block
that sprung Eafon lose for a 34 yard run. Seconds later, Eafon
flipped over Oregon State's defensive line for a 1-yard TD and
Arizona's first score of the game.
</P>
<P>
   Later in the second quarter, McDaniel baffled the Oregon State
secondary with a pattern that left him open for a 26-yard strike
from Smith. Northcutt followed with a 19-yard reception that set
the stage for another EafonTD, this time on a 4-yard run.
</P>
<P>
   Just before the half, Marcus Bell knocked the ball loose from
the graspof Beavers quarterback Terrance Bryant, who was injured in
the half's final moments. Daniel Greer recovered the fumble and
Arizona released the hounds.
</P>
<P>
   Four of Arizona's next seven plays were to Callen twice,
Canidate once and finally Eafon on a 2-yard TD.
</P>
<P>
   It was an old tactic and a new look for what the Wilcats hope is
another another victory run.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
