<HEADLINE>
STRESS SOLUTIONS MUST BE TAILORED TO THE INDIVIDUAL
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 (Sidebar to DAILYLIFE-AZR) 
 
 By MAUREEN WEST  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
PHOENIX _ On any given day, about half the people in the waiting
room of the Family Practice Center at Good Samaritan Hospital are
middle-age people with illnesses resulting from daily stress.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Some have piled too many obli gations on their lives. Others
have been overwhelmed by circumstances beyond their control.
</P>
<P>
   ``A tremendous number of mid life illnesses are a result of
punish ing work environments and unbalanced living,'' said James
MacKenzie, a psychologist and the assistant director of the
hospital's family practice residency program.
</P>
<P>
   ``These patients have headaches, backaches, problems with their
di gestive system, or they are de pressed or suffering from anxiety
or fatigue.''
</P>
<P>
   Doctors often are trained to look only for biological culprits,
rather than the stress that surrounds our lives, MacKenzie said.
</P>
<P>
   But awareness is increasing. The six family practice programs
operat ing in Valley hospitals now have mental health professionals
on staff to work with doctors in treating illnesses that may be
emotionally based.
</P>
<P>
   Dig a little deeper into com plaints from people with insomnia,
and you often find that their difficulty is not biological. They go
to bed worried sick about whether they will still have a job next
week or anxious about their kids' prob lems at school.
</P>
<P>
   Worrying about health is itself a major stress for many
midlifers _ people ages 40 to 60.
</P>
<P>
   What complicates the health-stress issue, MacKenzie said, is
that many of the factors that make us happy also cause stress, such
as family life and an active lifestyle.
</P>
<P>
   Examples from the waiting room:
</P>
<P>
   A 45-year-old woman who runs 25 miles a week recently injured
her knee and had to stop running. Stress builds each day that she
can't be on the track. Running had become her sole strategy for
boosting her daily energy and feeling youthfully fit.
</P>
<P>
   Like other energetic midlife peo ple, she is working hard to
hold back aging, MacKenzie said. Exer cise is a proven way to do
just that.
</P>
<P>
   But at some point, MacKenzie suggests, the runner may have to
acknowledge that she can't com pletely outrun aging. She may have
to blend in less strenuous forms of exercise such as swimming or
yoga.
</P>
<P>
   A 48-year-old man has problems sleeping, as well as headaches
and muscle pains. No mystery: He's works 50 hours per week at a
factory, drives clear across the Valley twice a day, co-chairs his
church's annual fund-raiser and coaches two soccer teams. Plus, he
has begun freelance writing to earn extra college money for his
kids, he dabbles in the stock market, he has begun helping his
parents more, and he is buying a new house.
</P>
<P>
   It's not surprising that some people get ills, MacKenzie said,
it's surprising they're still standing. They're up to their ears in
obliga tions and are resistant to making changes.
</P>
<P>
   Dozens of books and tapes are available to help people calm
their lives by simplifying their routines, but many of the
recommended changes may not work for most people.
</P>
<P>
   Suggestions not to go clothes shopping for six months or to give
up your car or get rid of the television set are not necessarily
forehead-slapping great ideas, ac cording to MacKenzie.
</P>
<P>
   Telling a person to relax more means nothing to someone with
serious responsibilities who may have never relaxed in his or her
life.
</P>
<P>
   A noontime fitness class might relieve tension for one person
but prove more stressful for another who dislikes group activities
or has to juggle a tough schedule just to fit it in. That person
may not have the patience for a yoga class.
</P>
<P>
   Solutions that work vary from person to person. An introvert may
need more private time. An extro vert may need something more
vigorous, such as an aerobic work out. The hardest thing, MacKenzie
said, is to find out what works for you.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MacKenzie has patients who can run multimillion-dollar
businesses yet struggle with remedying their unsatisfying, hectic
personal lives.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes he poses the miracle scenario: If you went to sleep
tonight, and if all your problems were gone in the morning, what
would your life be like? What would you do with your time? How
would you design your life?
</P>
<P>
   If you really know where you want to go, you can move slowly but
surely into that life, he said. The point is to get people to not
let today's stresses chew away at them, but to step back and
address the kind of life they really want.
</P>
<P>
   MacKenzie asks people to make a list of things they want to
change in their daily life. He then tells them to pick the one
thing they feel is most achievable, then do a couple of things
about it today or tomorrow to move in the right direction.
</P>
<P>
   And don't worry if you fall after a few steps. Like a toddler
testing new legs, you just have to keep trying, he says.
</P>
<P>
   In summary, the main way to reduce stress is to regain control
over your life.
</P>
<P>
   But MacKenzie and others agree it ain't easy. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
