<HEADLINE>
STRESS REDUCTION TOPICS
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 (budgeted with DAILYLIFE-AZR) 
 
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
Women may want to test their knowledge of stress and stress relief
and then chat with others online about it.
Visit www.womenswire.com.
<TEXT>
<P>
   The American Institute of Stress is a non-profit organization
that serves as a clearinghouse for information on all
stress-related subjects. It maintains a large library on
stress-related topics, though there is a charge for some
information on health and stress _
 &UR; www.stress.org. &QL; 
 &UR; Books &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Self-help and psychology sections of bookstores and libraries
are exploding with information, but it's hard to figure out what is
good. These books on combating stress are recommended by James
MacKenzie of Good Samaritan's family practice center:
</P>
<P>
   Changing for Good: A Revolutionary Six-Stage Program for
Overcoming Bad Habits and Moving Your Life Positively Forward. The
authors are psychologists James O. Prochaska and John C. Norcross
and Carlo DiClemente (Evonne, 1994).
</P>
<P>
   Stress Management: A Comprehensive Guide to Wellness, by Edward
Charlesworth and Ronald Nathan, has everything you may want in a
book about stress management. &QL; 
 &UR; Other advice &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Talk to your family physician if you believe you have
stress-related health problems and see if he or she has
suggestions.
</P>
<P>
   Counselors deal with everything from handling anger to surviving
a breakup to getting what you want out of life. Ask friends for
recommendations or call Community Information and Referral for
names of counseling services, 263-8856.
</P>
<P>
   The second volume of the Directory of Human Resources lists
self-help support groups in the Valley. It is available at public
libraries.
</P>
<P>
   Many churches also have support groups that may be on one topic,
such as depression, but people come in with all sorts of emotional
problems. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
