A3167 &Cx1f; tic-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-CARDS-CASSTEVENS-     10-18 0689
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-CARDS-CASSTEVENS-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CARDS COULD PARLAY RARE ROAD TRIFECTA 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID CASSTEVENS  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   EAST RUTHERFORD, N.J. - Do you remember the last time the
Cardinals beat the Giants, the Redskins and the Eagles on the road
in the same year?
</P>
<P>
   Here's a hint:
</P>
<P>
   ``All in the Family'' was the top-rated TV show.
</P>
<P>
   Nixon waved goodbye.
</P>
<P>
   Jake Plummer was born.
</P>
<P>
   If you said 1974, give yourself a high five. That glorious
autumn 24 years ago the St. Louis Cardinals defeated the three
division rivals on foreign turf.
</P>
<P>
   Now, just maybe, the Cards will do it again.
</P>
<P>
   You begin with the fact the Cardinals are the most overdue team
in sports history. Also, this year the Giants are so-so. The Eagles
are terrible; the Redskins hopeless. To quote the banner in
Veterans Stadium, where last Sunday the winless Eagles and Redskins
collided, ``May The Worst Team Lose.''
</P>
<P>
   It did.
</P>
<P>
   Since the 1970 merger, the NFC East has produced 10 Super Bowl
champions. No other division claims more than five. But the balance
of power has shifted, dramatically. Now the NFC East is the
league's weakest division.
</P>
<P>
   The Dallas Cowboys (4-2) lead the pack. Emmitt Smith is having a
big year. But a Super Bowl team? Without Troy Aikman, the Cowboys
lost to Denver, 42-23. A week ago Dallas had to come from behind,
at home, to beat winless Carolina.
</P>
<P>
   Recordwise, the 3-3 Cardinals are next.
</P>
<P>
   Then come the Giants, Eagles and Redskins, a combined 3-15. If
the Cardinals ever hit the trifecta on the road in the same season,
this could be the year.
</P>
<P>
   First up, today, New York. After beating Washington in the
opener, the Giants have lost four of five. Jim Fassel's team is
ranked last in the NFL in total offense. Last week the Giants,
playing at home, fell hopelessly behind Atlanta before Kent Graham
_ remember him? _ replaced Danny Kanell at quarterback and directed
his team to a meaningless touchdown. Even though the Giants
secondary is banged up, the Cardinals are underdogs because they
almost never win at the Meadowlands.
</P>
<P>
   In November, Vince Tobin takes his team to Washington, two weeks
after the Redskins play here.
</P>
<P>
   Washington is off to its worst start in 34 years. ``We're 0-6
and no better than our record,'' said Redskins linebacker Marvcus
Patton. The team that spent $57 million on free agents Dana
Stubblefield and Dan Wilkinson is so bad that one local newspaper
wit suggested that the only question left for embarrassed Redskins
fans is:
</P>
<P>
   Paper or plastic?
</P>
<P>
   Washington has a minus-13 turnover count, worst in the NFL. Last
week the offensive line had five false starts and allowed six
sacks. Coach Norv Turner, who should be fired, has replaced
starting quarterback Trent Green with a player from his doghouse,
Gus Frerotte.
</P>
<P>
   Frerotte is the fellow who last year gave himself a concussion
by banging his head into a padded wall.
</P>
<P>
   Turner should activate Sonny Jurgensen.
</P>
<P>
   Philadelphia has several problems, one of which is scoring. The
Eagles, who lost to the Cardinals in Tempe (17-3), are averaging
only 11.5 points.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's not a big step from 0-5 to 1-5,'' said Ray Rhodes, the
only NFC East coach who has won a playoff game. ``We have a long
way to go.''
</P>
<P>
   Yes, Ray, you do. The Eagles, who are 0-11-1 in their past 12
road games, play in San Diego on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   According to the 66,000 Eagles fans who showed up last week _ a
testimony to the magic of football in that town _ the most exciting
moment occurred at halftime when the franchise honored former
Eagles great Tommy McDonald, a recent inductee into the Pro
Football Hall of Fame.
</P>
<P>
   During the ceremony, McDonald, 64, caught a pass, flipped the
ball into the air and caught it, galloped into the end zone, turned
a somersault, chest-bumped the goal post and happily saluted the
crowd.
</P>
<P>
   When Tommy came off the field and rejoined his grand kids, Bill
Cosby turned and asked, ``What would he have done if they had given
him a car?'' &QL; 
David Casstevens can be reached at 602-444-8635 or at
david.casstevens(at)pni.com via e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-18-98 0019EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
