<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-18 00:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3168 &Cx1f; tic-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FAMILY-AZR &LR;      10-18 0659
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FAMILY-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DAILY LIFE KEEPS FAMILY'S PLATE FULL  
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 (sidebar with DAILYLIFE) 
 
 By MAUREEN WEST  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Surrounded by skinnier, younger people at the beauty salon where
she works and sees herself in the mirror all day, Connie Willford
wishes she hadn't stopped running a mile each morning.
</P>
<P>
   Connie, who turns 40 on Monday, does manage a 5:30 a.m. walk
with her sister and brother-in-law.
</P>
<P>
   But the mornings are crammed with too many tasks that pile up at
the moment when her teenage sons have to be taken to school and
work and she has to head to the Scottsdale salon, 20 miles away
from her south Phoenix home.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes she runs behind schedule, but it's not for lack of
trying. The family clocks are set a half-hour early.
</P>
<P>
   Once at work, she is constantly on edge about her performance.
Will the customer like the hairstyle? She's fairly new at
hairstyling and is still building a client base. But she loves what
she does. And cutting up with co-workers at the Vidal Sassoon salon
helps break the tension.
</P>
<P>
   Between customers, she will make some calls to ease the family's
upcoming move to a larger house down the street _ larger because
one of her parents might need to move in with them for health
reasons.
</P>
<P>
   She will work through the afternoon into the evening, wishing
she could be home when her kids get back from school.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Connie and her husband of 20 years, Jollie Willford, 55, are
parents of 15-year-old twins, Gabe and Seth, and 18-year-old Adam.
</P>
<P>
   She believes teenagers need their parents more than
grade-schoolers do. One of the twins used to call every afternoon,
if only to say that the other two boys were fighting. Recently, she
was so busy and short with him that now he doesn't bother to report
in, and she misses his voice in her day.
</P>
<P>
   She's home by 7:30, but many nights by that time, others in her
family have found their own dinner. She misses the dinner-table
conversations.
</P>
<P>
   Until three years ago she was a stay-at-home mom. The career is
nice, but she feels that each family member is living a different
life now, which saddens her.
</P>
<P>
   They don't go to movies together, like when the kids were
younger. The basketball hoop, once a neighborhood focal point,
stands unused most of the time.
</P>
<P>
   But the money from the extra career is necessary. Two more teen
drivers next year _ $2,000 extra for auto insurance. That and a
hundred other expenses.
</P>
<P>
   Jollie Willford is at work by 6:45 a.m. as a psychiatric
technician at the Arizona State Hospital. In the two decades he has
worked there, he has received a broken rib and bruised eyes. You
always have to be on the lookout, he said. He totally cuts off work
when he goes home.
</P>
<P>
   But he gets deep satisfaction from serving as a father figure
for some of the younger patients and from helping them to get hold
of their lives. He knows he has been responsible for more than a
few of them getting their lives together and moving back into
society.
</P>
<P>
   When he comes home from work, he sometimes naps on the couch to
relax. He picks up his high school boys from school and his
18-year-old working son from the warehouse _ the son he and Connie
are trying to get to enroll in community college.
</P>
<P>
   Jollie has taken on more of the household responsibilities since
Connie began her career, though he has always been the family
bookkeeper and budgeter. He misses her not being home when he gets
there. He lifts weights to shed stress and stay fit.
</P>
<P>
   Connie and Jollie, realizing they weren't seeing each other
enough, recently began ``dating'' again. On Wednesday nights they
go to a karaoke show while the boys attend a teen group at church.
</P>
<P>
   Connie says, ``I wouldn't trade my life for anything. . . . I
enjoy my kids. It's exciting to watch them grow up. Our marriage is
stronger. Going through these hard times has been good for us. We
are a family.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-18-98 0020EDT &QL; 
