<SLUG> BC-FBN-NOTEBOOK-SCHOENFELD-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PATRIOTS FIRE SALVOS AS TUNA BOWL NEARS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVE SCHOENFELD  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   They split the Tuna Bowls last year. Monday night is the rubber
match, with New York Jets Coach Bill ``Tuna'' Parcells going back
to New England to play his former team, a game being billed as
``Jihad with the Jets III.''
</P>
<P>
   Pete Carroll, who replaced Parcells as coach of the New England
Patriots, says the game will be a ``circus.''
</P>
<P>
   At least, nobody has done what Patriots defensive back Lawyer
Milloy did a year ago when he said he wouldn't mind getting a
chance to rush Parcells and knock down the coach.
</P>
<P>
   Carroll, who formerly coached the Jets, also wouldn't mind
getting a piece of the hefty coach.
</P>
<P>
   Carroll is upset with comments from Parcells in the off-season
that the Patriots overused running back Curtis Martin last season.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was the biggest crock,'' Carroll said of Parcells' remark
about Martin, who left the Patriots in the off-season to sign a
six-yer, $36 million deal with the Jets.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everything he says is a crock. You might as well make a list.
He's just full of it.''
</P>
<P>
   Martin has stayed out of the fray, but his mother, Rochella,
said she expects her son to get booed Monday night.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's going to affect Curt, but I'm not going to lie to you,''
she said. ``I'm going to be fired up.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was time to take another route, and I told him to go. I
made the decision. I'm sure it was a tossup for him.''
</P>
<P>
   Last week, Parcells talked about psyching out Patriots
quarterback Drew Bledsoe last season. ``I think it got to him a
little, but it will be much different now,'' Parcells said.
</P>
<P>
   He also praised Patriots receiver Terry Glenn, whom he once
referred to as ``she.''
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a good player,'' Parcells said of Glenn. ``No one knows
that more than I do. He's a threat.''
</P>
<P>
   Glenn was not impressed and called Parcells' remarks
``sarcastic.''
</P>
<P>
   The Jets, 2-3, come into the game off an embarrassing loss at
St. Louis.
</P>
<P>
   Parcells has benched starter Glenn Foley, 1-7 in his career as a
starter, and has gone back to Vinny Testaverde.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we don't do something soon, we're not going to be a
factor,'' Parcells said.
</P>
<P>
   Foley thinks he is being made a scapegoat.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are a lot of reasons that haven't been stated,'' Foley
said. ``There are a lot of things going on here. There are a lot of
things behind the scenes you don't know, a lot things you can't
know, things that can't be said.''
</P>
<P>
   Let the circus begin.
</P>
<P>
   ``Santa Claus is coming to town,'' Patriots cornerback Ty Law
said. ``Coach Parcells is coming back, and he's going to have his
boys ready.'' &QL; 
Savior or Satan?
</P>
<P>
   When New Orleans Saints Coach Mike Ditka claimed quarterback
Kerry Collins on waivers Wednesday, the ``New Orleans
Times-Picayune'' hailed him as the ``Next Best Hope.''
</P>
<P>
   Longtime New Orleans radio personality Buddy Diliberto described
Collins as a ``a gift from heaven.''
</P>
<P>
   Saints players weren't as excited about their new teammate, who
was viewed as quitting on the Carolina Panthers the previous week
when he reportedly told Coach Dom Capers that his heart wasn't in
it anymore, a statement Collins denies making.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nobody knows what really happened in the whole situation at
Carolina,'' Saints offensive tackle Willie Roaf said. ``Granted,
you don't leave your football team or walk out in that type of
situation. We had a coach do that a couple of years ago (Jim Mora).
I still respect Coach Mora, but you don't do that. I don't care how
bad it gets.''
</P>
<P>
   The Saints were the only one of the 30 teams to put a waiver
claim in for Collins. He becomes the fifth quarterback on their
roster.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not clairvoyant,'' Ditka said. ``Maybe we're the home of
lost souls. I don't know.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are guardian angels all over the world. They come into
your life for reason. And maybe we're going to be his guardian
angel. I hope so.'' &QL; 
Name calling
</P>
<P>
   Tampa Bay defensive tackle Warren Sapp, who plays Collins'
former team today, called Collins a ``coward'' and said Collins
``disgraced the game.''
</P>
<P>
   ``He disgraced Johnny Unitas and all the great quarterbacks who
have played the game,'' Sapp said. ``Archie Manning lived with New
Orleans through all the dismal years and came out each week and
gave his blood and guts. This guy comes out on a team and has a lot
of talent and a great coaching staff. He's the first pick in that
city's whole franchise, and he quit _ forever noted as the first
pick and the first quitter in the NFL. . . .
</P>
<P>
   ``I wouldn't be with him for all the money in the world and all
the riches and gold and diamonds, either. If I saw him walking down
the street, just the sight of him would (anger me).
</P>
<P>
   ``For him to come in and say all of a sudden he doesn't believe
in the system or believes his heart isn't in it _ where was his
heart when they were going to the NFC championship game? That is
the ultimate slap and spit in everybody's face and the organization
and football in general, because he disgraced the game.'' &QL; 
Growing up
</P>
<P>
   Former Cardinals quarterback Chris Chandler said he became a
good NFL player the day he stopped being angry about being a backup
on so many teams.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is something (former Cardinals offensive coordinator)
Jerry Rhome told me all the time, that he knew that is what I was
always fighting, and it took me a long time to get it through my
head,'' said Chandler, who has led the Atlanta Falcons to a 4-1
record.
</P>
<P>
   ``As soon as I stopped trying to prove anything, right or wrong,
to anybody, and just try to have fun playing the game and play the
game for the game's sake, I was able to concentrate a lot more and
play better. But I fought that for a lot of years. I was a victim
of circumstances, but I let it affect me in a negative way, and I
didn't handle it right.'' &QL; 
Quick kicks
</P>
<P>
   Syndicated TV talk-show host Regis Philbin picked the Vikings
(5-0) in the preseason to reach the Super Bowl. ``I had my eye on
the Vikings when they added Randy Moss,'' Philbin said of the
rookie wide receiver. ``I said, ``That could be it _ three great
wide receivers, two great quarterbacks, a great running back.' What
else does a team need?''
</P>
<P>
   Collins' Carolina jersey cost $200 at a Phoenix sports apparel
store before he was released. It was on sale for $35 last
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Former Miami Coach Don Shula, the last coach of an unbeaten
team, thinks the Broncos (6-0) could duplicate his feat. ``I think
the Broncos have a chance to run the table,'' Shula said. ``The
thing that (Coach Mike) Shanahan does so well, offensively, is that
he's always coming after you and utilizing that great talent he's
got. And they have enough talent to do it because of that running
back (Terrell Davis). He's made them a different team now.'' &QL; 
Includes information from other media sources. Steve Schoenfeld can
be reached at 602-444-8334 or at steve.schoenfeld(at)pni.com via
e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
