<SLUG> BC-FBN-CARDS-BROWN-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TRADING PLACES: EERIE SIMILARITIES FOR BACKUP QBS  
 BROWN, GRAHAM KNOW OPPONENT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By LEE SHAPPELL  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   EAST RUTHERFORD, N.J. _ It evokes images of the old Mad Magazine
Spy vs. Spy cartoons.
</P>
<P>
   Dave Brown, the Cardinals backup quarterback, used to be the New
York Giants starter until an injury opened the door last year for a
young quarterback (Danny Kanell) that the Giants organization
really wanted to play anyway.
</P>
<P>
   Kent Graham, the Giants backup quarterback, used to be the
Cardinals starter until an injury opened the door last year for a
young quarterback (Jake Plummer) that the Cardinals organization
really wanted to play, anyway.
</P>
<P>
   The Cardinals visit the Giants today. Brown and Graham are
saying nice things about each other and their former teams. But
imagine the counter intelligence that must have taken place this
week in their respective film rooms.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know that last year Kent was telling the defensive backs the
different audibles in Jim's (Giants Coach Jim Fassel) system,''
Brown said. ``I'm staying away from that. These guys on our defense
are playing so well right now why should I mess them up?
</P>
<P>
   ``But the wind in Giants Stadium certainly is something passed
down from every Giants quarterback. Phil Simms taught me, I told
Danny. I can tell Jake where the danger spots are in that stadium
and where not to throw it. One big thing, if you're smart about it,
is you can really play field position football. That's why they win
so many games there, because they really work the field.''
</P>
<P>
   Brown and Graham had been Giants teammates until Graham, tired
of being Brown's backup, came to Arizona in 1996. They faced each
other as starters that season in the Meadowlands, but it was
short-lived.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were supposed to have this big duel, but I got hurt in the
second series of the game and Kent got hurt in about the fourth
series,'' Brown said.
</P>
<P>
   Graham said they remain friends although ``we really haven't
talked that much because I don't have his phone number. But I think
our relationship is still real good.''
</P>
<P>
   Graham started the first six games for the Cardinals last season
_ until he was knocked out by the Giants. Stoney Case was the
starter the following week. Case was relieved by Plummer. And the
rest is history.
</P>
<P>
   As was Graham.
</P>
<P>
   Brown started the first five games for the Giants last season
until sidelined by a pectoral muscle strain _ the week the Giants
and their last-place offense came to Arizona. There, under the
direction of second year quarterback Kanell, they dominated the
Cardinals. And the rest is history.
</P>
<P>
   As was Brown.
</P>
<P>
   As free agents, Graham and Brown exchanged addresses during the
off season.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought Vince (Tobin, Cardinals coach) did make an effort to
get me back,'' Graham said. ``But they wanted Jake to play, no
matter what. Jake had some real good games last year. I was caught
between a rock and a hard spot.''
</P>
<P>
   Fassel said the moves were best for both.
</P>
<P>
   ``I like Dave, I have a hell of a lot of respect for him,''
Fassel said. ``But when he was playing before he got hurt we
weren't playing very good as a team. As hard as it is, the best
thing for Dave was to go to a new city, get out from underneath
that, and revive his career. It's the same thing for Kent.''
</P>
<P>
   Brown has yet to take a snap with the Cardinals even though
Plummer has struggled. Kanell went belly up against Atlanta last
week so Fassel brought in Graham. Fassel quickly reaffirmed that
Kanell will start today.
</P>
<P>
   Graham was in a struggling offense with the Cardinals last year,
as well.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's a big question as far as how to go into that,'' Graham
said. ``Our problems here are different. For the most part guys
know what they're supposed to be doing. We've just got to execute.
They're booing us here and there. That's the way it's been in New
York as long as I've been around.''
</P>
<P>
   Brown doesn't miss that.
</P>
<P>
   ``Giants fans expect and demand their team to play well,'' Brown
said. ``If it doesn't they're going to tell them about it. That's
one of the tough things about playing for that team. But those are
guys I played with for six years, guys I admire, guys I'm good
friends with. If it somehow comes down to Kent playing for them and
me playing for us, I think that's something we would both really
enjoy.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-18-98 0023EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
