r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-CARDS-RICE-RUN-AZ     10-18 0822
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-CARDS-RICE-RUN-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RICE MOTIVATED TO STOP GIANTS THIS TIME AROUND  
 FASSEL'S TEAM RAN AT HIM IN '97 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By LEE SHAPPELL  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   EAST RUTHERFORD, N.J. _ Maybe Jim Fassel deep inside knew he
could run at Simeon Rice, maybe he didn't.
</P>
<P>
   The bottom line is that Fassel's New York Giants did it
successfully last season. Twice.
</P>
<P>
   By Rice's own account, he did not have a banner year. He came in
with lofty expectations after his selection as NFL Defensive Rookie
of the Year in 1996. It started with elevation sickness that sapped
his strength. It was compounded by a shoulder injury that limited
his moves, and thus his effectiveness.
</P>
<P>
   The team dropped a succession of close early games and started
1-4. Yet only one foe had rushed for more than 100 yards against
it.
</P>
<P>
   Then Fassel and the Giants came to town, and Rice, playing
defensive right end, became a blocking dummy. The Giants' offense
was dead last in the NFL, but it rushed 46 times for 236 yards _
most of them directly toward Rice _ and cruised to a 27-13 win.
</P>
<P>
   That was the week the defense let go. And, some said, it was the
week that Rice was exposed as a questionable run-stopper. As the
season wore on, Tennessee, Pittsburgh, and the Giants again (40
rushes, 201 yards in a 19-10 win in the rematch in the Meadowlands)
enjoyed success running to Rice's side.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think a lot of things went into us running to our left more
than our right,'' Fassel said. ``Trust me, it wasn't because Simeon
was over there. It was our match-ups and where we were playing
better ourselves. I get more involved in what we're doing good.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet the perception was that perhaps Rice had been overrated as a
rookie. That's not the sort of thing that sits well with a
competitor, which Rice has come back this season and shown himself
to be.
</P>
<P>
   Were foes running at him?
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know,'' Rice said. ``I do know that when it gets bad
for a person it can have a snowball effect. It's not like a
situation that heals itself quickly.''
</P>
<P>
   Rice is highly motivated to prove that he was not a ``one-hit
wonder'' who hauled in those rookie accolades two seasons back.
</P>
<P>
   He has supported his claim with 20 tackles, three sacks, eight
quarterback pressures, three pass deflections, and two fumble
recoveries to help the Cardinals rally from an 0-2 start to 3-3
going into their visit to the Giants (2-4) today.
</P>
<P>
   The Cardinals defensive line is becoming dominating with rookie
left end Andre Wadsworth playing like the third pick in the draft,
left tackle Eric Swann performing like a Pro Bowler again, right
tackle Mark Smith maturing into the tackles leader of the group,
and a healthier, stronger Rice redeeming himself. They're third in
the NFC in total defense and they lead the NFL with 19 takeaways.
</P>
<P>
   The Cardinals again catch the Giants when their offense down.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's one thing to say you're going to run to your left, but if
our left tackle isn't playing good, it doesn't make any sense to
run to our left,'' Fassel said. ``Last year, Roman (Oben, Giants
left tackle) was playing good. Right now, I don't know where we're
playing good so I don't know which way to go.
</P>
<P>
   ``Each week you try to get a scheme that combines where we're
playing well and where we can attack either by formation or
direction. Right now, that's kind of difficult to figure out for
us.''
</P>
<P>
   Cardinals Coach Vince Tobin, having been burned by his former
offensive coordinator twice last year, is skeptical of Fassel's
praise.
</P>
<P>
   ``I find when they're getting ready to play you that the
opponent tries to set you up,'' Tobin said. ``They throw a lot of
smoke at you, make you think you're better than you are, and in
their own reality they think they're going to be able to come out
and whip you pretty good. I don't worry too much when people say
good things. That usually means they're going to attack a certain
area.
</P>
<P>
   ``When an offensive coach schemes, he is trying to utilize his
strengths but also go at what he perceives is the weakness of the
other team. In Jim's case last year, it was probably both. The
Giants dominated both games on the line of scrimmage last year. I'm
sure they're going to try it again.''
</P>
<P>
   This time, Rice is determined to show he belongs on the field
against Fassel's offense.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now, I'm good,'' Rice said. ``I have a host of guys around me
playing really well. It's all good for me. It's one of those
situations where each individual is taking care of his
responsibilities and making it better for everybody.
</P>
<P>
   ``Things are going well. We feed off each other. Things are
happening for us, building for us. Individuals are getting better.
Our defense as a whole is getting better, becoming more dominating.
But you've got to prove that every time you go out. I look forward
to going out this week and proving my competing edge and nature.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-18-98 0023EDT &QL; 
