r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBC-ASU-ACADEMICS-AZR     10-18 0561
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-ASU-ACADEMICS-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ASU PUTS NEW SPIN ON ACADEMIC ASSISTANCE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By PAOLA BOIVIN  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   TEMPE, ARIZ. - In an effort to prevent more academic casualties,
Arizona State's athletic department has shifted the emphasis of its
Academic Services program to personal responsibility.
</P>
<P>
   ``The biggest thing that's under construction is to let all
student-athletes understand we're an assist, but we're not going to
make the slam dunk for them,'' said Betsy Mosher, ASU's senior
associate athletic director for administration and compliance.
</P>
<P>
   Three ASU seniors _ tailback Marlon Farlow, wide receiver Ricky
Boyer and linebacker Larry Johnson _ were declared academically
ineligible before the start of the 1998 season. The administration
has acknowledged that retention has been a problem in recent years
and said it is taking steps to correct it.
</P>
<P>
   ``We haven't had a bad system, but their whole assignment was to
keep kids eligible,'' Mosher said. ``Now our assignment is to give
the kids the greatest experience and for it to culminate with
graduation. If you're going to go pro, we want to you be as close
to graduation as possible.
</P>
<P>
   ``The other end of it is our student-athletes have to play a
role in that.''
</P>
<P>
   The program's face lift, as well as tougher university admission
standards, could help change the perception of a program not known
for luring many athletes with strong academic backgrounds.
</P>
<P>
   This was the first year incoming students were required to have
16 high school core class credits based on standards set by the
Arizona Board of Regents four years ago. The NCAA requires only 13.
ASU previously asked for 11.
</P>
<P>
   While the decision may prove to weed out more at-risk students,
it could make recruiting more of a challenge.
</P>
<P>
   ``You hear about other schools using that as a recruiting tool:
`You can't get in there, but you can get in here,' '' said Tim
Desch, ASU's director of admissions.
</P>
<P>
   Additionally, the Pac-10 has limited this season the number of
partial qualifiers an institution can take to four and an
individual sport can take to one.
</P>
<P>
   A partial qualifier is an athlete who qualifies in only one area
of the NCAA's sliding scale of entrance exam score and grade-point
average.
</P>
<P>
   Partial qualifiers currently on ASU's roster include cornerbacks
J'Juan Cherry and Courtney Hysaw, linebacker Terrelle Smith and
defensive tackle Che' Britton.
</P>
<P>
   ASU has always provided academic assistance for its athletes,
including the use of tutors, counselors and computers. But the
focus, Mosher said, has changed from keeping athletes eligible to
making progress toward graduation and taking responsibility.
</P>
<P>
   ASU recently put in place a ``freshman-sophomore team'' that
will help underclassmen understand the concept. A graduation team
also is expected to be in place next year.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not that the services aren't here,'' Mosher said. ``It's
that we've tried to put a different spin on those services.''
</P>
<P>
   Johnson, who has visited football practice to encourage
teammates not to follow his path, is testament the new spin may be
needed.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just want to help the young guys because that's something I
didn't have,'' he said. ``I didn't have someone to say to me, `This
is what you've got to look forward to. Be ready.' '' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
