<HEADER>
A3198 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBC-BOSTONCOLLEGE-SYR     10-18 0816
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-BOSTONCOLLEGE-SYRACUSE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MCNABB SHOOTS DOWN EAGLES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL VEGA  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; BOSTON _ For a fleeting moment, there was a spark. A smidgen
of hope. After Boston College suffered a total flameout in the
first half of Saturday's 42-25 loss against a red-hot Syracuse team
and its white-hot quarterback, Donovan McNabb, BC wide receiver
Anthony DiCosmo provided a glimmer when he caught a 32-yard
touchdown pass from quarterback Scott Mutryn that pulled the Eagles
within 10 points with 12:51 left in the game.
</P>
<P>
   All of a sudden, it appeared this CBS-televised Big East
showdown against the No. 23 Orangemen was a contest.
</P>
<P>
   But BC had no sooner scored its second touchdown of the game _
on a two-play, blitzkrieg strike that covered 54 yards in 16
seconds _ when Kevin Johnson rendered it no contest. In 18 seconds
flat.
</P>
<P>
   That's how long it took for Johnson to settle underneath a John
Matich kickoff, break a tackle by BC redshirt freshman Nick
Blevins, pick up a picket fence of blockers, and race up the
Syracuse sideline untouched for a 97-yard return for a touchdown
that deflated BC's sideline and silenced the Alumni Stadium crowd
of 43,413.
</P>
<P>
   ``Their kicker was doing an excellent job pushing me to the
sidelines,'' said Johnson. ``But on that play they sealed them to
the inside and I was only touched by one person. I made one guy
miss. I saw a little hole and no one was going to catch me after
that.''
</P>
<P>
   The Eagles, as a result, tailspinned to a .500 record (3-3
overall, 2-2 conference) with their third consecutive loss. It was
the second defeat in a row against a Big East opponent, following a
17-0 loss to Virginia Tech 10 days ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``This game today we just came out flat, but in the second half
we were ready to go,'' said BC senior running back Mike Cloud, who
carried 25 times for 104 yards and scored on a fourth-and-goal
plunge from the 1 _ BC's first TD of the month. ``We just made
mistakes and it just got us back into that slump again. When Coz
made that nice grab in the end zone, all our spirits on the
sideline were lifted right there and we were ready to go and we
were fired up.
</P>
<P>
   ``But when they brought it back and scored on that kick return,
it took the wind right out of us.''
</P>
<P>
   McNabb, the marvelous senior quarterback who appears to have
climbed back into the Heisman Trophy race by leading Syracuse (4-2,
2-0) to back-to-back victories after a hideous 38-17 loss at North
Carolina State Oct. 1, was equally breathtaking. He left BC's
defense sucking wind from the frustrating cat-and-mouse game he
played all afternoon. He constantly dodged and weaved his way past
BC defenders while pulling all the levers, pushing all the buttons,
and turning all the knobs of Syracuse's awesome offensive machine,
which rolled up 400 yards of total offense.
</P>
<P>
   ``The difference in the game is McNabb,'' said BC coach Tom
O'Brien. ``He gets out of those situations that are unbelievable. I
don't think he misthrew a pass in the first half. I don't think he
made a mistake in the first half.''
</P>
<P>
   McNabb on his own accounted for more than half of Syracuse's
offense (220 all-purpose yards) by completing 13 of 19 passes for
182 yards and a pair of TD passes of 12 and 29 yards to Jeff Lowe,
while rushing 11 times for 38 yards. And that's not counting the
amazing 95-yard scramble he had for no gain in the fourth quarter.
</P>
<P>
   Mutryn completed 11 of 20 passes for 199 yards but was
intercepted twice by Syracuse safety Quentin Harris, including a
flutterball intended for DiCosmo that Harris returned 63 yards to
help set up McNabb's first TD pass of the game.
</P>
<P>
   Kyle McIntosh gave Syracuse a 7-0 lead in the first quarter with
his first of two touchdown runs, a 15-yarder. Then Rob Konrad, the
former St. John's Prep standout, scored on a 21-yard TD run that
made it 14-0 with 5:11 left in the period.
</P>
<P>
   Matich converted a 36-yard field goal to put BC on the board in
the second, but the Orangemen came roaring back _ following
Harris's 63-yard interception return _ to take a 21-3 lead at
halftime on McNabb's 12-yard TD pass to Lowe.
</P>
<P>
   McNabb again connected with Lowe in the third on a dazzling
29-yard strike to give Syracuse a whopping 28-3 lead before BC
finally answered with an eight-play, 75-yard march that culminated
with Cloud's fourth-and-goal TD.
</P>
<P>
   DiCosmo's 32-yard TD catch gave rise to BC hopes, but Johnson
quickly dashed them with his kickoff return. McIntosh tacked on
another TD with a 23-yard run, but BC answered when Tim Hasselbeck
connected with Derrick Crittenden on a 19-yard TD pass with 2:22
left.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not a bad football team, and we're not a good football
team,'' O'Brien said. ``But we've got to be a perfect football
team. A team like (Syracuse) puts so much stress on us, and we were
just outmanned.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
