u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBC-BOSTONCOLLEGE-ANA     10-18 0810
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-BOSTONCOLLEGE-ANALYSIS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BC'S EAGLES AT A LOSS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARK BLAUDSCHUN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; BOSTON _ No mystery this time, folks. No talk of turning
points or key plays or might have beens.
</P>
<P>
   Oh, there could have been, of course, if you want to really
break down what happened in Saturday's 42-25 Syracuse romp past
Boston College at Alumni Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   But BC coach Tom O'Brien wasn't buying any of it. ``The bottom
line is that Syracuse is too much for us, they're just too good for
us,'' O'Brien was saying after the Eagles were run over by Donovan
McNabb and Company. ``It wasn't a good matchup for us. We lose.''
</P>
<P>
   Yes, they did. For the third straight time, which makes the
Eagles 3-3. With still another October loss, the Eagles are working
on their second season without a win in the first full month of
autumn.
</P>
<P>
   The question is, where do the Eagles go from here? Quarterback
Scott Mutryn had a direct answer: ``This team goes 4-3 next week by
beating Navy.''
</P>
<P>
   The Eagles should do that, of course. But before anyone gets
overconfident, let us recall Army 49, BC 7 on a dark and dreary
October afternoon three years ago.
</P>
<P>
   The bottom line, as O'Brien might say, for the Eagles right now
is that there are no more gimmes on this schedule. Not Navy next
week and not even Pittsburgh next month, although the Panthers look
vulnerable after getting beat at home by Rutgers Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   The question that O'Brien and his staff must ponder this morning
and the rest of this week is, do they make the journey with the
same starters? After another uneven performance by Mutryn Saturday,
a quarterback controversy could be brewing.
</P>
<P>
   At first O'Brien would have none of it, offering a simple ``no''
when asked if the Eagles might go to a ``younger'' look at QB,
meaning sophomore Tim Hasselbeck.
</P>
<P>
   A few minutes later, he conceded that the staff would make
evaluations before deciding, which is only natural and logical.
</P>
<P>
   O'Brien is in a tough spot. He has to juggle the present with
the future, while mindful of the past.
</P>
<P>
   Mutryn has been a spiritual warrior for the Eagles, embracing
the responsibility that comes with being a senior quarterback.
</P>
<P>
   ``Last week (the 17-0 loss to Virginia Tech) I felt that
everything was my fault,'' said Mutryn, who Saturday threw one
marvelous touchdown pass to Anthony DiCosmo and two
not-so-marvelous interceptions.
</P>
<P>
   Saturday's loss was not all Mutryn's fault. But he was a
contributor. So was the defense, which couldn't stop McNabb. So
were the special teams, which allowed a rally-killing 97-yard
kickoff return by Kevin Johnson, which turned a 28-18 game into a
rout.
</P>
<P>
   Then again, the Eagles won their first three games against
Georgia Tech (still the highlight of the season), Rutgers, and
Temple as a team, and now they are losing as a team.
</P>
<P>
   O'Brien can fiddle at quarterback, but there is no guarantee
that Hasselbeck will be any better than Mutryn. The coach also can
make some cosmetic changes on defense. But the bottom line is that
O'Brien doesn't have a lot of moves he can make.
</P>
<P>
   He is halfway through a season that could go anywhere from 5-6
to 7-4, which is what everyone sort of figured back in August.
</P>
<P>
   O'Brien says he is putting on blinkers and focusing on next week
as the key to success. After that, he will concentrate on Miami and
then on Notre Dame and week by week for the rest of the season.
</P>
<P>
   Game by game. ``We're 3-3,'' O'Brien said. ``Now comes the
challenge. We're halfway through the season, let's go find a way to
win. Let's find a way to win a game in October.''
</P>
<P>
   After that will come the challenge of November. O'Brien knows
what he has and what he doesn't have better than anyone.
</P>
<P>
   This will be a crucial week for the Eagles as they face their
most crucial game of the season.
</P>
<P>
   O'Brien said Saturday that the Eagles are neither a good
football team nor a bad football team. He is wrong. They are both.
What is frustrating for fans is that the Eagles sometimes display
characteristics of both in the same offensive or defensive series.
</P>
<P>
   O'Brien is smart enough to understand the ``if it ain't broke
don't fix it'' theory of coaching. But that doesn't apply to his
present circumstance. Offense, defense, special teams _ there's
plenty to fix and a diminishing amount of time to do it.
</P>
<P>
   O'Brien knows that if he can't do quickly, he must then start to
change his focus from this season to next. Changing quarterbacks
would be a sign that is happening.
</P>
<P>
   The Eagles aren't at that point yet. O'Brien hopes that time
doesn't come until recruiting season in December.
</P>
<P>
   But the signs the past three games have not been good.
</P>
<P>
   The bottom line is that BC football is broken right now and Tom
O'Brien has to find a way to fix it.
</P>
<P>
   Quickly.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
