r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBC-UCLA-GAMER-LADN     10-18 0924
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-UCLA-GAMER-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CRAZY UCLA WIN LIVES UP TO HYPE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JON WILNER  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PASADENA _ Amid the plays and the plots, the twists and turns,
the mistakes and the memories, some perspective to ponder:
</P>
<P>
   In a 15-game winning streak _ in a national championship drive
in a conference as rugged as the Pac-10 _ there will be games like
this.
</P>
<P>
   There will be games when the offense sputters and the freshman
tailback limps off and the defense bends and the quarterback throws
two interceptions and the star kicker misses a game-winner from 21
yards.
</P>
<P>
   Hey, they can't all be Texas.
</P>
<P>
   ``Wow, that should be worth two wins,'' Bruins coach Bob Toledo
said Saturday after defeating Oregon 41-38 in overtime before
75,367 at the Rose Bowl. ``This was a pivotal game. We are in
control of our own destiny, and we needed to win. These kids are
very confident. They know how to win.''
</P>
<P>
   Trailing 31-24, the Bruins outscored Oregon 17-7 in the final 10
minutes of regulation and overtime _ culminating with Chris
Sailer's 24-yard field goal _ to extend the nation's longest
winning streak. In the single-elimination existence all Fiesta Bowl
contenders face, the No.2 Bruins (5-0, 3-0) have advanced to the
sixth round.
</P>
<P>
   Barely.
</P>
<P>
   ``If UCLA's the second-best team in the country,'' Ducks coach
Mike Bellotti said, ``then we're pretty damn close.''
</P>
<P>
   If anything, the game was eerily similar to UCLA-USC '96, the
double-overtime thriller with big plays and momentum shifts, a
late-game fumble, a desperation pass, an errant field goal and
relief in the home-team locker room.
</P>
<P>
   The list of Saturday's memorable plays and performances is
nearly endless, but here's the abridged version:
</P>
<P>
   Oregon tailback Reuben Droughns rushed for 172 yards but fumbled
three times.
</P>
<P>
   Bruins quarterback Cade McNown completed 9 of 13 passes for 202
yards and a touchdown !ital!after!off! vomiting late in the third
quarter.
</P>
<P>
   UCLA receiver Danny Farmer made seven catches for 161 yards and
two touchdowns, including a 60-yarder that gave the Bruins a 38-31
lead with two minutes left.
</P>
<P>
   Oregon quarterback Akili Smith threw for 221 yards and three
touchdowns. His last, to Damon Griffin, tied the game 38-38 with 22
seconds remaining.
</P>
<P>
   Sailer missed a 21-yard field goal at the end of regulation,
then made UCLA's first game-winner since 1992, when Louis Perez
beat _ you guessed it _ Oregon.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wish I could have ended it the first time,'' Sailer said.
``But I'm just glad the team gave us another chance and that the
coach and the team had the confidence in me to give me another
chance.''
</P>
<P>
   This was unlike any UCLA performance since the winning streak
began 57 weeks ago. Rather than methodically dispatching the
opposition _ converting turnovers, limiting their own mistakes,
grabbing a lead and building upon it _ the Bruins tried their best
to give it away. Of course, so did Oregon.
</P>
<P>
   UCLA jumped to a 24-7 lead and was driving for another touchdown
when the mistakes surfaced.
</P>
<P>
   First, Oregon intercepted McNown's screen pass to Brian
Poli-Dixon _ ``Bad call by the offensive coordinator,'' said Al
Borges, UCLA's offensive coordinator _ and scored with one second
left in the half.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of a 31-7 deficit, the Ducks were down 24-14 at halftime
and feeling good.
</P>
<P>
   They felt much better early in the third quarter, when
Poli-Dixon dropped a perfect touchdown pass: another opportunity
wasted.
</P>
<P>
   The Ducks responded with 17 consecutive points, grabbing a 31-24
lead early in the fourth quarter. Oregon's defense was as effective
as its offense. Stacking nine players on the line, the Ducks
contained UCLA's ground game and pressured McNown.
</P>
<P>
   ``We pounced on them, and then the offense died,'' UCLA
offensive tackle Kris Farris said. ``It was like we just turned
over and died. They were putting nine men in the box, and they
executed better than we expected. A lot of times, they knew what we
were doing.''
</P>
<P>
   Poli-Dixon regained his composure in time to snatch a 43-yard
slant from McNown midway through the fourth quarter. Two minutes
after Oregon had taken its first lead, the Bruins pulled even at
31-31.
</P>
<P>
   The Ducks were driving for the go-ahead touchdown when UCLA's
Pete Holland knocked the ball from Droughns _ his third fumble.
</P>
<P>
   Disgusted, Droughns head-butted the Oregon bench. Somewhere,
LaVale Woods cringed.
</P>
<P>
   UCLA wasted no time as McNown found Farmer for 60 yards on the
ensuing play, and the Bruins had regained the lead 38-31.
</P>
<P>
   A few minutes later, with Oregon facing a fourth-and-16,
receiver Damon Griffin corralled a deflected pass on the left
sideline for 19 yards. The Ducks had a final chance and, with 28
seconds left, Smith found Griffin for the tying touchdown.
</P>
<P>
   Twenty-two seconds remained _ plenty of time for a 6-foot-5
reserve quarterback (UCLA's Drew Bennett) to make a 53-yard catch
and set up the winning field goal. Except it wasn't the winning
field goal. Implausibly, Sailer missed wide left from 21 yards.
</P>
<P>
   While Oregon rejoiced, the Bruins stayed calm.
</P>
<P>
   ``When it went into overtime, we didn't freak out,'' said UCLA
linebacker Brenden Ayanbadejo, who had two sacks as Oregon's
overtime possession lost yardage.
</P>
<P>
   Needing only a field goal, the Bruins ran on five consecutive
plays.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a great kicker,'' Borges said. ``I don't care if he
missed or not. He's a great kicker. We played for a field goal at
the end. We were putting it on Sailer.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
