</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-SYRACUSE-MCNABB-BOS </SLUG>
  
 McNABB CAN'T BE NABBED  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PAUL HARBER  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Syracuse quarterback Donovan McNabb had a plan going
into Saturday's 42-25 Big East victory over Boston College.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was to spread it around,'' said the Heisman Trophy
candidate. ``Let everybody get in on offense.''
</P>
<P>
   And that's exactly what he did. Statistics don't tell the real
story. Both teams had 20 first downs. Both teams had similar
offensive numbers: from total plays (BC, 65-60), to net yardage
(Syracuse, 400-370).
</P>
<P>
   However, it was McNabb that broke BC's heart early.
</P>
<P>
   For example, on Syracuse's opening drive, the Eagle defenders
has seemingly caught McNabb for a sack. But he somehow eluded them
and completed a 38-yard pass to Jeff Lowe for a first down. It set
the tone for the game.
</P>
<P>
   Just ask BC coach Tom O'Brien. ``The difference in the game is
McNabb,'' he said. ``He gets out of those situations that are
unbelievable. I don't think he misthrew a pass in the first half.
The guy's a magician.''
</P>
<P>
   The second time the Orangemen had the ball, BC twice had a
chance to force a Syracuse punt. Both times McNabb came up big,
leaving BC tacklers frustrated on the Astroturf.
</P>
<P>
   First, facing third and 9 from Syracuse's 26-yard line, McNabb
again eluded BC tacklers, and this time found Darryl Daniel for a
10-yard completion. Later in the series, McNabb faced third and 6
from the BC 48, and this time found a different way to keep the
drive alive as he ran the quarterback option for a 22-yard gain.
</P>
<P>
   North Andover's Rob Konrad made McNabb's handiwork pay off when
he rumbled 21 yards for the score.
</P>
<P>
   On the third and final TD drive of the first half, Syracuse was
faced with another third and 9, this one from the BC 12. Again
McNabb found daylight and hit Lowe with a 12-yard TD pass.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jeff and I worked out together during the summer with the rest
of the receivers,'' said McNabb. ``He did a great job catching the
football. I was scrambling and I just got away from the defense,
and he knew where I was going.''
</P>
<P>
   Added coach Paul Pasqualoni, ``Jeff made a play that is a
typical Quinton Spotwood play.'' Spotwood, sidelined with a knee
injury, was one of McNabb's favorite targets.
</P>
<P>
   The McNabb-Lowe connection clicked again early in the third
quarter as the duo hooked up on a 29-yard touchdown play that
essentially put the game away, 28-3. Again it was on a third-down
(and 15) situation. And again McNabb avoided the BC rush and found
the junior wide receiver from Liverpool, N.Y.
</P>
<P>
   While McNabb's statistics were far from exceptional (13 of 19
for 182 yards), he did involve everyone in the offense.
</P>
<P>
   McNabb ran the lead on the option, gaining 38 yards on 11
carries, but also taking the hit after tossing off to Kyle McIntosh
(15 carries, 103 yards, two TDs).
</P>
<P>
   He also divvied up the receptions among seven receivers.
</P>
<P>
   ``We knew what we had to do,'' said McNabb. ``I felt confident
that if we could separate the BC defense, we would win. I figured
if we kept BC off balance, keep them on their toes, we would have a
good chance. Anytime you can go into a team's home stadium and win
is a big win.''
</P>
<P>
   Much of what McNabb accomplishes never is reflected in the
statistics.
</P>
<P>
   For example, late in the game from the BC 36, McNabb couldn't
find a receiver and was under pressure. He bounced off a couple of
BC tacklers, was chased back to his 16-yard line, and still found
daylight to get back to the line of scrimmage. It was for no gain,
but McNabb must have run for 100 yards dodging BC pursuers.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-18-98 0101EDT &QL; 
