u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SYRACUSE-MCNABB-BOS &LR;      10-18 0537
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SYRACUSE-MCNABB-BOS </SLUG>
  
 McNABB CAN'T BE NABBED  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JIM GREENIDGE  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Time and time again, the Boston College linemen had him
in their sights. And time and time again, Syracuse quarterback
Donovan McNabb escaped.
</P>
<P>
   For four quarters Saturday, McNabb teased the Eagles' defense as
he completed 13 of 19 passes for 182 yards and two touchdowns in
Syracuse's 42-25 rout of its Big East rival before 43,413 at Alumni
Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   And he had fun every step of the way.
</P>
<P>
   ``He just knows what he's going to do,'' said BC nose guard
Chris Hovan. ``You think that you're going to tackle him and then
you don't. We wanted to make sure that he didn't run the ball; we
preferred that he throw the ball.
</P>
<P>
   ``Then again, he has so many threats, so many players to choose
from to pass the ball. We had him a couple of times, and things
just broke down with the rush.''
</P>
<P>
   Added defensive end Mike Willetts, ``You become cautious. You
become somewhat afraid after a while whether you're going to be
able to make the tackle. We held him somewhat last season, but this
time he came right at us. He learned.''
</P>
<P>
   Needless to say, the duo would second the consensus opinion that
McNabb is something special. The multitalented senior can beat you
in so many ways. He connected with seven receivers Saturday, and on
the rare occasion he couldn't find one, he'd just tuck the ball
under his arm and create, gaining 38 yards on 11 carries.
</P>
<P>
   McNabb's talent was never more evident than on Syracuse's second
drive of the second half. Third and 15? No problem. McNabb just
went for the score, hitting Jeff Lowe with a 29-yard TD pass.
Willetts gave chase to McNabb, but it was to no avail.
</P>
<P>
   ``I should have had him on that play,'' Willetts said. ``There's
not a better quarterback around. He can run and he can throw. He
always seems to find a way. And we kept bringing everything in
there to get him, but we couldn't get him. During our preparation,
we wanted to keep him in the pocket, but it didn't work.''
</P>
<P>
   McNabb always got the time.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you come in at him from four different directions and
there's one opening, he seems to always find that one opening,''
Willetts said. ``He'll find your weakness. You never get to the
guy. He's just too good. And as a defensive lineman, because I'm up
front, I'm not so much worried about his passing, but I had to be
careful of his running. He hurt us, playing a flawless game. He
always seems to make that big play when he has to, taking advantage
of your mistake.''
</P>
<P>
   And McNabb didn't waste any time geting started.
</P>
<P>
   First possession: 81 yards on 10 plays in 4:50, culminating in
Kyle McIntosh's 15-yard TD run.
</P>
<P>
   Second possession: 75 yards on nine plays in 2:40, culminating
on Rob Konrad's 21-yard TD run.
</P>
<P>
   And the rout was on.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's tough to give up 14 points and getting behind that many
right away,'' Hovan said. ``You can't allow someone to come out and
do that. You've got to stop them. You bring everyone at McNabb and
then you can't tackle him. And it's not just one thing with McNabb.
No question, he's the best quarterback I've ever played against.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-18-98 0103EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
