<HEADER>
A3207 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBC-SMU-TCU-TEX     10-18 0591
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-SMU-TCU-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SMU TURNS TABLES ON TCU
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By WHIT CANNING 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DALLAS _ Recalling the events of the late fourth quarter
yesterday, SMU's Kelsey Adams figured it was all perfectly obvious.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were out there gettin' beat, going nowhere, and it was a
bad deal,'' he said, ``because we came out here to win this game
for Mr. Doak Walker.''
</P>
<P>
   So, in the manner of the late SMU legend who was honored in a
halftime ceremony, Adams saved the Mustangs in the last reel _
taking a pitchout and running 55 yards straight through TCU's
heart.
</P>
<P>
   The touchdown _ with 4:19 remaining _ lifted SMU (2-5, 2-2
Western Athletic Conference) to a 10-6 victory that knocked the
Horned Frogs (4-2, 2-1) out of a tie for the Mountain Division
lead.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were better than us on one play,'' said TCU safety Reggie
Hunt, ``but it was enough.''
</P>
<P>
   TCU coach Dennis Franchione, who had watched his team win four
games this season in similar fashion, had similar thoughts.
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, nobody knows better than us how important one play can
be,'' he said. ``This game was similar to those we won, except this
time it turned against us.
</P>
<P>
   ``A cat only has so many lives.''
</P>
<P>
   Before Adams' burst, the rainy day had been rather grim for the
Mustangs and their supporters among a soggy throng of 26,360 in the
Cotton Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   To that point, the Frogs led, 6-3, because Chris Kaylakie had
kicked two field goals while SMU's Roy Rios had missed three times
in four tries. On a day ruled by defense, the teams combined for
eight first downs and 140 yards in the first half.
</P>
<P>
   But with the Mustangs sitting at their 45, Adams, a former
Western Hills High School star, took a pitch, cut back through a
hole, ran through a tackle, veered right, and was gone.
</P>
<P>
   ``It seemed like they had overshifted to the right, away from
where I was going,'' he said. ``I saw the hole, bounced off
somebody, got a block, and I knew that was it.''
</P>
<P>
   The Frogs rolled back to the SMU 44, but the final pass from
Patrick Batteaux was intercepted by Donald Mitchell, and the
Mustangs ran out the clock.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was scrambling left and trying to throw,'' Batteaux said,
``and I just never saw the guy coming. This was not one of our
better days.''
</P>
<P>
   But for SMU's Mike Cavan, whose snake-bitten troops had lost
twice in overtime and again by five points at Wyoming last week,
the day was beautiful.
</P>
<P>
   ``God, we needed this,'' he said. ``We've been through so much,
and it just seemed like it would never end. But we stuck together,
and the thing I can say about these guys is they never gave up.
</P>
<P>
   ``And Kelsey just made a great run and did it for us.''
</P>
<P>
   So the Mustangs, who were knocked out of a bowl possibility last
year by an 0-10 TCU team, got some measure of revenge.
</P>
<P>
   Both offenses struggled most of the day, with linebackers Joseph
Phipps of TCU and Jason Simonton of SMU delivering several
drive-stopping hits.
</P>
<P>
   The Frogs broke out of a 3-3 tie on a third-quarter drive fueled
by Basil Mitchell's 65-yard run to the SMU 22, where Donald
Mitchell made a saving tackle. The drive stalled at the SMU 5, and
Kaylakie kicked a field goal.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought I was gone,'' Mitchell said, ``but I just didn't get
it done.''
</P>
<P>
   Noting that his team is 2-2 in league play, Cavan said, ``This
gives us a lift and puts us back in it, and that's the way we'll
approach things.''
</P>
<P>
   As for TCU, Phipps said, ``This creates an obstacle for us. It
will be interesting to see how we respond.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
