<HEADER>
A3208 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBC-BARNHOUSE-COLUMN-     10-18 0732
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-BARNHOUSE-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FROGS MAKE LONG WALK TO THE EDGE WITH LOSS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By WENDELL BARNHOUSE 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DALLAS _ Losses mean long walks. The worse the loss, the longer
the walk.
</P>
<P>
   SMU 10, TCU 6 was a bad loss for the Horned Frogs. Forget the
Oklahoma game that slipped away. Yesterday's bolt-out-of-the-blue
defeat was a Western Athletic Conference loss to a longtime,
down-the-road rival. It only counts as one loss, but it was a
doubleheader of a defeat.
</P>
<P>
   TCU came within five minutes of a 5-1 start. The Frogs came
within five minutes of overcoming an offensive blackout. TCU's
defense came within one play of winning the game.
</P>
<P>
   That's what made it a sad stroll. TCU coach Dennis Franchione
climbed the Cotton Bowl ramp to the Frogs' locker room, holding
hands with his wife, Kim. She looked dejected. Franchione's head
was down as he slowly trudged along with his silent team.
</P>
<P>
   The victories that get away cause the most pain, the most
sleepless nights, the most doubt.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sure, they're disappointed they lost,'' Franchione] said after
talking to his team. ``They're supposed to be. I told 'em that it's
OK to hurt. If they didn't care, it wouldn't hurt.''
</P>
<P>
   When SMU's Roy Rios missed a 42-yard field-goal attempt with
7:09 remaining, it appeared that TCU would have just enough, would
find another way to win again. Franchione, though, intuitively knew
that his team's 6-3 lead was tenuous.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was just like the other games, it's been the same every
week,'' he said. ``They've all been tight and come down to the
fourth quarter.''
</P>
<P>
   On SMU's next possession, it took the Mustangs two plays to get
the game's only touchdown. So what happened on Kelsey Adams'
55-yard scoring run?
</P>
<P>
   ``It was an `iso' play,'' TCU defensive coordinator Gary
Patterson said. ``They started strong and brought the fullback
weak. He bounced it outside, we didn't get off the block, we missed
a tackle and he outran us.''
</P>
<P>
   Simple translation: SMU made the play, TCU didn't. ``You gotta
make plays,'' said Patterson, who took full responsibility for
Adams' run.
</P>
<P>
   For much of the gloomy afternoon, TCU's defense made the plays
it had been making all season. A Russell Gary blitz sack, a Shawn
Worthen tackle for loss, a pass defensed by Kendrick Patterson. The
Frogs frustrated the Mustangs, who missed three field-goals
attempts.
</P>
<P>
   But there is a fatal flaw in this TCU team. It can't move the
ball through the air. And that's not a criticism of quarterback
Patrick Batteaux, whose on-the-job training continues.
</P>
<P>
   SMU knew TCU was going to pass only when desperate. Mustangs
coach Mike Cavan admitted it. His team stacked the line of
scrimmage hoping to stop the Frogs' running game. Other than a
65-yard scamper off a draw play by Basil Mitchell, SMU's strategy
was successful.
</P>
<P>
   TCU rushed for only 146 yards and had an anemic 185 yards of
total offense. Batteaux completed seven of 14 passes for only 39
yards. His longest completion was a 20-yarder to Royce Huffman on
the Frogs' final series that ended with SMU's second interception
of Batteaux.
</P>
<P>
   Clearly, the Frogs are a one-dimensional team. TCU is averaging
82.8 yards passing per game. Its next touchdown pass will be its
first.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know how much more we can do about it,'' Franchione
said of his team's passing attack. ``We work on it very hard. I
can't invent certain things, can't invent an arm. We know we've got
some limitations, but the fact we didn't run the ball very well
today was our biggest flaw.''
</P>
<P>
   TCU, in winning four of its first five games, had been playing
on the edge. Exhibit A is the fact the team has survived
offensively without a valid passer. The question Franchione must
answer is this: Will this loss push his fragile team over the edge?
</P>
<P>
   ``Being around this football team, I think we're going to
respond the right way,'' linebacker Joseph Phipps said. ``We're not
quitters. We've got our minds set to play hard every game. I think
we're stronger mentally than last year. It takes mental toughness
to come back from a game like this.''
</P>
<P>
   Last year's TCU team would have called it a season after the
Oklahoma loss. This year's team has exhibited considerable mental
toughness. Franchione pulled the Frogs back from the edge after
losing to Oklahoma. He'll need a repeat performance this week.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
