<SLUG> BC-FBC-TEXAS-A&AMP;M-BAYLOR-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BEARS BAFFLED BY AGGIE TRICKS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MIKE JONES 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WACO, Texas _ Texas A&AMP;M coach R.C. Slocum, one of the great
sideline stone faces in college football, actually cracked an
expansive smile last night at Floyd Casey Stadium as he watched the
final seconds expire on a 35-14 victory against Baylor.
</P>
<P>
   And why not? The 10th-ranked Aggies (5-1, 3-0 Big 12) not only
artfully dodged what many perceived to be an upset bullet aimed
straight between their eyes after last week's upset of then-No. 2
Nebraska. They also caught the projectile between their teeth and
spat it harmlessly to the ground.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was really concerned about coming up here and playing this
game,'' Slocum confessed.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone thought we'd have a letdown,'' said A&AMP;M quarterback
Randy McCown, who had a 2-yard touchdown run. ``But the guys came
back focused and intense. That says a lot about the maturity of our
team.''
</P>
<P>
   This was not the Aggies' normal day at the offensive office,
however, as they cracked the 28-point glass ceiling for the first
time this season.
</P>
<P>
   ``We pulled out some stops,'' McCown said. ``We've been saving
them for the right moment. The coaches thought this was the right
moment, and they worked.''
</P>
<P>
   The Aggies turned in a business-as-usual first half and led
14-0. They then shockingly shed their three-piece suits for
Hawaiian shirts and baggy shorts. A&AMP;M scored second-half touchdowns
on a 61-yard reverse by wide receiver Chris Taylor, on a 17-yard
halfback pass from Sirr Parker to tight end Derrick Spiller and on
a 3-yard run by fullback Ja'Mar Toombs three plays after a fake
punt with less than two minutes to play.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those plays were all a credit to Baylor,'' Slocum said. ``We
had enough respect for them and how they had played that we knew we
couldn't just line up and hammer them. So we put in a few
wrinkles.''
</P>
<P>
   Bears coach Dave Roberts said, ``A&AMP;M is an excellent football
team. They are hard to defend and stop. They were more physical. I
think the best team won, but I'm proud of our team.''
</P>
<P>
   Quarterback Odell James came off the bench to spark the Bears to
a pair of second-half touchdowns, but Baylor never closed the
two-touchdown halftime gap.
</P>
<P>
   Taylor's 61-yard sprint broke the second-half ice. The play was
set up by Dante Hall's gains off the sweep. Hall carried 17 times
for 137 yards _ his third consecutive 100-yard game _ and scored on
a 38-yard run in the first quarter.
</P>
<P>
   On the reverse, Hall took a toss right and handed to Taylor
coming back the other way.
</P>
<P>
   ``Dante running the sweep gets the defense going the wrong way,
and here I come,'' said Taylor, who has 4.31-second speed in the
40-yard dash. ``Dante helped set that up. He gave me a good
handoff, \Rguard\S Cameron Spikes threw a great block, and then it
was just me and the last guy. I beat him to the end zone.''
</P>
<P>
   James rallied the Bears for a 72-yard scoring drive, but A&AMP;M
answered with an 80-yard march that ended with Parker's dead-on
toss to a wide-open Spiller. James hit Morris Anderson on a 29-yard
scoring play with 4:24 to play. A&AMP;M moved with the kickoff from its
30 to a fourth-and-six at its 45 _ and lined up to punt.
</P>
<P>
   But Shane Lechler pulled the double-cross, hitting safety Rich
Coady for 29 yards. Toombs gained 5, then 18 and then bull-rushed
into the end zone with 40 seconds left.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told coach Roberts we were not even thinking about scoring
on \Rthe fake\S,'' Slocum said. ``I just wanted to make a first
down because \Rthe defense\S was gassed, they had just taken the
ball right down the field, and there was enough time left that I
didn't want to get into a shootout deal. Then Ja'mar made the big
run and we ended up scoring.''
</P>
<P>
   Cause enough to break precedent.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
