r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBC-STARS-BLACKHAWKS-     10-18 0745
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-STARS-BLACKHAWKS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STARS STUMBLE ON ROAD
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MIKE HEIKA 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHICAGO _ On a night when irony hung thick at the United Center,
Alexei Zhamnov's play was simply poetic.
</P>
<P>
   Zhamnov, who has struggled in his two seasons with the Chicago
Blackhawks and quickly was finding himself under the watchful eye
of new coach Dirk Graham, turned last night's game with the shift
of his life and helped the Blackhawks to a 4-3 victory against the
Stars.
</P>
<P>
   The loss was the first of the season for the Stars (2-1-1),
stopped their six-game unbeaten streak against the Blackhawks,
handed goalie Ed Belfour his first loss against his former team,
featured 36 shots by an opponent and _ quite possibly the greatest
irony _ was created by lackadaisical play on the Stars' part.
</P>
<P>
   ``They outworked us; there's no other way to say it,''
defenseman Craig Ludwig said. ``They outworked us all over the ice,
and especially in our own zone.''
</P>
<P>
   That was never more apparent than on the Zhamnov play. With the
Stars leading 3-1 and five minutes remaining in the second period,
the typically soft Zhamnov hustled to drag down Stars winger Mike
Keane on what appeared to be a sure goal and a 4-1 lead.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought it was a penalty,'' Keane said of his foiled shot at
an open net.
</P>
<P>
   But no whistle was blown, and Zhamnov scrambled to his feet to
get to the offensive end of the ice, where he ended up slapping in
a rebound goal that ignited his team.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had total control of the game,'' Stars coach Ken Hitchcock
said. ``But we were very casual with our play. And once Chicago
sniffed it out, they really went after us.''
</P>
<P>
   The Stars were outshot 36-29, were outdrawn in the faceoff
circle, 41-38, were outhit 27-15, and seemed to shy away from the
physical play the Blackhawks wanted to dish out.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even when we were up 3-1, I still felt we were being
outplayed,'' Stars defenseman Derian Hatcher said. ``We just did a
lot of things that we don't usually do as a team. Even defensively,
we were running around in our end _ and we never do that.''
</P>
<P>
   The Stars were yielding an average of 21.3 shots per game this
season and led the NHL last season giving up 23 shots a game. They
gave up 16 in the second period and 13 in the third to a Blackhawks
team that had been emotionally challenged by Graham before the
game.
</P>
<P>
   The Stars started the game perfectly by preying on the
Blackhawks' tendency to be overaggressive. Handed three power-play
opportunities in the first period, the Stars scored on two to take
a 2-0 lead. Darryl Sydor flicked a wrister through a Jere Lehtinen
screen for the first goal, and Lehtinen then put in an easy tap-in
off a Brett Hull rebound.
</P>
<P>
   At that time, the Stars looked like the team that led the NHL in
road points last season. Even after Hatcher took a hooking call
trying to stop the speedy Zhamnov and Zhamnov then set up Tony
Amonte for a five-on-three goal to draw within 2-1, the Stars
simply grabbed the two-goal cushion back on another power-play
goal.
</P>
<P>
   Hull got his first goal as a Stars player when he slam-dunked a
rebound for his third point of the game (a goal and two assists).
But Hitchcock said after that kind of success with the man
advantage (the Stars are 7-for-27), his team looked like it was
waiting to get on the power play.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our play five-on-five is not very good; it's not near good
enough,'' he said. ``You've got to give Chicago credit; they came
after us. But we gave away two points today on the road.''
</P>
<P>
   Zhamnov helped turn the table as he drew the Blackhawks to 3-2
heading into the third period. And Chris Chelios then tied the game
with a huge blast from the top of the right circle just 23 seconds
into the third frame.
</P>
<P>
   Five minutes later, the Blackhawks were working with six men on
a delayed penalty call, and Ethan Moreau chipped in a rebound past
a crowd of players in front of the net. It was the fourth goal
Belfour had allowed _ twice as many as he had given up in four
previous wins against his former team.
</P>
<P>
   Even so, Belfour had a strong night. He stopped several
breakaways and gave the Stars a chance to tie in the third period.
</P>
<P>
   But a struggling Stars offense couldn't produce.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you work harder than the other team, good things happen.
And they outworked us tonight,'' Keane said. ``Usually we win by
outworking teams. Tonight, we didn't do it, and look what
happened.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
