<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RAC-PEPSI-400-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GORDON PUTS HALT TO OCTOBER SWOON
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOHN STURBIN 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTONA BEACH, Fla. _ The only elements slowing Jeff Gordon's
march to a third NASCAR Winston Cup championship are the occasional
rain shower, the occasional red flag.
</P>
<P>
   Even those distractions ultimately were not enough to keep
Gordon from his 11th victory of 1998, in the inaugural nighttime
edition of the Pepsi 400 at the Daytona International Speedway.
</P>
<P>
   The 160-lap race was reduced to a three-lap shootout after the
event was red-flagged to a stop for 36 minutes, 56 seconds because
of rain. When it resumed on lap 157, Gordon outlegged runner-up
Jeremy Mayfield and held off a last-gasp drafting dash by
pole-sitter Bobby Labonte to claim the first October victory in his
Cup career.
</P>
<P>
   With only three races remaining, Gordon took a major step toward
his second consecutive championship and third in four years before
an estimated 170,000 fans.
</P>
<P>
   Gordon began the night with a 288-point lead over runner-up Mark
Martin in the championship chase. Gordon's victory, combined with
Martin's 16th-place run, unofficially left Gordon 358 points up
heading into Phoenix International Raceway next weekend. Gordon
needs to finish only 32nd or better in the final three races to
clinch. Or, if he gains another 12 points on Martin at PIR, Gordon
will clinch next Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm certainly not seeing that happening,'' said Gordon, driver
of the No. 24 DuPont Automotive Finishes Chevrolet Monte Carlo.
``But we've got a really good car to take to Phoenix. We tested it
at Homestead (Fla). We want to go there and be a challenger to win,
like we do at Rockingham and Atlanta.''
</P>
<P>
   After Phoenix, the tour visits North Carolina Motor Speedway in
Rockingham, N.C., on Nov. 1 and concludes at Atlanta Motor Speedway
in Hampton, Ga., on Nov. 8.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just hope things don't turn around to the opposite side,''
said Gordon, who averaged 144.549 mph. ``We want to run good
whether we've got a two-point lead, whether we're two points behind
or whether we've got a 300 or 400-point lead.''
</P>
<P>
   Gordon led three times for 49 laps around the high-banked,
2.5-mile trioval, including the final 38. His margin of victory
over Labonte was 0.176 seconds.
</P>
<P>
   ``The last couple of weeks have been the best restrictor plate
engines we've ever had,'' said Gordon, who finished second to Dale
Jarrett in the Winston 500 at the 2.66-mile Talladega Superspeedway
a week ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want everyone to know this is October, baby,'' said Gordon,
who had been reminded all month that his team never had won a Cup
race in either October or November. ``Everybody said we couldn't
win in October. We said this is a July race run in October. My
hat's off to \Rcrew chief\S Ray Evernham. This thing handled like a
dream.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a big day for all of us.''
</P>
<P>
   The victory was the 40th of Gordon's career, and marked his 17th
consecutive top-five finish of the season. Gordon, 27, previously
won the 1997 Daytona 500 and the 1995 Pepsi 400, when it was run in
July. This race was scheduled to be run at night on the Fourth of
July weekend, but postponed when wildfires swept through the area.
</P>
<P>
   Following Gordon and Bobby Labonte across the finish line were
Mike Skinner, Jeremy Mayfield, Rusty Wallace, Terry Labonte, Ward
Burton, Ricky Craven, Ken Schrader and Dale Earnhardt.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jeremy and I worked very well. He tried to work with me (on
the restart) and I appreciate his help,'' Gordon said. ``I wasn't
sure we were going to be able to stay up there, especially with
Dale Jarrett, because he was strong.''
</P>
<P>
   Jarrett saw his bid for a second consecutive restrictor-plate
victory go awry when he cut a left front tire. Jarrett, driver of
the No. 88 Quality Care-Ford Credit Taurus, was running second to
Gordon on lap 148 when the problem forced him off the pace and into
the pits.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier, seven-time Cup champion Earnhardt, who won the
season-opening Daytona 500 here in February, had his chances for a
Daytona sweep dashed by a pit mishap. Earnhardt, Jarrett and Bobby
Labonte all pitted for tires and fuel on lap 97. With 63 laps
remaining, all three were making what they hoped would be their
last pit stop.
</P>
<P>
   But Earnhardt, who had entered the pits running second to
Labonte, collected a stray tire from Labonte's pit stall as he
returned to pit road. The tire struck the center of Earnhardt's
front air dam, pushing it in and upsetting the car's aerodynamics.
Earnhardt returned to pit road on several occasions to have his
crew tape and pop-rivet a replacement spoiler onto the lower front
of the No. 3 GM Goodwrench Chevy. The work dropped him to as low as
22nd on lap 125, the last car on the lead lap.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
