<SLUG> BC-BB0-REEVES-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
YANKEES SPOIL PERFECT SCRIPT FOR GWYNN
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JIM REEVES 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ It may have been the most perfectly executed
``rope-a-dope'' since Muhammad Ali suckered George Foreman with the
same strategy in the jungles of Zaire 24 years ago this month.
</P>
<P>
   San Diego's Tony Gwynn laid the trap.
</P>
<P>
   New York's David Wells supplied both the rope and the dope.
</P>
<P>
   But in this star-spangled season in which they can seemingly do
no wrong, the Yankees still found a way to win.
</P>
<P>
   The Yanks, trailing 5-2, nuked the Padres with a seven-run
seventh inning, capped by Tino Martinez's dramatic two-out grand
slam, and took an electrifying 9-6 victory in Game 1 of the 1998
World Series last night at Yankee Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   It was a sickening loss for the National League champion Padres,
who got two home runs from Greg Vaughn and Gwynn's tiebreaking
two-run homer in the fifth, had ace Kevin Brown on the mound and a
three-run lead after six innings and still couldn't put the Yankees
away.
</P>
<P>
   ``You hate to give up a 5-2 lead,'' Padres manager Bruce Bochy
said. ``This is something we're going to have to put behind us.''
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees' comeback turned what should have been the story of
the game _ Gwynn winning his mind games with Wells _ into little
more than an interesting side note, and pulled New York's burly
left-hander off the hook after he'd talked himself into a hot spot.
</P>
<P>
   It started Thursday when Wells, who had been virtually
unhittable in the postseason, did what a lot of others have done
and said way too much on Howard Stern's syndicated talk show.
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't X-rated, but, oh how Yankees' manager Joe Torre wished
he could have hit the ``dump'' button before Wells' prediction that
the Yankees would win the Series in five games had gone out over
the airways and around the world.
</P>
<P>
   It is a baseball axiom that is as old as the game itself: You
don't kick sleeping bulletin boards ... or something like that.
</P>
<P>
   ``Harumph,'' Padres pitching coach Dave Stewart growled Friday.
Or words to that effect. ``We've already beaten five pitchers
better than him in the playoffs.''
</P>
<P>
   You can debate the names _ Shane Reynolds, Randy Johnson, John
Smoltz, Tom Glavine and Greg Maddux _ but not the sentiment. Well,
maybe ``you'' can. I know Stewart too well, thank you very much.
</P>
<P>
   It was Gwynn's turn to jabber on the eve of his first Series
appearance since 1984. To any reporter who would listen _ and there
were wave after wave of them _ the Padres' 38-year-old superstar
hitter Gwynn talked of how terrible he'd been so far in the
postseason.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've got to quit trying to pull everything,'' he said, shaking
his head, ``and just take the ball to left field.''
</P>
<P>
   Was he setting Wells up?
</P>
<P>
   It's a moot point now, but it certainly looked that way when
Gwynn turned on a high fastball in the fifth, yanking it down the
right-field line and high off the Bud Light sign on the third-deck
facade.
</P>
<P>
   Gwynn's two-run homer snapped a 2-2 tie, and when Vaughn
followed with his second homer of the game, a solo shot deep into
the left-field stands, the Padres had a three-run lead, and Yankee
Stadium was virtually silent.
</P>
<P>
   That should have been it. After a 14-year absence, Gwynn returns
to Fall Classic and leads the Padres to a first-game victory. Cue
the credits. Sell the rights to the movie. Turn off the lights.
</P>
<P>
   But that's not how it works here in the Big Apple.
</P>
<P>
   This Series began against a typically Manhattan backdrop: Joe
DiMaggio, desperately ill with pneumonia in a Florida hospital;
Darryl Strawberry, home from the hospital after surgery for colon
cancer two weeks ago; owner George Steinbrenner, feuding with
baseball officials over who should sing the national anthem,
longtime Yankee standby Robert Merrill or Anthony-come-lately Tony
Bennett.
</P>
<P>
   Just your normal October ballgame at Yankee Stadium, in other
words.
</P>
<P>
   So we should have known Gwynn couldn't be the hero last night,
not in a season when the Yankees have been nothing if not magical.
</P>
<P>
   A limping Brown, who had taken a Chili Davis line drive off his
left knee in the second inning without even a flinch, had nothing
left in the seventh, giving up a one-out single to Jorge Posada and
a walk to Ricky Ledee.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was hurting more than he was letting on,'' said Bochy, who
hopes to get two more starts from Brown if the Padres can take this
Series to seven games. Bochy had no choice but to turn to his
bullpen.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees blow-torched it for seven runs, three on Chuck
Knoblauch's game-tying homer off Donne Wall and the final four on
Martinez's ``salami'' off a 3-2, two-out fastball from Mark
Langston.
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew eventually I'd get a big hit and help this team win,''
said Martinez, who had been slumping throughout the postseason.
</P>
<P>
   Just like that a game the Padres had seemingly wrapped up as
tight as a burrito was gone, and the Yankees had taken a 1-0 lead
in the Series.
</P>
<P>
   Funny, but it already seems more like 3-0.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe ``The Dope'' was right after all.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-18-98 0114EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
