<SLUG> BC-BB0-SERIES-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
YANKEES SLAM LID ON PADRES
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By T.R. SULLIVAN 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ San Diego Padres manager Bruce Bochy took heat in the
League Championship Series for using All-Star pitcher Kevin Brown
in relief. That was nothing compared to the second-guessing he'll
get for pulling Brown out as the starter in Game 1 of the World
Series last night.
</P>
<P>
   Bochy tried to turn a 5-2 lead over to his bullpen in the
seventh inning after Brown had thrown 108 pitches. But the move
turned into disaster when the Yankees' Chuck Knoblauch tied the
score with a three-run homer off Donne Wall, and Tino Martinez hit
a grand slam off Mark Langston. The homers sparked New York to a
9-6 victory before 56,717 at Yankee Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   ``Kevin pitched well,'' Bochy said. ``He did his job. We just
couldn't hold them with our bullpen.''
</P>
<P>
   The seven-run outburst allowed the Yankees to overcome the
Padres' muscle against David Wells, who gave up two home runs to
Greg Vaughn and another to Tony Gwynn. But Wells stayed around long
enough to get the victory, his fourth in four starts this
postseason. It also made him 8-0 in the playoffs in his career.
</P>
<P>
   ``Boomer has spoiled us the way he's been pitching,'' Yankees
manager Joe Torre said. ``He had good stuff. His location was just
awesome.''
</P>
<P>
   Brown took a 5-2 lead into the seventh, but couldn't handle the
bottom of the Yankees' order. Jorge Posada, the No. 8 hitter,
dropped a one-out single into right-center and then Brown walked
hitter No. 9 Ricky Ledee.
</P>
<P>
   ``We said before the inning started if he was scuffling, we were
going to get him,'' Bochy said. ``He gave it his best shot. All
these games, the bullpen's going to play a role and you have to use
them.''
</P>
<P>
   That was the point in which Bochy decided to pull Brown even
though 108 pitches is not a high number for a starter, especially
for the ace of a staff.
</P>
<P>
   ``Any time you get a starting pitcher out of game it's a good
thing, especially when it's Kevin Brown,'' Knoblauch said.
</P>
<P>
   Bochy brought in Wall, but the moved backfired. Knoblauch jumped
on a 2-0 pitch and crushed it down the line in left for his
three-run homer that tied the score at 5-5.
</P>
<P>
   After Derek Jeter singled, Langston took over for Wall, getting
Paul O'Neill to fly out, but he walked Bernie Williams and Chili
Davis. Martinez worked the count to 2-2, then took a pitch that
Langston believed was strike three. Umpire Richie Garcia said
otherwise.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought it was down,'' Martinez said. ``He \RGarcia\S did a
great job all night being consistent.''
</P>
<P>
   Martinez, who had 123 runs batted in during the regular season,
but only one in the first two rounds of the playoffs, hit the next
pitch into the right-field seats for a grand slam.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was nice,'' Martinez said. ``I haven't been doing much and
we were still winning. I knew eventually I would come up with a big
situation and get a big hit to help us win. It's definitely a
relief.''
</P>
<P>
   The bottom of the order was also trouble for Brown when the
Yankees scored two runs in the second inning. Chili Davis lined a
ball off Brown's leg that went for a one-out single and Martinez
drew a one-out walk.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the ball off the shin affected him,'' Bochy said of
Brown. ``He wasn't saying anything, but I think it was there.''
</P>
<P>
   Brown struck out Scott Brosius, but walked Posada to load the
bases. Ledee then worked the count full before lining a double into
the right-field corner, giving the Yankees a 2-0 lead. Brown
escaped that inning by striking out Knoblauch.
</P>
<P>
   Brown then allowed only three singles over four scoreless
innings before running into trouble in the seventh.
</P>
<P>
   The Padres struck back quickly in the third when Vaughn smashed
an 0-2 pitch over the right-field bleachers for a two-run homer.
San Diego went ahead 5-2 in the fifth when Gwynn hit a two-run
homer to right and Vaughn followed on the next pitch with a home
run to left.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a tough one to swallow,'' Vaughn said of the loss. ``It's
very disappointing. We've got to keep fighting. We can't keep
down.''
</P>
<P>
   The Padres also got an unearned run off the Yankees in the
eighth, but Mariano Rivera pitched a scoreless ninth to close it
out.
</P>
</TEXT>
