<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BB-WORLD </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
YANKEES HAVE THE ANSWER 
</HEADLINE>
 SERIES-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By GORDON EDES  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ They could have been wearing prison stripes as easily
as pinstripes, trapped as they were in their postseason misery.
</P>
<P>
   Chuck Knoblauch didn't think. Tino Martinez didn't hit.
</P>
<P>
   But pick the right time for atonement, like Game 1 of the World
Series, and amnesia is almost certain to follow. Nothing like a
three-run homer (Knoblauch) or a grand slam (Martinez) to wipe the
slate clean.
</P>
<P>
   Put them both in the same inning, as Knoblauch and Martinez did
Saturday night in Yankee Stadium, and you're not only welcomed back
in the house, you're given the keys to the city.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees, in a seven-run seventh-inning show of power,
squashed the San Diego Padres, 9-6, before a delirious crowd of
56,712.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you try to make up in this game for every time you strike
out with the bases loaded or make an error, the pressure would pick
up so much you wouldn't even be able to walk,'' Yankees manager Joe
Torre said.
</P>
<P>
   Down, 5-2, after the Padres did some flexing of their own _ two
home runs by Greg Vaughn, one by Tony Gwynn, all off Yankees
starter David Wells _ the Yankees tied the score on Knoblauch's
three-run homer just inside the left-field foul pole off San Diego
reliever Donne Wall.
</P>
<P>
   The magnitude of that moment barely had time to register before
Martinez trumped it with a grand slam into the third deck in right
field off Padres lefthander Mark Langston.
</P>
<P>
   ``I got so excited, I had a stomach ache,'' said Chili Davis,
who had drawn a full-count walk just before Martinez buried a
3-and-2 fastball.
</P>
<P>
   And just like that, memories shut off in five boroughs.
</P>
<P>
   Knoblauch chose to argue with an umpire rather than retrieve a
ball in play against the Indians in the ALCS?
</P>
<P>
   Martinez had a .135 (7 for 52) average with one RBI in 16
previous games in the ALCS and World Series, and Torre was hinting
at using the creaky Davis at first base in San Diego?
</P>
<P>
   Fuhgeddaboudit.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had a little smile on my face,'' Knoblauch said, ``because
Tino and I have been trying to pump each other up. I was probably
more excited when he hit his home run.''
</P>
<P>
   That sentiment traveled down a two-way street Saturday night,
according to Martinez.
</P>
<P>
   ``We know we've been struggling,'' Martinez said. ``When he hit
his home run, I ran out of the dugout as fast as I could. I said to
him, `It's behind you. Now you're going to have a great
postseason.'''
</P>
<P>
   The Yankee eruption came after Padres ace Kevin Brown departed
with one out in the seventh and runners on first and second
following a single by Jorge Posada and a four-pitch walk to Ricky
Ledee.
</P>
<P>
   Brown, who had given up a two-run double to Ledee in the second
when the Yankees seized a 2-0 lead, admitted afterward that he was
suffering from a sinus infection.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, when he lost two games in the World Series to the
Indians while pitching for Florida, Brown had a viral infection
that left him weak.
</P>
<P>
   This latest illness raises questions about his ability to pitch
three times in this Series, if it goes the full seven games.
</P>
<P>
   ``What are the chances of going through a whole season feeling
good without coming down with something?'' said Brown.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've thrown three World Series games, and I haven't been
healthy yet. It would be nice to see how that feels.''
</P>
<P>
   Wall, who relieved Brown, threw his first pitch about 55 feet.
Knoblauch had to duck from his second.
</P>
<P>
   The third was redirected toward the 318-foot sign in left, where
Padres left fielder Vaughn scaled the wall in a vain attempt to
bring Knoblauch's ball back to his side of the fence.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had a pretty good feeling when I hit it,'' Knoblauch said,
``but I got a little worried when I saw Vaughn jump up on the
wall.''
</P>
<P>
   But the high anxiety belonged exclusively to San Diego. When
Derek Jeter grounded Wall's next pitch into center field for a
single, Padres manager Bruce Bochy went to Langston. He retired the
first batter he faced, Paul O'Neill, on a fly ball, but after
throwing a wild pitch, he intentionally passed Bernie Williams,
then loaded the bases by walking Davis.
</P>
<P>
   And for the first time this October, it was Tino's time.
</P>
<P>
   ``I haven't done much,'' Martinez said. ``But we've been
winning. We got to the World Series. I knew eventually I'd come up
in a big situation and get a big hit to help the team win.''
</P>
<P>
   And so he did, and so he bounded out of the dugout to face the
crow chanting his name. Just as Knoblauch had screamed to the crowd
after crossing the plate.
</P>
<P>
   ``To have the whole place standing up, screaming, you just get
caught up in the emotion of the moment,'' Knoblauch said.
</P>
<P>
   Those are the moments that you truly wish to remember.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
