</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BB-RYAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PITCHERS' DUEL FOILED BY HEAVY ARTILLERY 
</HEADLINE>
 COLUMN-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB RYAN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Conventional Wisdom is off to a bad start in the 1998
World Series.
</P>
<P>
   CW held that Saturday night's Game 1 would be a veritable mound
classic. CW held that good hits, and perhaps even good swings,
would be as rare as palm trees on Seventh Avenue. CW held that the
Star of the Game would be either David Wells or Kevin Brown,
perhaps both.
</P>
<P>
   CW certainly did not foresee a 9-6 victory by anyone. And CW
certainly did not foresee a seven-run Yankee seventh inning
featuring home runs by Chuck Knoblauch, the leadoff man still
trying to live down a celebrated case of ALCS brain lock, and Tino
Martinez, a woeful 1998 postseason batter whom most Yankee fans had
probably wished to be manager Joe Torre's leave-out man.
</P>
<P>
   Knoblauch refused to frame his three-run tying homer off
reliever Donne Wall in terms of vindication. ``I tried to put that
play (i.e. the interference whine while the go-ahead run was
circling the bases) behind me when I stepped onto the field that
Friday night in Cleveland,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But Tino really did have something for which to apologize. The
team had been lugging him through these playoffs, and he knew it.
``I haven't done much, but we got to the World Series, and I knew
that eventually I'd get a big hit to help the team,'' he said. His
big moment came with the bases loaded and two outs in a 5-5 game
against lefty Mark Langston. First he had to survive a close 2-2
pitch that the Padres will forever maintain was strike three but
that Tino insists was ``down in the zone.''
</P>
<P>
   Common sense dictated that an agitated Langston would come in
with a fast ball, and he did. This one was up in that zone, and
Tino sent it soaring into the third deck for the winning grand
slam. That's the way to break out of a slump.
</P>
<P>
   Now, on any pregame scale of 1 to 10, the suggestion that nine
earned runs and three homers would be surrendered by the starting
duo would have been somewhere around a one-half. But that was the
case by the Yankee seventh, when Knoblauch's three-run homer off
Wall saddled Brown with two more earnies to go with the pair he had
given up in the second on a Ricky Ledee bases-loaded double.
</P>
<P>
   Wells's mortality had been firmly established by the fifth. He
first ran afoul of Greg Vaughn in the third when the left fielder
hit a two-out, two-run opposite-field homer just to the right of
the 385-foot sign. His next jolt came when Tony Gwynn smashed a
pitch off the facing of the third deck with Quilvio Veras aboard in
the fifth. When was the last time in Series history such a rotund
batter hit a homer off such a rotund pitcher as the well-rounded
Mr. Wells?
</P>
<P>
   Gwynn had nailed a first pitch. That brought up clean-up man
Vaughn, who likewise zeroed in on a first pitch, driving it deep
into the left-field seats. Vaughn had made no secret of his
animosity toward the Yankees, who had turned him back like a
bruised grapefruit when he was traded to New York last year. The
Yankee claim was simple: Vaughn had a bad shoulder. He couldn't
pass the physical. He was your basic damaged goods. It turns out he
was so damaged that all he could manage for the Padres this summer
were 50 homers and 119 runs batted in.
</P>
<P>
   At 5-2 after five, it was no longer a pitcher's duel. It was
becoming more and more ``The Kevin Brown Show.'' For after
requiring 62 pitches to get through three innings (including 30 in
the second and 20 in the third), Brown appeared to be in a proper
groove entering the seventh. He had survived a first-and-second,
one-out situation in the fifth when he retired Derek Jeter and Paul
O'Neill on successive ground balls, and he had looked especially
sharp in the 1-2-3 sixth, which included a pair of strikeouts.
</P>
<P>
   Entering the seventh, he was sitting on that 5-2 lead and had
thrown 98 pitches. But the Padres' decision already had been made.
``If he scuffled at all,'' explained manager Bruce Bochy, ``he was
coming out. He had done his job.''
</P>
<P>
   After getting Scott Brosius easily to start the seventh, he
allowed a sharp single to right by Jorge Posada. When he walked
Ledee on four pitches, Bochy called on set-up man Wall, the man he
had passed over in San Diego last week in order to bring in Brown
as a reliever. That move didn't work, and this one didn't, either.
</P>
<P>
   Wall surrendered the tying homer by Knoblauch, then a single by
Jeter before being relieved by Langston, who promptly loaded the
bases and would have been yanked had not the next batter been
Martinez.
</P>
<P>
   On any pregame scale of 1 to 10, the thought that this man, of
all people, would hit a clutch, tie-breaking, late-inning grand
slam was approximately a one-quarter. Torre wasn't making any
Turnpike Joe Morgan-style ``I had a hunch'' claims of clairvoyance,
but he did say that Tino had (finally) had a nice batting practice.
``He had soft hands, and the ball was really flying off his bat,''
Torre pointed out.
</P>
<P>
   So there it is. The Yankees are now three wins away from
finishing with a great flourish what is arguably their most
wondrous season ever. CW would say that El Duque will beat Andy
Ashby Sunday night, but CW is probably off hiding in a closet
somewhere after last night's sorry performance.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
