r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBO-SERIES-BICKLEY-AZ     10-18 0704
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-SERIES-BICKLEY-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BOCHY DESERVES THIS LOSS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By DAN BICKLEY  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   New York - In an instant, the opportunity was gone, the victory
a terrible mirage. In an instant, the neurons misfired in the
manager's brain, prompting a stroll up the stairs and a trip to the
mound.
</P>
<P>
   In an instant, the tone of the entire series swung like a wild
pendulum, as if King Kong plopped down on one side of the
teeter-totter.
</P>
<P>
   If the Padres never recover, if they turn into another chunk of
roadkill on one team's road to history, they will remember this
night. The night when the Midas touch disappeared and Bruce Bochy
finally pulled the wrong lever.
</P>
<P>
   The night he looked around at the boiling madness of Yankee
Stadium, chewed on the magnitude of a Game 1 on the road, pondered
a sticky situation that just might decide the World Series. The
night he opted for Donne Wall over Kevin Brown.
</P>
<P>
   ``We talked about it before the game,'' Bochy said. ``We said if
(Brown) struggles at all, we're going to take him out. He knew
that. He was ready to be out at that point.''
</P>
<P>
   Was he?
</P>
<P>
   Brown, owner of an amazingly resilient arm, a pitcher his
general manager called a freak of nature, had thrown 108 pitches
when his manager asked for the ball.
</P>
<P>
   Brown, the most intense competitor in baseball and a man full of
postseason pedigree, was yanked in favor of a guy who has had one
good season in the bigs.
</P>
<P>
   If I'm the manager, it's a slam dunk. I take my chances with
Brown staring down the moment, raising his game, snuffing out a
fire of his own making.
</P>
<P>
   Which is what great pitchers do.
</P>
<P>
   ``Brown had so much success in the postseason, it seemed like he
reached a point where he was unbeatable,'' the Yankees' Chili Davis
said.
</P>
<P>
   Granted, Brown planted the seeds for the disastrous seventh
inning, giving up a one-out single to Jorge Posada and walking
Ricky Ledee, the eighth and ninth hitters, respectively, in the
Yankees' lineup. Granted, Brown was suffering from a sinus
infection. Granted, he had taken a shot off the shin in the second
inning that may have limited his effectiveness.
</P>
<P>
   But before the mess started, Brown had retired six consecutive
batters, including a called strikeout of Bernie Williams and a
whiff of Tino Martinez. And on the night, he had allowed only one
hit with runners on base.
</P>
<P>
   ``Donne's been in that situation all year,'' Bochy said. ``All
year he's done a good job there. We kind of stayed with what got
you here, and we felt like Donne would get the job done.''
</P>
<P>
   Yeah, right. From a guy who spent six years in the minors before
earning his promotion. A guy making his first postseason appearance
in the Bronx zoo.
</P>
<P>
   Predictably, the Yankees seized the moment. Vilified for
brain-lauch against the Indians, Chuck Knoblauch lifted a pitch
that landed in the bleachers of forgiveness. And by the time he
rounded the bases, the pardon was official.
</P>
<P>
   Against Mark Langston, Tino Martinez lost the horns and a
growing label as playoff gag artist, crushing a grand slam that
sealed the deal.
</P>
<P>
   In an instant, Brown was gone, and so was the opportunity. Think
the sight of Wall didn't lift the Yankees' spirits?
</P>
<P>
   ``Absolutely,'' Martinez said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Anytime you get a starting pitcher out of the game, it's a
good thing,'' Knoblauch said. ``Especially when it's Kevin Brown.''
</P>
<P>
   Had the Padres held on, they could've taken control of this
affair, exposing a New York rotation that is somewhat suspect.
After all, El Duque is a rookie. David Cone's arm condition is
always a concern this time of year. Andy Pettitte was a question
mark before his father underwent triple bypass surgery on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   In an instant, it all slipped away.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think it's a wasted opportunity,'' Bochy said. ``Sure,
you hate to lose a 5-2 lead, and this is something we'll have to
put behind us. But we came out and played a good ballgame. The
seventh inning just got out of control.''
</P>
<P>
   Yes, it did. Largely due to a miscue that won't show up in the
boxscore. An error in judgment charged to the manager. &QL; 
Dan Bickley can be reached at 602-444-8253 or at
dan.bickley(at)pni.com. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
