r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBO-SERIES-GAMER-AZR &LR;      10-18 0713
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-SERIES-GAMER-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
YANKEES ROLL LUCKY 7  
 7-RUN 7TH INNING EARNS GAME 1 WIN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By PEDRO GOMEZ  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ For six innings Yankee Stadium was an unusually
somber place to be. The partisan crowd of 56,712 sat mostly stunned
as their hometown heroes fell behind by three runs to San Diego.
</P>
<P>
   Then Chuck Knoblauch, as big a goat who has ever worn the Yankee
pinstripes one week earlier, connected on a three-run home run. The
Bronx was the Bronx again, cups of beer flying through the air as
pandemonium reigned.
</P>
<P>
   Five batters later, Tino Martinez muscled a grand slam into the
right field bleachers and the Yankees were the Yankees again,
pouring it on an opponent like they had done so many times during
their record-setting season.
</P>
<P>
   From that moment on the Padres could forget about it, their
chances of snagging a lead in the World Series were essentially
over. New York wound up walloping the Padres, 9-6, on Saturday
night.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every inning we were telling ourselves keep playing the game,
keep pushing and try to get some more runs across because they're a
great team,'' said Padres left fielder Greg Vaughn, whose two home
runs were the driving force behind San Diego taking a 5-2 lead into
the seventh. ``The game's not over until the last out is made. They
came across with some big hits.''
</P>
<P>
   The moment was especially sweet for the two Yankees _ Knoblauch
and Martinez _ who each endured a personal variation of the
notorious Bronx cheers during these playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   Knoblauch was ridiculed by the New York press and fans after his
boneheaded play in the 11th inning of Game 2 in the American League
Championship Series against Cleveland.
</P>
<P>
   Knoblauch's ability to impersonate a statue while arguing a play
with an umpire as Cleveland runners, including the tie-breaking
run, circled the bases made him the object of tabloid covers and
cannon fodder for radio talk shows.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was embarrassed for him,'' Yankees right fielder Paul
O'Neill said.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, all is forgotten now.
</P>
<P>
   ``In this game there are days up and days that are down,''
Knoblauch said. ``You have to face the facts, answer the questions,
be a stand-up guy and that's all you can do.''
</P>
<P>
   Martinez has also experienced a personal hell of his own,
languishing in a postseason slump that is basically three years
old. Martinez entered the night batting .167 with one RBI this
postseason, not very different from his postseasons the previous
two years.
</P>
<P>
   There was even speculation that Martinez, who has driven in at
least 100 runs in each of the past four seasons, would be benched
when the series shifts to San Diego and National League rules will
not allow the designated hitter.
</P>
<P>
   Yankees Manager Joe Torre opened up a potential controversy when
he said he would play Chili Davis at first base rather than the
outfield if he were to start him in the field in San Diego. Torre
quickly backpedaled on the issue but said the possibility existed
if Martinez remained unproductive.
</P>
<P>
   ``I haven't done much,'' said Martinez, who hit the 17th grand
slam in World Series history and the first by a Yankee since Joe
Pepitone's in St. Louis in 1964. ``I knew eventually I'd come up in
a big situation and get a big hit to help the team win. It's
definitely a big relief.'' Of course, it wouldn't be a World Series
without an element of disagreement and the pitch before Martinez's
game-winning home run served it up. Padres reliever Mark Langston
threw a knee-high fastball that definitely could have been called a
third strike, which would have ended the inning. But home plate
umpire Richie Garcia did not ring up Martinez.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was really shocked,'' Langston said. ``It's a big game and a
big pitch. Obviously I have to be able to push that aside and
execute the next pitch. I didn't do that. It was on my mind for a
split second.''
</P>
<P>
   The Padres can kick themselves all winter over this one,
especially since Yankees starter David Wells was not on top of his
game, allowing five runs on seven hits in seven innings.
</P>
<P>
   ``They kicked my ass,'' said Wells, who is 4-0 since the
playoffs started.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, though, it was the Yankees muscle doing all the
tail-kicking. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
