<SLUG> BC-BBO-SERIES-LEDEE-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LEDEE ANSWERS THE CALL  
 SURPRISE STARTER CHARMS YANKS FANS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By PEDRO GOMEZ  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Two weeks ago, Ricky Ledee was working out in Tampa
with dozens of other young Yankees prospects. Today he wakes up a
Yankee hero.
</P>
<P>
   ``Opportunities are presented, and they have to be taken,'' said
Ledee, who was the surprise starter in left field for Game 1 of the
World Series Saturday night. ``I know how big it is to play in New
York, how championships are important here.''
</P>
<P>
   Ledee, obviously a quick study in Yankees history, ingratiated
himself to the most fickle but loyal fans in baseball. His
game-tying double in the second inning off San Diego ace Kevin
Brown, a line drive into the right-field corner with the bases
loaded, made him an immediate man of the people.
</P>
<P>
   Ledee's journey to the World Series was a bizarre one. Only
after Darryl Strawberry was diagnosed with cancer in his colon did
Ledee find out he was being added to the Yankees postseason roster.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been amazing,'' said Ledee (pronounced Leh-day). ``I
didn't even know I was playing until (Friday). I figured it would
be Tim Raines because he's been around long enough to deserve
starting.''
</P>
<P>
   Ledee, a 24-year-old from Puerto Rico, was the one player the
Yankees were unwilling to let go of when they acquired Hideki Irabu
from San Diego last year. The Padres finally yielded and decided to
take Ruben Rivera instead.
</P>
<P>
   Clearly, the Yankees were aware they may have a good player on
their hands.
</P>
<P>
   Left field has become a sort of hole for the Yankees, especially
since Strawberry's illness surfaced. New York Manager Joe Torre
rode the hot bat of rookie Shane Spencer for a while, but his
bubble seems to have popped.
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew the place was going to be rocking,'' said Ledee, whose
father, Antonio, was a famous salsa singer who died in a car
accident when Ledee was 12. ``Everyone knows about all the famous
players and games that have been in this stadium. I just wanted to
do my part to help the team.''
</P>
<P>
   After his game-tying double in the second, one which came with
two outs, Ledee again got the best of Brown in the fifth inning,
hitting a sharp single to right field with one out.
</P>
<P>
   He also walked and scored during the Yankees' seven-run uprising
in the seventh inning and reached base again in the eighth when San
Diego left fielder Greg Vaughn dropped a fly ball from Ledee.
</P>
<P>
   ``It doesn't matter what else happens the rest of the series, he
knows he can do that,'' Torre said. ``So I'm free to use him any
way I want.''
</P>
<P>
   Spoken like a great manager who just found himself a $100 bill
in the seat cushion of his sofa.
</P>
<P>
   ``He came up to me before the game and said, `Skip, I just
wanted to say thank you,''' Torre said. ``I said, `thank me? You've
earned the right. You're on the roster. I put you in the lineup.' I
was just pleased for him to do that and of course pleased for us
because it gives us another weapon.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
