<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-18 02:03 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3234 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBC-USC-LADN     10-18 0684
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-USC-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
USC WINS 42-14
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
BY SCOTT WOLF  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PULLMAN, Wash. _ All those USC fans clamoring for more of
freshman quarterback Carson Palmer got their wish Saturday night,
although it took an upset stomach to get him in the lineup ahead of
Mike Van Raaphorst.
</P>
<P>
   Van Raaphorst was forced to leave the game in the second quarter
after experiencing vomiting, and the Trojans' offense never looked
back.
</P>
<P>
   Palmer's appearance seemed to infuse the offense with
confidence, because the Trojans went on a 28-point scoring blitz
and defeated the Cougars 42-14 before 31,178 at Martin Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   If nothing else, the quarterback controversy should be
re-ignited for another week.
</P>
<P>
   More importantly, the Trojans (5-2, 3-1) picked up a critical
victory with their bowl hopes beginning to hang in the balance.
</P>
<P>
   And for once, they could thank the offense.
</P>
<P>
   The offense received a twin boost, with Palmer's early insertion
in the second quarter along with the return of tailback Chad Morton
from a bruised back injury.
</P>
<P>
   Morton gave the Trojans some much-needed elusiveness in the
backfield that had been missing the previous two games, when he was
sidelined. Morton gained 68 yards in 16 carries and scored a
touchdown.
</P>
<P>
   But Palmer was the key.
</P>
<P>
   Prior to the true freshman's appearance, the offense was showing
signs of its usual rut in the first half. It had produced just
seven points midway through the second quarter, with linebacker
Chris Claiborne responsible for another touchdown on an
interception.
</P>
<P>
   Coincidence or not, the offense woke up behind Palmer, just like
it had in several previous victories.
</P>
<P>
   On Palmer's second snap, Petros Papadakis raced 53 yards up the
middle to put USC ahead 21-14 in the second quarter.
</P>
<P>
   Palmer got more involved in the third quarter, throwing a 2-yard
touchdown pass from Palmer to tight end Lonnie Ford.
</P>
<P>
   Moments later, wide receiver R. Jay Soward broke the game open
on a 27-yard touchdown run off a reverse. Soward's score gave the
Trojans a 35-14 lead with 9:16 left in the third quarter.
</P>
<P>
   Palmer then completed a 67-yard pass to tight end Antoine Harris
that culminated with Morton scoring on a 6-yard run to give the
Trojans a 42-14 lead in the fourth quarter.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the defense remained consistent, intercepting six of
quarterback Paul Mencke's passes, with Claiborne snagging two.
</P>
<P>
   USC can secure a bowl berth with two more victories, and would
be making its first bowl appearance since the 1996 Rose Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   Prior to USC's 28-0 scoring run, it looked like the Trojans
would be in another struggle, even though the weather (46 degrees)
never posed a problem.
</P>
<P>
   As has so often been the case, Claiborne bailed out the Trojans.
He stole a pass intended for Love Jefferson and returned it 25
yards for a touchdown to give the Trojans a 14-7 advantage. It was
Claiborne's second interception return for a touchdown this season.
</P>
<P>
   The momentum from that touchdown evaporated, however, thanks to
the Trojans' penchant for silly penalties. USC lined up offsides on
the kickoff, and on the second try Washington State's Dee Moronkola
returned it 49 yards to the Trojans' 45-yard line.
</P>
<P>
   Six plays later, Mencke found Nian Taylor wide open on a 29-yard
touchdown pass to tie the game.
</P>
<P>
   Washington State (3-4, 0-4) wasted little time scoring to open
the game. The Cougars went 78 yards with tailback DeJuan Gilmore
going off tackle 35 yards for a touchdown and 7-0 lead.
</P>
<P>
   USC struck back later in the quarter, as the offense finally
concentrated on throwing to senior receivers Billy Miller and Mike
Bastianelli. Miller caught two passes on the drive, then Van
Raaphorst found Bastianelli over the middle for a 32-yard gain.
</P>
<P>
   Three plays later, Van Raaphorst hit Soward in the corner for a
13-yard touchdown pass to tie the game, 7-7.
</P>
<P>
   It was almost remarkable the way USC focused on Miller,
considering he had just 16 receptions in the first six games.
Miller caught seven passes in the first half.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
