<HEADER>
A3235 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBO-SERIES-LADN     10-18 0819
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-SERIES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
YANKEES RALLY TO WIN GAME 1
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
BY MATT McHALE  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Tino Martinez heard the boos and the rumors. They are
always louder in October.
</P>
<P>
   But so is the drama, and no matter how badly he has played this
postseason, no matter how many times he has been traded to make
room for Mo Vaughn, Martinez will always have one swing no one can
ever take away.
</P>
<P>
   His seventh-inning grand slam off left-hander Mark Langston on
Saturday night gave the New York Yankees a 9-6 victory over the San
Diego Padres in Game 1 of the best-of-seven series.
</P>
<P>
   It also capped a comeback that made the Yankees look like, well,
the Yankees. They had trailed by three runs entering the seventh
inning and the crowd of 56,712 was getting a little nervous.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think everybody on the bench took a deep breath,'' said
Yankees manager Joe Torre, who coaxed Martinez out for a curtain
call. ``It's been a tough time for Tino. We all felt great for
him.''
</P>
<P>
   Martinez came in with just five hits in 32 at-bats in the
postseason. And his home run came one pitch after Langston thought
he had a strikeout. But home plate umpire Rich Garcia called
Langston's 2-2 fastball low, setting up the biggest moment of the
night.
</P>
<P>
   The home run landed in the lower stands in right field, scoring
Derek Jeter, Bernie Williams and Chili Davis and giving the Yankees
a 9-5 lead. Mariano Rivera came on to get the final out of the
eighth and retired the side in order in the ninth.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just came out here every day and expected to turn it
around,'' Martinez said. ``I never got down. These guys wouldn't
let me get down. That is why we have been so successful.''
</P>
<P>
   The seventh inning was redemption for more than just Martinez.
Chuck Knoblauch, whose mental lapse helped lose Game 2 of the
American League Championship Series, tied the game with a three-run
homer off Padres reliever Donne Wall.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tonight's a great feeling,'' Knoblauch said. ``We got to the
ALCS and we got to this point. It's a great night tonight.''
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees had just gotten rid of San Diego ace Kevin Brown,
whom the Padres hope can pitch Games 4 and 7, if needed. He made
103 pitches in 61/3 innings and took a sharp grounder off the shin
early in the game.
</P>
<P>
   Brown was given a 5-2 lead after two home runs by Greg Vaughn
and a solo homer by Tony Gwynn, the eight-time batting champion who
is playing in his first World Series since 1984. All three came off
Yankees starter David Wells, who still wound up the winning
pitcher.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we've all got a little spoiled with David,'' Torre
said of Wells, who now has four victories in the postseason. ``He
had good velocity but he put them in some bad spots.''
</P>
<P>
   For six innings the game belonged to the Padres, underdogs in
all three of their postseason series.
</P>
<P>
   Vaughn, the left fielder who hit 50 home runs for San Diego
during the regular season, added two more to put the Padres ahead
5-2. This was the same Vaughn who was traded to New York last
season but sent back when his right shoulder failed a physical.
</P>
<P>
   The first home run came on a 2-2 fastball from Wells that first
appeared to be a casual fly ball to right center. But the ball
carried well past the 385-foot sign and into the stands.
</P>
<P>
   The crowd was stunned and quiet for the first time all night.
They were ready to start the celebration when rookie Ricky Ledee
gave the Yankees the early lead with a two-run double into the
right field corner.
</P>
<P>
   Ledee, placed on the postseason roster 2{ weeks ago when Darryl
Strawberry was diagnosed with colon cancer, not only got a hit in
his first World Series at-bat, he turned on the mighty Brown like
he had been doing it all his life.
</P>
<P>
   But Vaughn's first homer quickly tied it and Gwynn gave the
Padres a 4-2 lead in the fifth when he whacked Wells' first pitch
off the face of the upper deck with Quilvio Veras on first.
</P>
<P>
   Vaugh was next, and he hooked Wells' first pitch around the
left-field foul pole for his second homer.
</P>
<P>
   There was nothing cheap about either homer, but if you expected
it to match some long-ago series record, think again. Florida's
Moises Alou and Charles Johnson did it last year in the fourth
inning of Game 1.
</P>
<P>
   Although Brown was cruising, he was throwing a lot of pitches _
and that was his eventual undoing.
</P>
<P>
   Brown seemed fine when he struck out Martinez to end the sixth,
but he was gone after allowing a single and a walk to No.8-9
hitters Jorge Cosada and Ledee.
</P>
<P>
   Wall came in to face Knoblauch and fell behind 2-0. The next
pitch was a fastball and Knoblauch drove it into the left-field
stands to tie the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``It feels like you didn't do enough,'' Vaughn said. ``You know,
we battled. We battled. It's a tough one to swallow. We've been
here before. You just have to come out and go get them tomorrow.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
