<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-18 02:07 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3236 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBO-KRIKORIAN-COLUMN-     10-18 1104
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-KRIKORIAN-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOR SURE, THESE YANKS ARE SPECIAL
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DOUG KRIKORIAN  
 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ It seemed as though the opener of the 94th World
Series Saturday night was settled by the fifth inning when Tony
Gwynn and Greg Vaughn hit back-to-back home runs to stake Kevin
Brown and the San Diego Padres to a 5-2 lead against the New York
Yankees.
</P>
<P>
   Giving Mr. Brown such an advantage this October is roughly
tantamount to, say, giving the ball to Michael Jordan in June with
a game on the line.
</P>
<P>
   The outcome would seem to be almost automatic, considering Brown
has been Sandy Koufax, Bob Gibson and Roger Clemens all wrapped up
into one obscene-throwing 6-4, 205-pounder who tore through the
National League during the regular season and through Houston and
Atlanta during the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   No way the Yankees could overcome such an insurmountable edge,
not with David Wells so shaky, not with New York's RBI leader, Tino
Martinez, immersed in a terrible slump, not with Tony Gwynn putting
on a hitting demonstration, not with the streaking Padres bursting
with confidence.
</P>
<P>
   But these Yankees aren't the Houston Astros, or Atlanta Braves,
those hapless Padre playoff victims.
</P>
<P>
   These Yankees, performing for the 35th time in their ancestral
fall rite, are something special and showed Kevin Brown and the
Padres why they swept across the summer with an American League
record 114 victories.
</P>
<P>
   They knocked Brown out of the match in the seventh inning and
then two Yankee players who have been struggling with the bats,
Chuck Knoblauch and Martinez, knocked the Padres out of Yankee
Stadium with booming home runs that spurred a seven-run eruption
that resulted in a 9-6 victory before 56,712 delirious onlookers.
</P>
<P>
   Form once again took a beating in this one except for the final
result.
</P>
<P>
   Who would have thought the Yankees would be so disdainfully
impervious to Kevin Brown? Who would have thought David Wells would
be roughed up for five runs in the first five innings? Who would
have thought the first Yankee to score against Brown would be
driven in by the rookie leftfielder, Ricky Ledee? Who would have
thought Chuck Knoblauch, slumping throughout the regular season
with a .265 average and slumping throughout the playoffs with a
.167 average, would tie the game with a three-run homer?
</P>
<P>
   And, most of all, who would have thought the left-handed hitting
Tino Martinez, a mere 5 for 32 for a .156 average in this
post-season as he strode to the plate in that seventh inning
against the left-handed Mark Langston, would seal the Yankee
triumph with a grand slam home run?
</P>
<P>
   ``I needed that ... a big relief,'' admitted Martinez later.
``It's been a tough month for me, but you can't get too down in
this game. You have to battle it day to day. And that's what I've
been doing. I was just fortunate to get a pitch down the middle.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, when the count was two and two, Tino Martinez took a
pitch down that middle that appeared to be a strike to everyone in
the park except to Martinez and to the plate umpire, Rich Garcia.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was over the plate, but definitely low,'' insisted
Martinez.
</P>
<P>
   ``It looked to be a strike, but what can you say?'' said San
Diego manager Bruce Bochy.
</P>
<P>
   Bochy himself could be held responsible for creating some of the
havoc for the Padres, not so much by yanking Brown, who was
faltering, but by replacing him with Donne Wall.
</P>
<P>
   Wall had his bright moments during the regular season, but in
the playoffs he has been ineffective, yielding five hits and three
runs in his previous appearances.
</P>
<P>
   ``Definitely, we were glad to see Kevin Brown out of the game,''
said Tino Martinez.
</P>
<P>
   No one was happier to see Wall than Chuck Knoblauch, the stout
second baseman who greeted him with his home run that barely
cleared the leftfield fence behind the 318-foot sign.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those homers by Knoblauch and Martinez are the kind of
confidence-builders that can get them going,'' said Yankee manager
Joe Torre afterward.
</P>
<P>
   That might be an ominous development for the Padres, heavy
underdogs who squandered a three-hit, two-RBI performance from Tony
Gwynn and squandered a big lead with their best pitcher on the
mound.
</P>
<P>
   Naturally, before David Wells made his first pitch at 8:07
Eastern Standard Time on a 57-degree evening, there were already
all sorts of intriguing subplots and controversies surrounding this
series.
</P>
<P>
   Wells went on the Howard Stern Show Thursday and created tabloid
headlines, even though he didn't shed any apparel or say anything
outlandish, unless you consider it outlandish that he picked the
Yankees to beat the Padres in five games.
</P>
<P>
   What would have been outlandish, of course, if David Wells had
picked the Padres to whip his team in five games.
</P>
<P>
   Upset that Wells would make such a rash prediction that I guess
defied hallowed thou-shall-not-open-your-mouth-in-an-
</P>
<P>
   unseemly-manner World Series convention, the esteemed pitching
coach of the Padres, Mr. Dave Stewart, defiled Wells' reputation.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've faced five pitchers in the playoffs who are better than
David Wells,'' claimed Stewart, referring to the Astros' Randy
Johnson and Shane Reynolds and the Braves' John Smoltz, Tom Glavine
and Greg Maddux.
</P>
<P>
   Actually, considering the way the Padres worked over Wells Torre
removed him after the seventh inning Stewart might be right.
</P>
<P>
   The Boss, George Steinbrenner, a model of low-key restraint
throughout this glorious Yankee season, reportedly also was miffed
that baseball commissioner Bud Selig decided to have Tony Bennett
perform the pre-game singing duties that are traditionally done at
Yankee Stadium by the former opera star, Robert Merrill.
</P>
<P>
   And in an act of pure sacrilege, the 72-year-old Bennett didn't
even sing the National Anthem, the first time in the second half of
the 20th century that this has happened at a World Series according
to venerable baseball historians who monitor such arcane matters.
</P>
<P>
   Lest you think ol' Tony is some anti-American Bolshevik, forget
it.
</P>
<P>
   He sang ``God Bless America'' with a flair that would have made
Kate Smith proud, eliciting loud applause from the crowd, including
even Steinbrenner.
</P>
<P>
   George will have Merrill, whom he considers a Yankee good luck
charm, back doing the Star Spangled Banner honors before Game 2
tonight.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe Robert Merrill, instead, will bring good fortune to the
Padres, who now desperately need it after the fates so cruelly
betrayed them on a night that seemed theirs until the Yankees
displayed their greatness.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
