<P>
   MICROSOFT-GAMEPLANS (Washington) _ The game plans for the
Microsoft trial: handicapping the strategy likely to be pursued by
the two sides, likely key points and, assuming we know by then, key
witnesses. By Steve Lohr.
</P>
<P>
   MICROSOFT-HISTORY (Washington) _ A little-noticed press
conference featuring Bill Gates and a mid-level IBM executive at a
computer show in 1989 first brought Microsoft to the attention of
federal antitrust enforcers. And in the decade since then, the
company has been the subject of unrelenting investigations, one
after another. The issues have molted as the computer industry
matures. But investigators, first with the FTC and then Justice,
have never stopped. All along, by all accounts, they have been free
of political direction or interference from other parts of the
government. By Joel Brinkley.
</P>
<P>
   MICROSOFT-ANTITRUST (Undated) _ The antitrust laws at the core
of the Department of Justice's suit against the Microsoft Corp.
have been around for over a hundred years. Yet their broad
formulation and decades of ambiguous court decisions have produced
what many antitrust experts regard as an intellectual muddle _
confusing interpretations that leave the basic purpose and concepts
of the antitrust laws largely unresolved. That confusion nearly
guarantees that any jury verdict in this case will be appealed.
That could put the current Supreme Court in the position of bring
intellectual order to a century of clashing legal and economic
doctrines.
</P>
<P>
   MICROSOFT-ANTITRUST-LAW (Undated) _ The actual text of the
Sherman Antitrust Law is a mere 180 words. But as wielded by the
government, it has proven to be a big weapon against big business _
even though it was originally derided as a congressional sellout to
big corporate interests. An historical view.
</P>
<P>
   BOOKPUBLISH-GLOBAL (Undated) _ A look at how globalization is
changing the book business: why the Barnes &AMP; Noble/Bertelsmann deal
is scaring midlevel publishers; how the concept of foreign rights
is changing; and how the English language is increasing its
dominance. By Doreen Carvajal.
</P>
<P>
   FCC-PHONE-ASSESS (Undated) _ Analysis: Behind the scenes at last
week's oral argument at the Supreme Court, in which the
local-telephone industry contested the FCC's network-access rules _
and a look at what is likely to come next, regardless of how the
court eventually rules. By Seth Schiesel.
</P>
