<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LEAH-PERSONALS-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BLAME IT ON THE MEDIA
</HEADLINE>
  
 By LEAH GARCHIK  
 c.1998 San Francisco Chronicle
<TEXT>
<P>
   - The  &UR; Mike Barnicle &LR;  incident at the Boston Globe -- in which a
journalist lost his job for allegedly confusing fact and fiction --
prompted essayist/reporter  &UR; Calvin Trillin &LR;  to review his own
career.
</P>
<P>
   As a reporter, he writes in the latest issue of Brill's Content,
he strived for accuracy; as a humorist, he didn't.
</P>
<P>
   ``But do readers make a similar distinction?'' he writes.
``During the 15 years I spent traveling around the country to do a
series of reporting pieces for The New Yorker, the question I was
asked most frequently when I ran across people in New York who
claimed to be regular readers of the series was, `Do you actually
go to the places you write about?'
</P>
<P>
   ``Can these readers really be counted on to take a quote from
 &UR; Immanual Kant &LR;  as a joke?''
</P>
<P>
   - ``Marin County is really determined to do something about
declining birth rates,'' notes  &UR; Milt Moskowitz &LR; , forwarding a
headline from page one of the Mill Valley Herald: ``Sexual assault
program launched.''
</P>
<P>
   - The October issue of  &UR; Francis Ford Coppola &LR; 's magazine,
Zoetrope: All Story, leads off with the first chapter of a
forthcoming memoir by Nobel prize winner  &UR; Gabriel Garcia Marquez &LR; ,
in both English and Spanish.
</P>
<P>
   Coppola's literary magazine, created as a breeding ground for
stories that can expand into movie scripts, claims that  &UR; Tina &LR; 
 &UR; Brown &LR; 's Miramax venture is a copycat enterprise.
</P>
<P>
   If the aim of Zoetrope is new-fangled, advertising support for
it is not. Picture the stereotypical Hemingway-esque writer; all
three ads in the Summer 1998 issue, each a page or more, are from
liquor companies.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; HOW TO BE STYLISH &LR;
</P>
<P>
   InStyle magazine, which usually devotes itself to pushing glitzy
products it says are favored by the stars, has at last decided to
help out the poor plain folks. The latest issue features ``100
Tips, Tricks and Things'' that constitute the ``Secrets of Style.''
Personals' top five (and hang in there, gents, these are unisex):
</P>
<P>
   - ``If the vertical distance from the bottom of your earlobe to
your chin is more than 2-1/4 inches, then you shouldn't have short
hair.''
</P>
<P>
   - ``How to know if a belt fits? The tab should fit comfortably
into the third hole.''
</P>
<P>
   - ``Never wear a white that's whiter than your teeth.''
</P>
<P>
   - ``Never use scented candles at the dinner table.''
</P>
<P>
   - ``Don't mention your weight on a date.''
</P>
<P>
   (P.S.: Where  &LR; ha &LR; s your nose been? Shape magazine's beauty
section describes ``Awake's total Cleansing Sheets,'' which ``work
like diaper wipes, but for the face.'')
</P>
<P>
   &LR;   &LR;   &UR; FLASH &LR;
</P>
<P>
   - There were unpleasantries reported between the protectors of
 &UR; Bill Clinton &LR;  and the protectors of almost-as-important  &UR; Sarah &LR; 
 &UR; Ferguson &LR;  at the G&AMP;P Foundation cancer research benefit in New York
last week. The New York Daily News said that a Secret Service agent
told a Fergie bodyguard: ``You've overstepped your bounds. If you
persist, you will be escorted out of the building.''
</P>
<P>
   (This brought back memories of the  &UR; Duchess of &LR;   &UR; York &LR; 's
appearance in behalf of Weight Watchers in San Francisco, when in
response to a question from KCBS's  &UR; Mike Sugerman &LR; , she threatened
to sic her bodyguards on him.)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; - Johnny Depp &LR;  may play Ichabod Crane in a movie version of
 &UR; Washington Irving &LR; 's ``Legend of Sleepy Hollow.'' Movieline
magazine says that  &UR; Tim Burton &LR;  will direct.
</P>
<P>
   - Gag writer  &UR; Lee Frank &LR; , who contributes one-liners to an array
of TV talk shows, explains their differentiation in Men's Fitness
magazine: `` &UR; Dennis  &LR; ( &UR; Miller &LR; ) is edgy and loves obscure
references.  &UR; Dave  &LR; ( &UR; Letterman &LR; ) is broad and New York-centric, and
he goes for obvious references.  &UR; Jay  &LR; ( &UR; Leno &LR; ) is the front page of
USA Today.  &UR; Bill Maher &LR;  is borscht-belt irreverent.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; - June Gardner &LR;  says her neighbor has both ``Pro-Choice'' and
``Pro-Life'' stickers on his car, leading to the inescapable
conclusion that ``He must be a politician.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WHO SAID WHAT &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ``It was wonderful. The scenery was unbelievable. The &LR; 
 &UR; community was idyllic and the people were just beautiful. The &LR; 
 &UR; whole town had nothing but beautiful people. I think there must &LR; 
 &UR; have been an ordinance banning stupid, ugly people within city &LR; 
 &UR; limits ... then I came to Las Vegas and realized what they'd &LR; 
 &UR; done with them all.'' &LR;
</P>
<P>
   - British bicycle designer  &UR; Mike Burrows &LR;  in VeloNews describing
a trip to the United States that started in Marin County. &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-18-98 1608EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981018.0074 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-18 16:08 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
