<P>
   ``Can these readers really be counted on to take a quote from
 &UR; Immanual Kant &LR;  as a joke?''
</P>
<P>
   - ``Marin County is really determined to do something about
declining birth rates,'' notes  &UR; Milt Moskowitz &LR; , forwarding a
headline from page one of the Mill Valley Herald: ``Sexual assault
program launched.''
</P>
<P>
   - The October issue of  &UR; Francis Ford Coppola &LR; 's magazine,
Zoetrope: All Story, leads off with the first chapter of a
forthcoming memoir by Nobel prize winner  &UR; Gabriel Garcia Marquez &LR; ,
in both English and Spanish.
</P>
<P>
   Coppola's literary magazine, created as a breeding ground for
stories that can expand into movie scripts, claims that  &UR; Tina &LR; 
 &UR; Brown &LR; 's Miramax venture is a copycat enterprise.
</P>
<P>
   If the aim of Zoetrope is new-fangled, advertising support for
it is not. Picture the stereotypical Hemingway-esque writer; all
three ads in the Summer 1998 issue, each a page or more, are from
liquor companies.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; HOW TO BE STYLISH &LR;
</P>
<P>
   InStyle magazine, which usually devotes itself to pushing glitzy
products it says are favored by the stars, has at last decided to
help out the poor plain folks. The latest issue features ``100
Tips, Tricks and Things'' that constitute the ``Secrets of Style.''
Personals' top five (and hang in there, gents, these are unisex):
</P>
<P>
   - ``If the vertical distance from the bottom of your earlobe to
your chin is more than 2-1/4 inches, then you shouldn't have short
hair.''
</P>
<P>
   - ``How to know if a belt fits? The tab should fit comfortably
into the third hole.''
</P>
<P>
   - ``Never wear a white that's whiter than your teeth.''
</P>
<P>
   - ``Never use scented candles at the dinner table.''
</P>
<P>
   - ``Don't mention your weight on a date.''
</P>
<P>
   (P.S.: Where  &LR; ha &LR; s your nose been? Shape magazine's beauty
section describes ``Awake's total Cleansing Sheets,'' which ``work
like diaper wipes, but for the face.'')
</P>
