<SLUG> BC-FOOD-COLUMN-OWEN-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ALL'S WELL THAT ENDS WITH CYMBERLINE CAKE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JOHN OWEN  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   You can order an ice cream sundae called Shakespeare's
Inspiration at Rosie's Sweet Shoppe in Ashland, Ore. It's just up
the street from the All's Well Herb and Vitamin Shoppe, not far
from Puck's Doughnuts and a motel known as Bard's Inn.
</P>
<P>
   Or you could skip ice cream and doughnuts and head for the city
park where lithia water _ containing at least 20 minerals _ is
offered free of charge. The city fountains were installed in 1911
in hopes that Ashland might become a European-style health spa.
</P>
<P>
   Today Ashland does, in fact, have an international reputation _
for bad water and great drama. The Oregon Shakespeare Festival,
begun in 1935, now employs 430 actors, directors and technicians
almost year-round. Such is the status of the company, it might even
be possible to order ice cream sundaes and Puck's doughnuts
delivered c.o.d. to the green room underneath the open-air
Elizabethan Theatre, where the actors await their cues.
</P>
<P>
   ``On a typical night there might be a chess or backgammon
tournament going on in the green room,'' Seattle actor G. Valmont
Thomas reveals. ``A couple of other people might be reading
books.'' The actors keep track of the play's progress over audio
feeds of two different plays. When they bolt from the green room on
cue they not only have to remember what part they are playing, they
have to remember in which theater they are appearing.
</P>
<P>
   For example this past season Dan Donohue played Sir Benjamin
Backbite in an afternoon performance of ``School for Scandal'' in
the Angus Bowmer Theatre. Then he returned that night to portray
Prince Hal in ``Henry IV'' on the Elizabethan stage.
</P>
<P>
   And save a few doughnuts for Charlie Kimball, who plays seven
different if minor roles during a single performance of ``Henry
IV.''
</P>
<P>
   Those are long days and some cold nights, although a play's
running time may diminish slightly on the outdoor stage. ``When the
temperature dips, there are not nearly as many pregnant pauses,''
production assistant Mark Mezadourian Hughes reports.
</P>
<P>
   Yet it is anticipated that as many as 1,300 actors will audition
for 10 or 12 openings next season in the Oregon Shakespeare Theatre
company.
</P>
<P>
   They must be serving something more satisfying than Puck's
doughnuts in the green room these days. They might even be serving
up portions of:
</P>
<P>
   Shakespearean Salmon Tart
</P>
<P>
   1 unbaked 9-inch pastry shell
</P>
<P>
   1 egg white, lightly beaten
</P>
<P>
   One-half pound smoked salmon, chopped
</P>
<P>
   1 cup grated Swiss cheese
</P>
<P>
   4 eggs
</P>
<P>
   One-and-one-quarter cups half-and-half
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon dillweed
</P>
<P>
   One-half teaspoon salt
</P>
<P>
   Freshly ground black pepper
</P>
<P>
   Preheat oven to 400 degrees. Brush the pastry shell with the egg
white and bake five minutes. Let cool slightly.
</P>
<P>
   Turn the oven to 450 degrees.
</P>
<P>
   Scatter the salmon over the pastry shell and sprinkle with
cheese. Beat all the other ingredients together and pour over the
cheese. Bake 15 minutes, reduce heat to 350 degrees and continue to
bake until the tart is golden and set, about 15 minutes more.
</P>
<P>
   Serves eight members of the Fairy Kingdom from ``A Midsummer
Night's Dream'' or six soldiers serving under Henry IV.
</P>
<P>
   Cymbeline Cake
</P>
<P>
   One-third cup butter
</P>
<P>
   1 cup sifted flour
</P>
<P>
   One-half teaspoon baking powder
</P>
<P>
   One-quarter teaspoon baking soda
</P>
<P>
   One-quarter teaspoon salt
</P>
<P>
   Three-quarters cup sugar
</P>
<P>
   1 egg
</P>
<P>
   One-third cup buttermilk
</P>
<P>
   One-half teaspoon vanilla extract
</P>
<P>
   One-and-one-half cups raspberries
</P>
<P>
   Crumb topping (recipe follows)
</P>
<P>
   Actually, you could use any fresh fruit with this cake. If you
wait until the raspberry season, you can serve this cake next
summer to the Three Musketeers, who will be sharing the green room
with the cast of ``Chicago.''
</P>
<P>
   OK, places everybody! Melt the butter and then allow it to cool
to room temperature. While this is happening, oil or butter the
sides and bottom of an 8-by-8-inch cake pan.
</P>
<P>
   Sift together the flour, baking powder, baking soda and salt.
Add the sugar and mix.
</P>
<P>
   In another bowl thoroughly mix the egg, buttermilk and vanilla.
Add the melted butter and stir again. Dump this muck in with the
flour and stir for a couple of minutes more with a wooden spoon.
</P>
<P>
   Gloop the batter into the prepared cake pan, spread it out
evenly and then scatter the raspberries over the top. Add the final
crumb topping and shove the cake into a 375-degree oven for about
40 minutes. Let the pan cool on a rack and when the cake is just
warm, dish it up with vanilla ice cream on the side.
</P>
<P>
   The Crumb Topping
</P>
<P>
   One-half cup firmly packed brown sugar
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons flour
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon butter in small bits
</P>
<P>
   One-half ounce (or about two tablespoons) grated semisweet
chocolate
</P>
<P>
   Dump those ingredients into a food processor, give it a blast
until the topping is the consistency of damp dirt.
</P>
<P>
   In the green room at Ashland, they probably assign somebody from
the Rapier and Dagger Workshop to slice the tarts and cakes.
</P>
<P>
   John Owen writes ``The Intermediate Eater'' weekly for the
Seattle P-I.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
