u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MEDIA-TALK-2TAKES-NYT     10-18 0951
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEDIA-TALK-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MEDIA TALK: SHORT LIST FOR NEWSWEEK EDITOR; MEDIA'S POOR IMAGE;
L.A. TIMES BROADENS LATINO COVERAGE; MINORITIES IN MAGAZINES;
MARTHA STEWART AND THE GAP 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Mass., Ohio, Calif.)  (mk) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   The editor at Newsweek magazine needs the management skills of
an eagle-eyed chief executive, the energy of a distance runner and
the composure of the Mona Lisa. Maynard Parker, the editor from
1982 until his death on Friday, had all of those qualities, those
who worked with him say.
</P>
<P>
   ``His credo was `More, faster, better,''' said Michael Elliott,
editor of international editions. ``Watching him edit was like
watching someone edit by lightning, not watching someone edit by
60-watt bulb.''
</P>
<P>
   Washington Post Co., which owns the magazine, is not expected to
announce a successor for at least several weeks. The list of
potential editors includes Ann McDaniel, Newsweek's Washington
bureau chief; Elliott; assistant managing editor Evan Thomas, and
managing editor Mark Whitaker, who was Parker's first deputy and
has been responsible for day-to-day operations since Parker became
ill.
</P>
<P>
   Among the Newsweek staff, most bets are on Whitaker, who began
his Newsweek career as an intern in 1977, before graduating from
Harvard University in 1979. One staff member said any other choice
would be ``astonishing.'' If Whitaker were chosen, he would become
the highest-ranking black journalist in the country.
</P>
<P>
   Whitaker has overseen coverage of the Monica Lewinsky matter and
of crises in Bosnia and Somalia. He has contributed essays on race,
including one titled ``The Verdict'' after the O.J. Simpson trial.
</P>
<P>
   The choice of Ms. McDaniel would mark a different milestone: She
would be Newsweek's first woman editor. She is a close friend of
Parker and holds three titles: assistant managing editor,
Washington bureau chief and chief of correspondents.
</P>
<P>
   Elliott oversees Newsweek's international coverage as well as
international editions in six languages.
</P>
<P>
   Thomas was Washington bureau chief for 10 years until 1996, and
is a frequent guest on the talk-show circuit. He is at work on a
biography of Robert F. Kennedy.
</P>
<P>
   _ ALEX KUCZYNSKI
</P>
<P>
   Scandals Don't Much Harm an Already Bad Reputation
</P>
<P>
   Has the recent spate of journalistic scandals damaged the
media's credibility? There's a good news/bad news answer.
</P>
<P>
   A public opinion poll by the nonprofit Media Studies Center
found most people haven't noticed the scandals. But it also found
that not many had a high opinion of journalists to begin with.
</P>
<P>
   The pollsters found that 42 percent of those surveyed had heard
of the scandal in which CNN retracted a report that the U.S.
military used nerve gas. Eleven percent knew about an investigative
project by The Cincinnati Enquirer in which the reporter stole
voice mail messages. The dismissal of two columnists at The Boston
Globe was known to 21 percent, and 12 percent were aware of the
dismissal of Stephen Glass of The New Republic for fabricating
information in more than two dozen articles.
</P>
<P>
   The scandals did not seem to affect how much people read or
watched the news. In Boston, 67 percent of those surveyed knew
something about the scandal at The Globe, which is owned by New
York Times Co., but only 3 percent said they were reading the paper
less than before. One percent said they were reading it more.
</P>
<P>
   The poll found that 67 percent thought journalists often or
sometimes invent stories, 76 percent thought they often or
sometimes plagiarize, 87 percent felt they often or sometimes use
unethical or illegal tactics and 86 percent believed that stories
often or sometimes have factual errors.
</P>
<P>
   ``The attitude of many Americans toward journalists when these
things happen seems to be, `There they go again,''' said Robert
Giles, executive director of the Media Studies Center.
</P>
<P>
   _ DYLAN LOEB McCLAIN
</P>
<P>
   The Los Angeles Times Assembles a `Latino Team'
</P>
<P>
   In its effort to broaden coverage of minority communities and
meet its ambitious circulation goals, The Los Angeles Times is
establishing an 11-member ``Latino team'' that will include
reporters in the business, cultural, sports and general news
departments. It will meet daily and plan coverage of Latino issues
throughout the newspaper.
</P>
<P>
   The team represents the latest in a series of efforts to
increase both coverage of Latino affairs and the newspaper's
circulation in the Hispanic population. About a third of residents
in the five-county area around Los Angeles are Hispanic and about
19 percent of the newspaper's readers are, according to the paper's
research. The publisher, Mark Willes, who is also chairman and
chief executive of the newspaper's parent, Times-Mirror Co., has
said he wants to increase the newspaper's circulation by 50
percent, to about 1.5 million. He provoked widespread opposition by
suggesting separate space for Latino news.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a better idea than a Latino section,'' said Vicki
Torres, a small-business columnist, ``because the Latino team then
makes sure that there's something throughout the paper, as part of
our ongoing coverage, that addresses Latinos.''
</P>
<P>
   The paper will add positions for a reporter specializing in
relations between Mexico and the United States, a national Hispanic
affairs reporter with a counterpart in the Los Angeles area, a
religion reporter and a photographer who doubles as a photo editor.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are a kind of Latino capital,'' said Frank del Olmo, the
associate editor heading the team. The idea, he said, is ``to try
to get as far ahead of the curve as we can on Latino stories.''
</P>
<P>
   _ FELICITY BARRINGER
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Minorities at 6.1 Percent on Major Magazine Staffs
</P>
<P>
   How well are minority groups represented in the magazine
industry?
</P>
<P>
   A survey commissioned by the trade magazine Mediaweek included
interviews with 165 of the top 300 magazines as ranked by
circulation. It found people of color represent 6.1 percent of
professional staff _ from nonclerical editorial staff, freelance
writers and sales staff up through the publisher's level.
</P>
<P>
   A breakdown showed these percentages: blacks 2.6; Hispanics
1.5., native Americans, 0.3, Asian-Americans, 1.7. The survey was
done by Fairfield Research in Lincoln, Neb.
</P>
<P>
   Advice About Clothing and a Snug Fit for the Ads
</P>
<P>
   For anyone who has wondered who invented dry cleaning or how to
care for mohair, Martha Stewart has come to the rescue. This month,
Martha Stewart Living published a special issue titled
``Clotheskeeping,'' devoted to the maintenance of _ and how to
choose _ classic clothing.
</P>
<P>
   Apart from the hijinks of Monsieur Jolly-Bollin (the father of
modern dry cleaning), what's intriguing about the
``Clotheskeeping'' issue is that it has only one advertiser: 33
pages of the Gap.
</P>
<P>
   Clearly, the Gap aesthetic is Stewart-friendly. Folded in the
bureau (page 73) and dangling from the ironing board (page 22) are
Gap items. More are on pages 54, 63 and 69 _ and on the cover,
which shows shirts from the Gap, along with some from Barneys and
Agnes B.
</P>
<P>
   A coincidence?
</P>
<P>
   Marlene Kahan, president of the American Society of Magazine
Editors, which monitors the practices of magazine editors, said
that she was ``concerned'' about the use of Gap shirts on the
cover. But Suzanne Sobel, publisher of Martha Stewart Living,
published by Martha Stewart Living Omnimedia LLC, said there was
nothing unusual in the magazine's dealings with Gap Inc. ``We
didn't see the ads prior to them delivering them, and they didn't
see the editorial,'' she said. ``But we do have the same taste.''
</P>
<P>
   Allen Adamson, managing director at Landor Associates, a New
York brand consulting firm that is part of Young &AMP; Rubicam, saw
criticism of Ms. Stewart as likely. ``How far can you push the
envelope on editorial credibility and advertising promotion?'' he
asked. ``For someone as powerful an authority on what is right and
what is in, there will be a little nipping and tugging on her
credibility.'' He said he thought damage would be minimal but
added, ``Any illusion that this is not a
promotional-slash-infomercial use is a fallacy.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Sobel sees no problem. ``We really handled this so it would
not appear infomercialized,'' she said. ``There was no collusion
whatsoever.'' She added: ``We've gotten calls from so many
advertisers this week wanting to do the same thing.''
</P>
<P>
   _ ALEX KUCZYNSKI
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
