</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-BARNHART-COLUMN19-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    A look back at what has transpired
 &HT;    By Tony Barnhart
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ They don't give awards for one-half season's work, but
if they did, these would be my nominees:
</P>
<P>
   Best game: Until Saturday, it was a tie between Georgia's 28-27
win over LSU and Tennessee's 34-33 win at Syracuse. But Georgia
Tech's 41-38 win over No. 7 Virginia, when the Yellow Jackets
rallied from 21 points down, takes the prize.
</P>
<P>
   Best player: Texas running back Ricky Williams had this week
off, but he is headed for immortality. Through six games Williams
has 1,225 yards and 22 touchdowns. Barring injury, he will be the
NCAA's all-time leading rusher at the end of this season.
</P>
<P>
   Best coach: Arkansas was picked to finish last in the SEC West.
Today the Hogs are 6-0 and No. 15 in the AP poll and No. 12 in the
coaches poll. Houston Nutt obviously did something right. Now let's
see how it goes in the second half with a schedule that includes
Auburn, Mississippi, Tennessee, Mississippi State, and LSU.
</P>
<P>
   Biggest disappointment: North Carolina was No. 11 in the
preseason. That was too high, given the personnel losses, which
included a ton of NFL draft picks and the coach. But there is no
way the Tar Heels should be 2-3. Doesn't matter. Basketball
practice started last week.
</P>
<P>
   Most overrated: LSU, 3-3 and out of the Top 25 after starting
the season in everybody's Top 10. After Saturday night's 39-36 loss
to Kentucky, it must be apparent to everybody that Lou Tepper ain't
getting it done as defensive coordinator.
</P>
<P>
   Most underrated: Texas A&AMP;M is 6-0 since losing to Florida State
in the Kickoff Classic. The Aggies have beaten Nebraska and will
probably face Kansas State in the Big 12 championship game. They
play great defense.
</P>
<P>
   Coach most likely to be moving (his choice): Tommy Bowden of No.
22 Tulane (5-0) who will have his pick of jobs at the end of the
season.
</P>
<P>
   Coach most likely to be moving (somebody else's choice): South
Carolina's Brad Scott, although the scribes in the Palmetto State
insist he'll get one more year from AD Mike McGee.
</P>
<P>
   Just thinking
</P>
<P>
   Not that the coaches don't put a lot of thought into it, but why
does their poll rank Kansas State, at No. 3, ahead of Tennessee?
Kansas State has played the worst non-conference schedule in
history: Indiana State (3-3), Northern Illinois, (1-5) and
Northeast Louisiana (2-4). The Wildcats have beaten one ranked
team, No. 17 Colorado, 16-9. Tennessee has beaten No. 21 Syracuse
on the road, No. 11 Georgia on the road and No. 5 Florida at home.
The AP poll of writers and broadcasters recognizes this and has the
Volunteers No. 3.
</P>
<P>
   Has there ever been a time when Auburn's Terry Bowden needed to
win a ball game more than Saturday's meeting with Louisiana Tech?
The Tigers are 1-5 and getting worse, not better. There are rumors
starting to come out of the state that Bowden is in trouble but I
don't buy it. Besides, the powers that be would have to take out a
second mortgage on Jordan-Hare Stadium to pay off Bowden's
seven-year contract.
</P>
<P>
   UCLA has invested a lot of emotional energy in the last two wins
over Arizona and Oregon, which it beat 41-38 in overtime Saturday.
The Bruins could be ripe for a stumble when they travel to
surprising California on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Worth noting
</P>
<P>
   Florida coach Steve Spurrier actually said this after Saturday's
24-3 win over Auburn: ``My job is to win games, not run up a bunch
of statistics,'' said Spurrier. My how times have changed.
Actually, Spurrier was just playing it smart against a team he knew
would never score on his defense, even if they played for three
days.
</P>
<P>
   Here's an early stat that should concern you Georgia Tech fans
as No. 6 Florida State comes to town. After struggling early in the
season, Seminole quarterback Chris Weinke has thrown 149
consecutive passes without an interception. After beating Clemson
48-0, the Florida State offense may be rounding into shape in time
for Saturday night's game on ESPN.
</P>
<P>
   Tennessee coach Phillip Fulmer will be reminding his team this
week that the 1992 Volunteer squad also started 5-0. Then they fell
off the face of the earth with consecutive losses to Arkansas,
Alabama, and South Carolina. It's the fourth Saturday in October,
but Alabama will be in Knoxville. The Crimson Tide has spoiled a
lot of Big Orange dreams.
</P>
<P>
   Kramer at TD Club
</P>
<P>
   SEC Commissioner Roy Kramer will be the featured speaker at
today's meeting of the Atlanta Touchdown Club, set for the Galleria
Centre. Lunch begins at noon, followed by remarks from Kramer. For
more information call 770-953-3200.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
