<HEADER>
A3476 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBC-GATECH-FOLO19-COX     10-18 0518
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-GATECH-FOLO19-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Fans, team find it too early to sweep Georgia Tech win under rug
 &HT;    By Carroll Rogers
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Sunday morning found Georgia Tech's campus scattered
with evidence of something special _ remnants of yellow pom-poms
strewn on the ground, floats still standing intact in front of
sorority and fraternity houses, tents with tables and chairs long
abandoned by Tech alumni and fans, and a curious void behind both
end zones at Bobby Dodd Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   This particular post-homecoming mess was worth keeping around
for a while. No Tech fan wanted to sweep the memory of Saturday's
improbable come-from-behind 41-38 win over Virginia under a rug
just yet. The only tricky part of the homecoming hangover was those
missing goalposts, which Tech fans engineered down in a few seconds
and carried off the field after Tech's biggest victory since it won
by the same score at Virginia on the way to the UPI national
championship in 1990.
</P>
<P>
   When Tech coach George O'Leary got into his office Sunday
morning, the first call he got was from the president of a football
equipment manufacturing company, asking if he needed some goal
posts.
</P>
<P>
   Oh, the hassles of winning big.
</P>
<P>
   O'Leary gave him the number of Tech associate athletics director
Sterling Brown, whose task it is to get his hands on some new
goalposts and quick, since No. 6 Florida State is coming Saturday
for what now looks like the ACC championship game.
</P>
<P>
   No. 20 Tech (5-1, 4-0) is the only team still undefeated in the
ACC and a win over Seminoles (6-1, 3-1) would all but secure its
first ACC title since 1990, assuming it could beat Clemson,
Maryland and Wake Forest. If FSU wins, Tech still has a shot at a
share. Things don't get complicated unless FSU beats both Tech and
Virginia, in which case there would be a three-way tie for first in
the ACC.
</P>
<P>
   The ACC has adopted a tiebreaking system based on head-to-head
</P>
<P>
   competition and rankings. If Tech, Florida State and Virginia
are all tied with 7-1 records, the highest-ranked team would get
the first bid.
</P>
<P>
   O'Leary, though, has turned his attention to getting this team
ready for a high-powered Seminole offense.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm glad we're playing Florida State now,'' O'Leary said.
``We'll catch
</P>
<P>
   the kids' attention real quick.''
</P>
<P>
   They'll need quarterback Joe Hamilton healthy to do it, and
expect to
</P>
<P>
   have him ready. Hamilton sprained his medial collateral ligament
during the second quarter on Saturday but was able to fight through
the pain and play.
</P>
<P>
   While he looked pretty mobile when he dropped back to pass,
Hamilton admitted after the game he had little confidence in his
ability to run. O'Leary said he may rest him in the early part of
the week, but Tech expects to have him for Florida State on
Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   As for Tech's defense, those eye-popping 600 yards the Yellow
Jackets gave up on defense come into focus this week as they look
for ways to play for four quarters like they did late against
Virginia.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
