<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOTEL-CITY-IMAGE-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Impact of killings on tourism may depend on circumstances
 &HT;    WITH HOTEL-SHOOTING
 &HT;    By Alfred Charles
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ In the wake of a triple slaying at an upscale downtown
hotel, city leaders and tourism officials are wondering what the
killings will mean for Atlanta's lucrative tourism and convention
business.
</P>
<P>
   But the officials who spoke Sunday said the impact on the city's
hotel business largely will depend on the circumstances of the
killings _ whether it was a random attack on conventioneers or a
dispute between acquaintances that turned deadly.
</P>
<P>
   ``Anything that casts a negative shadow on the city is a
concern,'' said Bill Howard, vice president for public relations
and tourism at the Atlanta Convention and Visitors Bureau. ``But we
are not sure whether the victims were visitors to our city or
people involved in illegal activity.''
</P>
<P>
   Police have said little publicly about the execution-style
slayings that occurred on the 24th floor of the Atlanta Hilton &AMP;
Towers. Police have said only that a maid discovered the bodies of
three men, who had each been shot in the head.
</P>
<P>
   With so few facts in the public domain, city officials said the
public and would-be guests at downtown Atlanta hotels should not
rush to judgement before all the facts about the killings are
known.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is unfortunate if people jump to the conclusion that this a
trend or the city is unsafe,'' said Jabari Simama, spokesman for
Mayor Bill Campbell. ``Downtown is safe.''
</P>
<P>
   The three killings occurred on the last day of a special
promotion called the Atlanta Homecoming Weekend that was sponsored
by the convention and visitors bureau. The effort provided
discounts to local residents who stayed at downtown hotels.
</P>
<P>
   Spurgeon Richardson, president of the visitors bureau, said
tourism business likely won't be affected if the victims were
involved in illegal behavior such as drug-dealing.
</P>
<P>
   ``Meeting planners understand that while it's unfortunate,
drug-related crime can happen anywhere in the country,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Other convention officials said if the attack does turn out to
be a deadly assault on convention-goers, they would work with the
city to protect Atlanta's tourism business.
</P>
<P>
   ``We would do whatever we could to fix the cause,'' Howard said.
</P>
<P>
   Convention officials said there has been little reported
violence against visitors who come to Atlanta on business and stay
in central business district hotels.
</P>
<P>
   Four months ago, police said crime in Zone 5, which includes
downtown, dropped 23 percent in 1997 and continued to decline this
year. Downtown has just four fewer police officers patrolling the
streets than in 1995, authorities said this summer.
</P>
<P>
   And yet, a study commissioned by the Convention and Visitors
Bureau showed that the perception of crime in Atlanta was one of
the biggest problems facing the city while trying to lure
convention and trade shows - and the guests who will fill downtown
hotel rooms.
</P>
<P>
   Such shows pump millions of dollars every year into Atlanta's
economy.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
