A3480 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BISHER-COLUMN19-COX     10-18 0705
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BISHER-COLUMN19-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Falcons reach back and call on an old relic of their own
 &HT;    By Furman Bisher
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ They came together in Georgia Dome Sunday afternoon
and gave us an interesting study in the world of quarterbacking,
though that was not the purpose of it all. The purpose was to see
if the Falcons, of the local precinct, could lay another one on the
New Orleans Saints, or vice versa. As it turned out, vice versa
came in second.
</P>
<P>
   Down through the tunnel of time, New Orleans has become the
Halfway House for NFL quarterbacks. A stream of lads with a hope
and oldtimers trying to stretch out careers have passed through
Saints uniforms. Steve Walsh, Wade Wilson, Jim Everett, then Heath
Shuler, and this year is no exception, beginning with Billy Joe
Holbert, who was injured, followed by Danny Wuerffel, then the
latest in couch cases, Kerry Collins, who didn't have the heart for
it in Charlotte.
</P>
<P>
   Who should show up Sunday, with a fleur de lis on his hat but
the old Texas redhead, Billy (Available) Joe Tolliver. He was
sitting at home a month ago, coaching his kid's team, when the
telephone rang, and it was Mike Ditka. When Billy Joe was a Falcon,
it was the consensus that you'd have more confidence in him if he
had a 2-iron in hand. Ditka wanted him because he's ``Iron Mike's''
kind, tough and tough.
</P>
<P>
   By the time night fell, as well as one can tell from inside the
big tent, the Falcons had reached back into their collection of
keepsakes and called on an old relic of their own. The fear
resident in all our hearts had come to pass, that Chris Chandler
might come down wounded and take the season with him. In the second
quarter, a linebacker named Mark Fields piled into Chandler with
malice in his heart and the result was, the Falcon quarterback was
gone, badly bruised shoulder and ribs.
</P>
<P>
   Enter Steve DeBerg, who will be 45 years old in January, and who
hadn't thrown a pass in the league since December, five years ago.
Now the combined age of the two quarterbacks on the field was 75.
It had the ring of an oldtimers game. But say this, Tolliver looked
as much at home as with his 2-iron, and DeBerg looked as though he
hadn't missed a beat. It was an intriguing match of ``The Redheaded
Quarterback'' and ``The Rocking Chair Quarterback.'' In honor of
the occasion, even ``the wave'' was revived by the rejuvenated,
re-inspired fans.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were great,'' Dan Reeves said, ``but I wish they'd learn
to time the wave to when the Saints have the ball.''
</P>
<P>
   The Saints were backed up by their usual shipload of ``Who
Dats,'' who came across loud and clear. Their effect is kind of
lost in the big old barn, not nearly the presence they were in the
old open-air stadium. They stood by their man Tolliver, and for a
guy who had been in mothballs a spell himself, he kept the Saints
in the game. He got off a couple of bombs to Keith Poole, out of
Arizona State, and completed 14 out of 29 passes for 261 yards.
</P>
<P>
   It was the longest time before DeBerg was able to move the
chains, but once he found the right gear, he also found the end
zone, on an 8-yard pass to Bob Christian in the fourth quarter. As
it turned out, if the Braves had had the Falcons kind of bullpen,
they'd be in the World Series today.
</P>
<P>
   The Falcons won, 31-23, and the record is now 5-1. Once before,
in Dan Henning's last year, they got away to a 4-0 start, including
a winning date with Dallas, but won only three more games the rest
of the season. When Mike Ditka was here the last time, he was so
furious he threatened to retire. He had reason again, and left no
doubt about it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not happy with this at all,'' he said. ``They were tougher
than us. They smacked us in the mouth. It's a lack of discipline.''
All of this after he and Reeves, old teammates at Dallas, had
embraced at midfield.
</P>
<P>
   It bears saying, though, that after all the twilight excitement
at Bobby Dodd-Grant Field Saturday, as Georgia Tech beat Virginia
in a game for the museum, this one was sort of like swearing off.
It was tame stuff, back to the predictable routine of the pro game.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
