u r &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RAC-NASCAR19-COX     10-18 0461
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RAC-NASCAR19-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Gordon edges closer Winston Cup
 &HT;    By Tom McCollister
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTONA BEACH, Fla. _ Jeff Gordon finally won a race in the
month of October on Saturday night, slaying those conservative
demons and leaving him within reach of securing his third Winston
Cup points championship.
</P>
<P>
   Gordon's victory at Daytona International Speedway was as
spectacular as the new 1,835 light fixtures that provided light for
the track and the capacity crowd.
</P>
<P>
   With the victory, the 27-year-old Gordon leads runnerup Mark
Martin, who finished 16th, by 358 points. All Gordon needs to claim
the title is to finish 32nd or better in the final three events, or
gain 18 points on Martin this week at Phoenix.
</P>
<P>
   ``What keeps me going? There's always something left to
accomplish,'' Gordon said of his 11 victories and 17 top-five
finishes. ``What drives me is competition, driving into Victory
Lane. It doesn't matter what race it is. I don't look at the
records. I like challenging for the wins. We haven't won at every
track on the circuit.''
</P>
<P>
   Gordon put victory No. 11 in the books the hard way. Following a
36-minute red flag rain delay, Gordon made the track as narrow as
possible for those who ran at him during the final laps. He locked
onto his rear view mirror and blocked every move by charging Bobby
Labonte for his 40th career victory.
</P>
<P>
   ``I saw Bobby coming on with a head of steam and said, 'Man,
I've got to block him,''' said Gordon, who led only 49 laps,
including the final 38. ``It was an awesome race. It wasn't the
Fourth of July, but there were a lot of fireworks out there.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nobody wanted to see race end under caution. It's tough to be
a driver and know what you go through out there with a three-lap
shootout. It's hard to be in favor of that. It's more dangerous.
It's a double-edge sword. But the fans make the sport. Thankfully,
there were no serious injuries.''
</P>
<P>
   There were six cautions for 26 laps and 16 lead changes among
nine drivers. The most serious injury was a fractured shoulder
blade, suffered by Kevin Lepage when he hit the wall in turn two
and began a 12-car crash.
</P>
<P>
   Dale Jarrett, who led 38 laps early, had a tire go down and
finished 23rd; and Dale Earnhardt, who ran through Bobby Labonte's
pit, pushed a tire down pit road and damaged the aerodynamics. He
finished 10th.
</P>
<P>
   ``We finally won a race in October,'' Gordon said. ``We wanted
to be little bit stronger in the latter part of the year. Maybe we
approached it too conservatively, but we couldn't be conservative
because Mark was running so strong. This gives us the opportunity
to go to Phoenix and run real strong there.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
