<HEADLINE>
GIVE ESPN CREDIT FOR MAKING IT LOOK ATTRACTIVE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By TOM HOFFARTH  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ The idea sounded good at the time.
</P>
<P>
   Three years ago, ESPN, which was just beginning to discover that
it could put its label on anything that wasn't moving, started to
offer its own Master Card through MBNA America, a bank based in
Wilmington, Del.
</P>
<P>
   The hook was, the more you used the card, the more ``dream
points'' you accumulated. Earn one point for every dollar charged
on the card. Then cash in the points for prizes down the road. It's
a popular, 18.9 percent-proof scam. Perfectly legal.
</P>
<P>
   Well, ESPN card holders were informed recently that the ESPN
Rewards Program will expire on Oct. 31, 1999. No problem. The
one-year warning has been sounded.
</P>
<P>
   But the point is, if you're a card-carrying customer in Los
Angeles, racking up ``dream points'' is kind of pointless. Consider
these choices:
</P>
<P>
   __ 1,000 points: An autograph from Gale Sayers, Walt Frazier,
Bob Feller, Bernie Parent or Bill Barber.
</P>
<P>
   Great, if you're a native of Chicago, New York, Cleveland,
Philadelphia... and who the hell is Bill Barber?
</P>
<P>
   __ 5,000 points: Two tickets to one of 12 sporting events
between now and September '99. Stuff like a New Orleans Saints game
in November, a Charlotte Hornets game in January (better wait on
that one), an ATP Tour event in Key Biscayne, Fla., next March or
the '99 Preakness in Baltimore.
</P>
<P>
   OK, but is travel included? Sure, if you use your card to buy
your own plane ticket. The closest event to pick is the PGA
International event in Las Vegas, which, by the way, ended Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   __ 7,500 points: Two choices: 1) A deluxe celebrity-hosted
private tour of ESPN's studio in Bristol, Conn., which includes a
night hotel stay, breakfast and dinner. Just pick one of nine
convenient dates. 2) A night at the ESPY Awards in New York City in
February '99.
</P>
<P>
   The downside: 1) no plane trip included and 2) no plane trip
included.
</P>
<P>
   __ 15,000 points: The grand prize, which can be easily had if
you put a new Chrysler LeBaron on the card, is a package _ hotel
accommodations, included _ for VIP access in the control room to
watch a taping of ``UpClose.'' And you get to meet Chris Myers
after the show!
</P>
<P>
   This time, they'll fly you there.
</P>
<P>
   And by the way, the show tapes in Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   There's time left to order a card and run up a tab (call
1-800-847-7378 or apply online at www.webapply.com/espn). I really
shouldn't admit to how much damage I've incurred on the card over
the last three years.
</P>
<P>
   Put it this way: Trade you four Gale Sayers scribbles and two
tickets to a Detroit Tigers game for another Bob Feller autograph.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
