<HEADLINE>
BUSINESS AT A GLANCE 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   A Possible Kroger Merger Draws Traders' Interest
</P>
<P>
   Wall Street is speculating that Kroger Co., the nation's largest
supermarket chain, will buy Fred Meyer, the owner of the Ralphs
Grocery chain in Southern California, in a move that would create
the first grocery chain spanning most of the nation.
</P>
<P>
   Fred Meyer's shares soared $3.6875, or 8 percent, to $49 on the
New York Stock Exchange on Friday. The stock has gained 27 percent
since Oct. 8. Kroger's shares fell $1.1875, to $48.75.
</P>
<P>
   When a Loss Could Be a Victory
</P>
<P>
   In the Byzantine world of telecommunications regulation, a loss
before the U.S. Supreme Court could turn out to be a victory for
local telephone companies when it comes to the prices long-distance
companies pay for access to local networks.
</P>
<P>
   Celebrating Every Man's Inner Guy
</P>
<P>
   Maxim, described by magazine consultants as the Playboy of the
1990s, is an unlikely success story at a time when the competition
in the men's magazine market is heated and most men's titles are
aiming for a sophisticated, advertiser-friendly audience. Instead
of encouraging sophistication, Maxim encourages its readers to
exist in a perpetual state of chest-thumping, girl-chasing,
adolescent jokesterism.
</P>
<P>
   Helping The World Spend Its Free Time
</P>
<P>
   Time Out, the listings magazine that began 30 years ago in a
London basement, has found its way in the world. The magazine's
name now adorns not just editions in London and New York, but also
franchises in Rome and Paris, along with an array of eating,
drinking and shopping guides.
</P>
<P>
   Perils of Covering Parent Company
</P>
<P>
   A shelved investigative report by an ABC News reporter about
hiring and safety practices at Disney World, the Florida theme park
owned by ABC's parent, Walt Disney, illustrates the thorny problems
journalists have in examining their own companies.
</P>
<P>
   Debate Over Census of Newsrooms
</P>
<P>
   As the governing board of the American Society of Newspaper
Editors prepares to meet in Miami on Monday, a proposal that women
be counted in the annual newsroom census of minority journalists
will most likely provoke a good deal of debate.
</P>
<P>
   Levi Ads Focus on Gay Consumers
</P>
<P>
   Intensifying its efforts to reach younger, more
fashion-conscious consumers, Levi Strauss, the nation's largest
apparel advertiser, is embarking on its most ambitious marketing
campaign aimed at gay men and lesbians. Levi Strauss is one of a
growing number of companies aiming sales pitches at gays and
lesbians for products from cars to computers.
</P>
<P>
   Congress Rewrites Copyright Law
</P>
<P>
   Congress moved to rewrite U.S. copyright law earlier this month
when it passed two hotly contested pieces of legislation concerning
extended protection for 20th-century cultural icons and
infringement online.
</P>
<P>
   Lawmakers finished work on a number of other bills affecting the
information technology industry, receiving high marks from the
industry despite failing to act on several pieces of legislation. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
