<HEADLINE>
OFF THE WALL
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By TOM HOFFARTH  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Nevada Boxing Commish: ``OK, Mr. Tyson, we've had a chance to
look at all the material _ the note from your wife, testimony from
Mr. Holyfield and all his kids, the psychological test results that
we successfully embarrassed you with and protected ourselves with
by making public ... and we have just one more question.''
</P>
<P>
   Mike Tyson: (grunt) ``What?''
</P>
<P>
   Commish: ``Are we out of our minds if we let you box here
again?''
</P>
<P>
   Tyson: (grunt) ``You'd be crazy not to.''
</P>
<P>
   Commish: ``Right answer. Pick up your license at Window 8.''
</P>
<P>
   So what about the rumors that Tyson is about to dump his
manager, Shelly Finkel , and allow Magic Johnson to run the show?
Imagine that...
</P>
<P>
   Magic tells the Washington Post that the 16-screen theater he
plans to build at the US Airways Arena outside of D.C. will cater
to the local residents and be a place where African-Americans ``get
the respect we deserve.''...
</P>
<P>
   After the stuff that came out of Knicks owner Dave Checketts
last week _ and the league isn't going to fine him for it _ you
don't even have to read between the lines here. If the owners can
help it, there's no season, pal...
</P>
<P>
   The Sterling Sunset Plaza office building on the Sunset Strip
doesn't have the billboard up any more with information about
Clippers season seats...
</P>
<P>
   Let us help the Clips decide which one of the finalists _ Eddie
Jordan, Jim Brewer or Chris Ford _ would best fit the coaching
shackles. All we need is a blindfold and one blunt dart. And Kurt
Rambis can throw it for us...
</P>
<P>
   The San Fran Chronicle reports that Raiders chief Al Davis has
his evil eye on possibly buying the Oakland A's...
</P>
<P>
   Pushing the issue for a new football stadium in Denver,
</P>
<P>
   Annabel Bowlen , wife of Broncos' owner Pat Bowlen , said it in
front of a rally held by the Citizens for a New Stadium that
included several team players' wives: ``This isn't about making Pat
and I richer... If we wanted to be richer, we could go to Los
Angeles and have blown out of here a long time ago and be 10 times
richer.''...
</P>
<P>
   No one wants the Dodgers' skipper job because Tom Lasorda
</P>
<P>
   will always be in the background getting his fingers in the
cake. And it hurts his feelings that people would say that. Maybe
the candidates have just been doing their homework before they
commit, and Bill Russell hasn't been giving the organization such a
ringing endorsement...
</P>
<P>
   Former Loyola Marymount baseball coach !arrow!Chris Smith
</P>
<P>
   has been added to the Dodgers organization as the area scout in
Texas...
</P>
<P>
   The Wall Street Journal reports that Nike has raised the salary
of entry-level factory workers in Indonesia from $23 a month to
about $28 a month, plus improved the quality and frequency of free
meals it serves at the plant. Merry Christmas...
</P>
<P>
   The Nashville Tennessean reports that Adidas reps ``went
ballistic'' and called USA Today to complain about a photo it ran
recently of Tennessee football coach Philip Fulmer , who was
wearing a Nike hat. Adidas pays up now to outfit the Vols; that
picture was a file photo before the '97 season, when Nike dressed
the team...
</P>
<P>
   The story that Sally Jenkins did on tennis stars Venus
</P>
<P>
   and Serena Williams in the current issue of Women's Sports &AMP;
Fitness magazine isn't meant to be sensationalized. But anytime you
quote the kids' dad, Richard Williams , the foundation usually
begins to shake. Jenkins even writes that the Williams trio are
``wiser and more principled than they have been given credit for.''
But she also includes this from papa Richard, whom she describes as
``a natural provocateur... alternately offensive and
charming''...and who might soon protest the following quote was
taken out of context:
</P>
<P>
   ``Most people thought, because I was in Compton, that I was
poor. Well, the only reason we moved to Compton was that I felt I
could buy more homes there than the Jews. They were buying up the
ghetto; I just wanted to give them a little competition...
</P>
<P>
   ``We were making tons of money. Everyone thought we were poor,
that tennis was our way out. It was not. I wanted to give the
Weinsteins, the Rubensteins, the I-forget-the-other-Steins,
competition. So I went over there and bought a few hundred, about a
hundred homes.''...
</P>
