<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Padres fans, team still love Leyritz
 &HT;    By I.J.Rosenberg
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ One of the big stories over the weekend here was Jim
Leyritz's return to the Big Apple. It was the Padres catcher, then
playing for the Yankees back in 1996, that turned around the World
Series with a Game 4 homer off Mark Wohlers.
</P>
<P>
   A hero then, they still love Leyritz here and he continues to
spend a lot of time with the fans as for both games he took the
subway from his hotel in midtown Manhattan instead of the cozy team
bus.
</P>
<P>
   ``I love it here,'' Leyritz said. ``People ask me whey I don't
take a taxi or limousine, but I like the subway. It makes me feel
like part of the city.''
</P>
<P>
   Under the weather again
</P>
<P>
   As he was in the postseason last year, Padres righthander Kevin
Brown is sick again. He got a head cold Friday and was immediately
put on antibiotics, pitching into the seventh inning Saturday
night. ``I never should have opened my mouth,'' Brown said. ``I
never should have said I was healthy. Someone's got a voodoo doll
working on me I guess. I was struggling all night. Physically, I
was not there. I have pitched in three World Series games and have
not been healthy yet.'' If the Padres are down in the series, Brown
will likely pitch in Game 4 on Tuesday on just three days' rest.''
</P>
<P>
   Braves getting ripped
</P>
<P>
   The national media continues its criticizing of the Braves, some
even calling for the job of manager Bobby Cox. On Sunday, Mike
Lupica of the New York Daily News wrote: ``Bobby Cox has done more
dumb squeezing than Bill Clinton. Cox has to go now, by the way. He
goes for a lot of reasons, but mostly because he only won once with
the Atlanta Braves in the 1990s and while winning once was more
than the Buffalo Bills ever did, it wasn't nearly enough.'' Lupica
goes on to add: ``The Braves are the ones that should hire Davey
Johnson.'' In the New York Times Sunday, a headline ran that said:
Braves May Have Rotation Fear, but in Playoffs It Isn't Enough.''
The story goes on to quote a general manager who said on the
condition of anonymity: ``They're not that good a club if you take
away their starting pitching. If you put their starting pitching on
several National League clubs, those clubs would be better.''
</P>
<P>
   Around the horn
</P>
<P>
   Yankees manager Joe Torre on Tino Martinez's grand slam in Game
1: Even with Tino struggling, we still got into the World Series.
We feel like we had something in the bank coming from them.'' ...
Before the opening game, Yankees rookie Ricky Ledee went up to
Torre and thanked him for putting him in the lineup. Ledee
responded with a 2-for-3 night and a walk and drove in two runs.
... Chuck Knobluach's homer Saturday was the first for a second
baseman in the Series since Tony Phillips went deep for Oakland in
1989. ... One more win and Yankees lefthander David Wells will set
a record for the postseason. He is 4-0. ... San Diego's Tony Gwynn
on the Yankee Stadium crowd: ``A Yankees crowd has chants that seem
like the whole crowd is in ... On Martinez's ball (slam), I could
barely hear myself breathing.'' ... Yankees legend Joe DiMaggio
from a hospital bed in Florida had this message for the current
Bombers: ``Win one for the Clipper.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
