<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOTEL-SHOOTING-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Three men shot execution-style at hotel
 &HT;    By Kathy Scruggs and Craig Schneider
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Three men were found shot to death execution-style
Sunday morning in a hotel room at the downtown Atlanta Hilton and
Towers just off Peachtree Street, police said.
</P>
<P>
   A hotel maid discovered the grisly scene in a 24th-floor room
about 8 a.m., police said. The three men had not been tied or
bound, but had been forced to the floor and shot _ probably at
point-blank range _ in the head, police said. The victims, two
white men and one African-American man, were killed between
midnight and 8 a.m., said Atlanta police Deputy Chief C.B. Jackson.
</P>
<P>
   ``At this point in the investigation, these murders do not
appear to be a random act,'' said Atlanta police Maj. Mickey Lloyd.
``The evidence on the scene apears to show that it was an
execution-style event. All indications are that this appeared to
have been a planned act. We're looking at narcotics as a possible
motive, but we're not closing the door on anything at this pont.''
</P>
<P>
   The killings occurred on the last day of a special promotion
called the Atlanta Homecoming Weekend, which was sponsored by the
Atlanta Convention and Visitors Bureau. The effort provided
discounts to local residents who stayed at downtown hotels.
</P>
<P>
   Spurgeon Richardson, president of the visitors bureau, said
tourism business likely won't be affected if the victims were
involved in illegal behavior such as drug-dealing.
</P>
<P>
   ``Meeting planners understand that while it's unfortunate,
drug-related crime can happen anywhere in the country,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The Hilton did its best to keep the triple slaying from
upsetting guests. Bellhops still greeted people at the front door
of the skyscraper on Cortland Street, though security was
increased. Reporters were escorted into one second-floor room. The
van that picked up the bodies did so behind a closed garage door.
Hotel operators still answered calls with, ``It's a great day at
Hilton Atlanta.''
</P>
<P>
   The killings happened on a night when the hotel was about 55
percent occupied, officials said. Guests ranged from computer
conventioneers from New Jersey, to postal workers visiting from
Texas, to a wildlife official from Kenya, here to study Zoo
Atlanta. People also were in town to see the Falcons-Saints game
and Georgia Tech's homecoming game Saturday against the University
of Virginia.
</P>
<P>
   Lloyd said the three dead men were not thought to be college
students or tourists in town for a sporting event.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to stress that this was not someone coming in off the
streets of Atlanta and killing three people,'' Lloyd said. ``It's a
terrible thing to have happened, but I don't believe all the
security in the world could have prevented it.
</P>
<P>
   ``The shootings were carried out in a very methodical manner.''
Lloyd said.
</P>
<P>
   Hotel security was quick to let guests know the deaths were not
believed to be random killings. Still, the triple murder shocked
many guests.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's kind of horrifying,'' said Tom Coppeto, 31, in town for a
computer conference.
</P>
<P>
   By Sunday evening, only one of the men has been tentatively
identified through the hotel registration, Lloyd said. His name has
not been released because his family has not been notified. Police
had not yet verified the names of the other two, Lloyd said.
</P>
<P>
   Detectives, along with the Georgia Bureau of Investigation's
crime scene technicians, were expected to investigate at the hotel
through the night. Autopsies on the three men will be conducted
today.
</P>
<P>
   Staff writer Alfred Charles contributed to this article.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
