<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Padres advantage becoming an obstacle
 &HT;    By I.J. Rosenberg
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ A shaky bullpen can destroy a team in the postseason.
Just ask the Braves.
</P>
<P>
   But what was supposed to be their big strength for the Padres is
quickly turning into their stumbling block.
</P>
<P>
   The problems for the San Diego pen started in the league
championship against Atlanta and came to a head in Game 1 of the
World Series Saturday when their relievers gave up a game-tying,
three-run home run to the Chuck Knoblauch in the seventh inning and
a what turned out to the game-winning runs on a grand slam to Tino
Martinez.
</P>
<P>
   This can turn a Series around quickly and certainly gave the
Yankees the momentum going into Game 2.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think last night was indicative of how I feel about my
bullpen,'' Padres manager Bruce Bochy said. ``I have a lot of
confidence in them. That is why we stuck with the guys that got us
here.''
</P>
<P>
   Some feel Bochy pulled starter Kevin Brown too early in Game 1
as Donnie Wall came in with one out and two runners on in the
seventh to give up the long ball to Knoblauch.
</P>
<P>
   ``Donne Wall, he was the guy that we brought in that kind of
situation,'' Bochy said. ``That is what we wanted to do for this
series. Dan Miceli normally pitches the eighth inning and (Randy)
Myers is there to help him out depending on who is coming up. So I
still have confidence in these guys.''
</P>
<P>
   One of San Diego's problems is Miceli appears to have a dead
arm.
</P>
<P>
   ``He did have a little arm fatigue there in the Atlanta
series,'' Bochy said. ``So instead of breaking him out last night
in that situation, Donne, you know, had felt good all along, so we
went with Donne there. But Dan is fine to go.''
</P>
<P>
   Another problem the Padres are having are getting to closer
Trevor Hoffman, who has been the one consistent force this
postseason for San Diego. But while the Padres bullpen continues to
stumble, New York relievers have almost been perfect, especially
closer Mariano Rivera, who know has xx saves this postseason and
has not allowed a run in xx innings.
</P>
<P>
   Bochy says it is very difficult to get something going against
Rivera. In Game 1, the righthander faced five hitters, getting four
outs and the other being an error by second baseman Chuck
Knoblauch.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is a challenge,'' Bochy said. ``He has got great stuff and
he is pitching very well now.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
