<HEADLINE>
CULTURE NOTES: THEATER STUDIOS IN NEW YORK; NEW WASHINGTON OPERA
SEASON; CLASSICAL FLUTIST TAKES UP JAZZ; LONDON THEATER OPENINGS 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ A new piece of the new 42nd Street begins to take
shape Monday, when Gov. George Pataki joins Marian Heiskell and
Cora Cahan, the chairwoman and president, respectively, of the New
42 Street Inc., in ceremonies at 1 p.m. at the New Victory Theater
to unveil the design and celebrate the start of construction of the
New 42nd Street Studios.
</P>
<P>
   Scheduled for completion in the winter of 2000, the 10-story,
84,000-square-foot, $22.9 million building will provide rehearsal
and office space and a 199-seat theater for rental to theater,
dance and music companies. Designed by Platt Byard Dovell
Architects, the studios, with multicolored lights playing across
its facade, are rising on the north side of 42nd Street between
Seventh and Eighth avenues.
</P>
<P>
   Curtain Raiser
</P>
<P>
   In Washington, new and old combine in a cultural highlight.
What's new is the Washington Opera season, beginning on Saturday
and including 74 performances of eight operas. What's old is the
opening attraction: Umberto Giordano's ``Fedora,'' which has
reached the age of 100 and will be performed for the first time by
the company when the curtain goes up in the Opera House at the
Kennedy Center for the Performing Arts.
</P>
<P>
   Adding to the luster are the stars, Mirella Freni as the
hot-tempered but vulnerable Russian princess Fedora, and Placido
Domingo as her love-hate object, Count Loris. Roberto Abbado will
make his Washington Opera debut as conductor, in a Teatro La Scala
production directed by David Edwards. Information: (202) 295-2400.
</P>
<P>
   New Venture
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ When a classical musician crosses into jazz, the
event is something akin to the legendary man biting dog. It's news.
In this case, the news revolves around the classical flutist Paula
Robison, who is taking up Brazilian jazz and the dance rhythms.
</P>
<P>
   At Cooper Union on Tuesday and Wednesday nights at 7, Ms.
Robison will join the Brazilian guitarists Romero Lubambo and
Sergio Brandao and the percussionist Cyro Baptista for ``Rio Days
and Rio Nights.'' Information: (212) 279-4200.
</P>
<P>
   Passions
</P>
<P>
   Stars are about to light up London's theatrical sky.
</P>
<P>
   At the Old Vic, David Suchet, television's Hercule Poirot, will
portray Mozart's conniving rival, Salieri, in Peter Hall's revival
of Peter Shaffer's ``Amadeus,'' opening on Wednesday. The play had
its premiere at the National Theater in 1979 and won eight Academy
Awards in its 1984 film incarnation. Information:
011-44-171-494-5372.
</P>
<P>
   At the National's Olivier Theater, Helen Mirren and Alan Rickman
will appear in Shakespeare's ``Antony and Cleopatra,'' opening
Wednesday for a run through Dec. 3. The National Theater has
performed this work only once before, in a 1979 staging by Hall.
Information: 011-44-171-452-3000.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
