<HEADER>
A3556 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOX-BOXCOL-LADN     10-18 1060
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOX-BOXCOL-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CANIZALES IS NO LIGHTWEIGHT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MICHAEL ROSENTHAL  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Orlando Canizales is one of the best fighters of all-time _ and
also one of the least-known.
</P>
<P>
   For six years, the hard-punching Texan ruled the bantamweight
division as no other little fighter in history, defending his IBF
championship a record 17 times between 1988 and 1994.
</P>
<P>
   At only 32 and still active, he should be cashing in on his past
deeds; he should be fighting for significant sums against
significant opponents before significant crowds. He should be
receiving respect.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, he is largely overlooked and struggling to get one more
championship fight.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yes, it's frustrating,'' said Canizales, whose tentative
opponent Thursday at the Country Club in Reseda is journeyman Tomas
Valdez. ``I'm just trying to stay active, fighting 10-rounders. And
eventually, I hope, something big will come up.''
</P>
<P>
   It's difficult to determine exactly how Canizales managed to
fade away even though he's still around. In part, he attributes it
to the fact he has never signed with a promoter. Instead, he has
been a free-lancer under guidance of longtime manager Bob Spagnola.
</P>
<P>
   There are also two losses in two years, to Wilfredo Vasquez for
the WBA junior featherweight title in 1995 and to Junior Jones the
following year.
</P>
<P>
   The biggest factor might be this: Aside from his accomplishments
in the ring, he's ordinary. He's reserved, he has never been in
trouble, his idea of fun is an evening at home. He has no gold
medals and he fights in the relatively anonymous lower-weight
classes. In other words, he has nothing on which to base an
effective marketing campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Canizales has an unusual background by boxing standards.
</P>
<P>
   He has three brothers, including former WBA bantamweight champ
Gaby Canizales. All three brothers have at least an associate
college degree and Orlando is following suit. In addition to his
training, he is taking college courses and plans to earn a degree
in psychology or sociology. He might work with at-risk kids.
</P>
<P>
   And, unlike so many fighters, he has invested his earnings
wisely, mostly in real estate. His desire to prolong his career at
an age when many lighter-weight fighters are long gone isn't about
money.
</P>
<P>
   However, it appears all this _ and the record number of defenses
_ isn't enough.
</P>
<P>
   Canizales (48-3-1, with 36 knockouts) has received some offers
to fight big-name opponents but hasn't been in the ring with one
since the Jones fight. And he hasn't fought on television for a
year and a half.
</P>
<P>
   ``You see another guy who doesn't have the resume Orlando has
getting offers twice as big as Orlando and you say ``(Forget)
that,' '' Spagnola said. ``I'm not going to let him do that. It's
ridiculous.''
</P>
<P>
   Canizales' mission at the moment is to land a fight with the
featherweight everyone in or near the division is clamoring to
meet: Prince Naseem Hamed, the flamboyant Briton who brings big
paydays to both parties.
</P>
<P>
   Canizales has been in the running but has received what Spagnola
believes are insulting offers from Hamed's handlers, roughly a
third of the $600,000 Kevin Kelly made and Wayne McCullough will
make when he meets Hamed on Oct. 31 in Atlantic City.
</P>
<P>
   Still, that's the one Canizales wants.
</P>
<P>
   Hamed is regarded as the best featherweight in the world. What
better challenge for a still-motivated, still-competitive champion
looking to make one more significant mark before he calls it quits?
</P>
<P>
   ``I made history in the sport of boxing,'' Canizales said. ``. .
.Now, I want to win a world title in another weight class. I want
to continue to make history.''
</P>
<P>
   __ Change of heart: Recently it seemed Evander Holyfield's
refusal to fight Lennox Lewis was because he didn't want to
jeopardize a potentially more-lucrative matchup with Mike Tyson.
</P>
<P>
   Now it appears he will take part in the title-unification bout
in February for the $20 million he rejected earlier this year. What
changed?
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps his view of Lewis, who looked ordinary and beatable
against Zeljko Mavrovic last month. Suddenly, the WBC champ didn't
seem to be as a big a risk as once thought. Of course, Lewis could
be thinking the same thing: Holyfield looked ordinary in his last
defense against Vaughn Beacon.
</P>
<P>
   Lewis is expected to sign his end of the contract today.
Holyfield signed on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Promoter Don King and HBO must reach an agreement for the fight
to take place.
</P>
<P>
   __ Tyson situation: It seems unlikely that the Nevada State
Athletic Commission will give Tyson a license today after his trial
for alleged assault in a Washington D.C. suburb was pushed back to
Dec. 1.
</P>
<P>
   Commissioners have said they want the D.C. incident to be
settled before they make a move.
</P>
<P>
   The hearing will be televised by U.S. Satellite Broadcasting
live at 9 a.m.
</P>
<P>
   __ Show canceled: One of boxing's most knowledgable and
passionate voices has been silenced. For now.
</P>
<P>
   Steve Kim has lost the call-in talk show on XTRA (690) he has
hosted for the past year and a half. He will remain on the air with
the station in a variety of roles: He'll do news updates,
on-the-field reports and more.
</P>
<P>
   ``I love the sport (boxing),'' said Kim, who also hosted a
similar show on KIEV for a year. ``. . .The reason they made the
decision was they don't want specialty shows. In certain ways, it's
a step up. They want to gear me more for the mainstream.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I plan to stay in boxing somehow, some way. I'll be
back.''
</P>
<P>
   __ Rabbit punches: Gabriel Ruelas will face talented but
light-punching John Brown on the undercard of the David Reid-James
Coker card Saturday in Atlantic City.
</P>
<P>
   Ruelas was scheduled to face James Leija, who had to pull out
because of a rib injury.
</P>
<P>
   The card is on HBO. . . .
</P>
<P>
   Mike Acre, the manager of Hector Camacho, said a bout with North
Hollywood's P.J. Goossen could take place in Pittsburgh or Los
Angeles on Dec. 4 or Dec. 11 if he can reach an agreement with
Univision.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's really still up in the air. I'll know more next week,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   Camacho faces Ken Sigurani on Friday in Chester, W. Virginia, on
ESPN2. . . .
</P>
<P>
   Carl Chancellor, the 7-foot, 425-pound heavyweight, probably
won't fight on the Country Club card as scheduled because of a hand
injury.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-18-98 2054EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
