<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Surprising Kentucky more than just Couch
 &HT;    By Mark Schlabach
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATHENS _ Last year, Kentucky served as homecoming fodder in
Georgia's turnaround season. The Bulldogs slowed down
record-setting quarterback Tim Couch, and held on for a 23-13 win
en route to a 10-2 record.
</P>
<P>
   Now, the Wildcats have apparently grown up under second-year
coach Hal Mumme, and enter Saturday's showdown against No. 11
Georgia in Lexington at 5-2, including a 2-2 mark in the SEC East.
</P>
<P>
   Kentucky will be riding the emotion from Saturday night's 39-36
victory at then-No. 21 LSU, perhaps the program's biggest win of
the 1990s and its first road upset of a ranked opponent since 1977.
</P>
<P>
   Mumme, the former coach at Valdosta State, set up the winning
score with characteristic trickery. On the Wildcats' final
possession, Mumme called two straight conservative running plays,
leaving the Tigers to believe they were headed for overtime.
</P>
<P>
   But Kentucky receiver Quentin McCord of LaGrange surprised LSU
with a 38-yard gain on an end-around, setting up Seth Hanson's
33-yard field goal as time expired. Kentucky outgained LSU in
rushing yards, 182-74, and held LSU's Kevin Faulk to 67 yards on 20
attempts.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought they came out and surprised LSU running the ball in
the first half,'' Georgia coach Jim Donnan said. ``It looked like
LSU was trying to stop their underneath (throws), and (Kentucky)
hit them with the quick hits and draws. If you can't pressure
Couch, he'll hurt you with the quick passes, and, of course, he'll
hurt you throwing deep.''
</P>
<P>
   The game is a matchup of two of the top quarterback prospects
from 1995. Georgia freshman Quincy Carter, who spent the last two
years playing minor-league baseball, and Couch were both Parade
All-Americans as high school seniors.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were two of the best (three) years ago and still are in
my opinion,'' Donnan said.
</P>
<P>
   Carter had two touchdowns in the 31-6 win over Vanderbilt, but
played only one quarter after injuring his non-throwing shoulder
against Tennessee. Carter should be at full strength.
</P>
<P>
   Donnan also said cornerback Glenn Ford, who returned a blocked
punt for a touchdown against Vandy before leaving in the second
half with a slight concussion, also should be ready.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
