<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-FALCONS-CHANDLER-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Chandler hurt, but no servere damage done to shoulder, ribs
 &HT;    By Curtis Bunn
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Well, at least it wasn't a concussion.
</P>
<P>
   That much could be said about Falcons quarterback Chris
Chandler's first injury of this season. Still, Chandler _ who was
carted off the field like a sack of bird seed too often last season
_ missed more than half of the Falcons' 31-23 victory against the
New Orleans Saints at the Georgia Dome.
</P>
<P>
   This time, Chandler left the field under his own power and with
his wits about him. He did, however, have bruised ribs and a
sprained left shoulder, injuries that thrust 44-year-old Steve
DeBerg into a significant role.
</P>
<P>
   The results of the tests were encouraging, on both counts.
X-rays showed no severe damage and Chandler said afterward he was
hopeful of being able to play next week against the New York Jets.
As for DeBerg, after an inauspicious few series, he found a comfort
zone and directed the club with aplomb in the final minutes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Steve did a good job in a tough situation,'' coach Dan Reeves
said.
</P>
<P>
   DeBerg said he had not seen significant time in the
regular-season since 1993.
</P>
<P>
   And it showed.
</P>
<P>
   He missed a handoff to Jamal Anderson in the third quarter and
was tackled in the end zone for a safety, cutting the Falcons'
advantage to 17-16 with 10:32 left.
</P>
<P>
   DeBerg said he did not feel comfortable until he got hit.
``After I got hit really hard, it was like, `Hmmm, that wasn't so
bad.'''
</P>
<P>
   Which is what Chandler hopes to be saying by midweek. His major
area of discomfort was in his rib cage under the shoulder blade.
Chandler was blindsided by 244-pound linebacker Mark Fields, who
slammed him into the turf. Chandler also had been hit hard on
several occasions in the first half.
</P>
<P>
   ``The field is in good condition,'' Chandler said. ``But the
downside is that the turf is rock hard.''
</P>
<P>
   DeBerg was solid much of the waning moments of the fourth
quarter. He was 7-for-10 for 60 yards. His third-down pass to
Terence Mathis _ which Mathis turned into a 26-yard gain to the
Saints' 17 _ was critical. Three plays later, DeBerg hit Bob
Christian on a short flare, and the fullback ran 8 yards for the
touchdown and 23-16 lead.
</P>
<P>
   ``That felt fantastic,'' DeBerg said. ``My responsibility is to
not lose the game. It took a while to get it together. Once I did,
I was solid. So this is very special.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
