<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-FALCONS-DEFENSE19-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Falcons' defense takes over at half
 &HT;    By Jeff Schultz
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ How many of these games have there been? The starting
quarterback goes down, the backup looks out of place in the huddle
(and without a baseball hat), and fans in the Georgia Dome wonder
if beating the traffic home would be more pleasing to the stomach
than watching the inevitable defensive collapse.
</P>
<P>
   How many? Too many.
</P>
<P>
   Except this time there was no defensive collapse.
</P>
<P>
   ``We talked about the situation at halftime,'' said Falcons
cornerback Ronnie Bradford. ``We knew our offense was not going to
run with the same efficiency with Steve (DeBerg). But we were still
ahead. It was up to us. If they don't score, they don't win.''
</P>
<P>
   We now present this atypical summary of a Falcons game: The
defense bailed out the offense. Overcoming some miscues in the
secondary, Atlanta's defense stuffed New Orleans' running game,
forced four New Orleans turnovers and held the Saints to one
second-half score (albeit an 82-yard touchdown pass) as the Falcons
held on for a 31-23 victory at the Dome.
</P>
<P>
   ``This just shows we've grown a lot as a defense,'' said
defensive tackle Travis Hall, whose play, along with that of Chuck
Smith and linebacker Cornelius Bennett, was key to holding the
Saints' running game to 1.9 yards per carry. ``We know now that we
can step up and play ferocious, vicious defense. I mean, we had
some serious ball-hawking out there. When you get four or five guys
flying to the ball, something is going to happen.''
</P>
<P>
   It had to take something big for the Falcons to finally win a
game without Chris Chandler, who left late in the second quarter
with a sprained left shoulder and bruised ribs. The play was
provided by Eugene Robinson with 10:37 left, when the free safety
picked off an errant pass by Billy Joe Tolliver and returned it 25
yards for a touchdown. It expanded Atlanta's led to 31-16 and,
well, allowed room for one more pratfall. With 3:19 left, Tolliver
ran out of the pocket and hit Keith Poole for an 82-yard score
after Poole beat rookie Elijah Williams.
</P>
<P>
   ``We took over the game on defense in the second half _
unfortunately, we still had that one play,'' defensive coordinator
Rich Brooks said.
</P>
<P>
   Robinson, who leads all active players with 50 career
interceptions, said the defense has made great strides, but, ``You
have to be able to sense when to put a team away. When everybody
senses that, that's when you win. When the defense is playing well,
like it did in the third quarter, it's contagious. ... You have
guys who are mediocre playing over their heads.''
</P>
<P>
   The Saints trailed 17-14 at halftime, but their only
third-quarter points came on a safety. Their first six possessions
resulted in: punt, fumble, fumble, punt, interception (Robinson's),
punt. New Orleans running back Lamar Smith was held to 13 yards on
seven carries in the second half. Tolliver, excluding the touchdown
to Poole, was 5-for-17 for 55 yards, one interception, one fumble
and one sack after halftime.
</P>
<P>
   ``The point we made to the players at halftime is, `The game is
in our hands,' '' Brooks said. ``We couldn't let them take the
lead. If they ever got the lead, it would've been a different
game.''
</P>
<P>
   And, likely, a different result.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
