A3572 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-FALCONS19-COX     10-18 0793
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-FALCONS19-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Falcons overcome Saints, but not without flaws
 &HT;    By Matt Winkeljohn
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ With first place in the NFC West hanging in the
balance, the biggest Georgia Dome crowd since a 1995 sellout
against Dallas was on hand Sunday as Atlanta Falcons coach Dan
Reeves saw some of his worst fears realized against the New Orleans
Saints.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, Jamal Anderson's record-tying fourth straight game
of 100 or more yards (132 on 25 carries) and a fourth-quarter
25-yard interception return for a touchdown by Falcons free safety
Eugene Robinson were the biggest factors in Atlanta's 31-23
victory.
</P>
<P>
   But it came at a steep price. Starting quarterback Chris
Chandler, who has helped keep the Falcons tied with San Francisco
atop the NFC West, left the game late in the second quarter with a
bruised left (non-throwing) shoulder and bruised ribs.
</P>
<P>
   There will be an additional examination today, but Reeves said,
``It doesn't look very good right now.'' Chandler is doubtful for
next Sunday's game against the Jets.
</P>
<P>
   After being slammed to the turf while being sacked from behind
by Saints linebacker Mark Fields, Chandler left the field for
medication and X-rays. He later was walking under his own power,
but that doesn't mean he's not seriously hurt.
</P>
<P>
   ``The X-rays didn't show any fracture or where it's chipped or
anything,'' he said. ``The rib under your shoulder blade, that's
where all the trouble is. I think it's just mainly the cartilage
and muscles in there that are sore. Hopefully, it'll be all right
by next week.''
</P>
<P>
   Chandler's replacement was 44-year-old Steve DeBerg, the NFL's
oldest player. He, like Chandler, completed 7-of-10 passes, but the
Falcons offense was dreadful the last couple minutes of the first
half, and all during a third quarter.
</P>
<P>
   When DeBerg muffed a handoff to Anderson on the Falcons' first
possession of the second half, he ended up taking a sack _ one of
five suffered by Atlanta _ and a safety with 10:32 left in the
third quarter.
</P>
<P>
   That pulled the Saints to within 17-16.
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta's offense was dreadful for the remainder of the quarter,
losing 15 yards in all, but the defense made up for it.
</P>
<P>
   Although they allowed New Orleans 322 yards, 146 came on
touchdown passes of 64 and 82 yards from two-time former Falcons QB
Billy Joe Tolliver to wide receiver Keith Poole.
</P>
<P>
   Just as important, the Saints (3-3) came in tied for second in
the NFL with a plus-seven turnover ratio and had not lost a fumble
all season. They lost three Sunday, two in the second half. Atlanta
didn't turn any fumbles into points, but two stopped Saints' drives
inside the Atlanta 35-yard line.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Atlanta didn't lose the ball once.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a huge win for us,'' Reeves said. ``I can't tell you
how pleased I am that we overcame some of the things that we did.''
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta scored 17 points in the first half on a 22-yard field
goal by Morten Andersen, a 31-yard touchdown run by Anderson, and a
45-yard touchdown pass from Chandler to wide receiver Tony Martin.
</P>
<P>
   The Falcons countered with a 5-yard touchdown run by Lamar Smith
and a 64-yard touchdown pass from Tolliver to Poole, who had
improvised a short route to get behind cornerback Ronnie Bradford.
</P>
<P>
   The safety was the only scoring the third quarter, but the
fourth quarter featured big plays.
</P>
<P>
   A sack by Falcons' defensive tackle Shane Dronett helped force a
New Orleans punt, and DeBerg's 26-yard pass to wide receiver
Terance Mathis moved the ball to the New Orleans' 18. A few plays
later, on third-and-one from the New Orleans' 8, DeBerg hit
Christian with a short pass, and he broke four tackles to score his
first touchdown of the season and to give Atlanta a 24-16 lead with
11:05 left.
</P>
<P>
   DeBerg said he got more comfortable as time went on, and his
teammates did most of the work.
</P>
<P>
   ``Chris Chandler makes a lot of plays on his own,'' he said.
``Chris Chandler can make plays I can't. I need help. I need the
defense playing good, the running game going good. I really think
those guys understand that, and their level of play rises.
Everything I'm living now is just amazing.''
</P>
<P>
   The Falcons added insurance minutes later. Backed up at his own
2 and facing third-and-17, Tolliver overthrew Andre Hastings, and
Robinson, the NFL's leading active interceptor with 50, returned
the interception for a touchdown.
</P>
<P>
   Poole got behind Williams for his second long touchdown, making
it 31-23 with 3:19 left, but the Saints failed to execute an onside
kick, and the Falcons ran out the clock behind Anderson's running.
</P>
<P>
   The Falcons distributed 60,774 tickets for the game.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
