<SLUG> BC-WOMEN'S-SHELTER-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MALE DIRECTOR OF BATTERED WOMEN'S SHELTER IS LET GO 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ANNE E. KORNBLUT  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Six months after a bitter ideological dispute ripped
through a prominent Cape Cod domestic violence agency, the central
controversy _ whether a man should run the place _ has been
resolved, at least for now.
</P>
<P>
   Richard Costa, the state's first male director of a battered
women's shelter, has been asked to leave Independence House by Nov.
13. Despite earlier accusations that the agency betrayed its
feminist roots by appointing a man, board chairwoman Christine
Kesten said his dismissal was unrelated to the public outcry, and
was, in fact, ``not an issue of sex at all.''
</P>
<P>
   But it may be a harbinger of further trouble.
</P>
<P>
   The state Department of Public Health announced last month the
cancellation of a $111,000 contract for rape counseling services at
the Hyannis-based agency, citing concerns over inadequate staffing
and the high turnover rate of employees.
</P>
<P>
   The state Department of Social Services also reviewed its
contract with Independence House recently, although Kesten said
that deal is still ``in place.''
</P>
<P>
   ``This agency has had a lot of history,'' Kesten said Sunday,
``and it all seems to have come to a head.''
</P>
<P>
   Marianne Milton, a board member who quit over Costa's hiring,
said the half-year ordeal had ``done so much damage to the
agency.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm just very sorry this had to happen,'' she said. ``I just
hope they are going to be able to find a direction.''
</P>
<P>
   Many members of the community and former board members admitted
some of the agency's troubles predated the recent flap. But it was,
by most accounts, Costa's appointment in May that underscored deep
rifts among those in charge of the $1 million-a-year domestic
violence operation, believed to be the largest on Cape Cod.
</P>
<P>
   Founded in the early 1980s as a grass-roots ``safe house'' for
battered women, Independence House blossomed into a large-scale
organization serving as many as 1,000 women a month with both its
shelter and its 24-hour counseling hotline.
</P>
<P>
   When Costa was appointed, it was with the idea that he would
serve as a business organizer and fund-raiser, a role made
necessary by the growing number of staff members and clients,
Kesten said at the time. Nearly 20 percent of the agency's budget
is dependent on outside fund-raising, board members said.
</P>
<P>
   But dissent began even before Costa was sitting in the
$45,000-a-year slot.
</P>
<P>
   Several board members complained that he lacked experience as a
hands-on counselor. The board's own president, Helen Goolishian,
argued that when a battered woman walks into a shelter, ``the last
thing she wants to see is a man.''
</P>
<P>
   Goolishian, along with three other board members, resigned after
Costa's appointment.
</P>
<P>
   Costa, while admitting that his presence split opinion on the
board of directors, insisted in an interview at the time that there
was no negative impact on the agency itself.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're all doing our jobs,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   On Oct. 8, after Costa's six-month probationary period ended,
the nine-member board of directors voted unanimously not to offer
him a full contract. It was a surprising about-face for the board,
which had vehemently supported Costa at the time of his
appointment; but, according to Kesten, ``it was a mutual
decision.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I think he would like to pursue other interests, too,'' she
said. ``I don't really want to go into every detail.''
</P>
<P>
   Attempts to reach Costa Sunday were unsuccessful.
</P>
<P>
   Peggy Wilbur, a former clinical director, has assumed the role
of interim director while a nationwide search is conducted to find
a permanent one _ and eventually, the board hopes, permanent
stability.
</P>
<P>
   ``You could fill a room with the people who are upset with
Independence House,'' said Gerry Garvey, executive director of the
neighboring New Bedford Women's Center. ``But you could fill a
stadium with women whose lives were saved by Independence House.
I'm feeling like, enough is enough.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
