<DOCNO> NYT19981018.0199 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-18 21:44 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3610 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CAMPAIGN-WELFARE-BOS &LR;      10-18 1380
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAMPAIGN-WELFARE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REFORM LAWS TEST GUBERNATORIAL CANDIDATES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SCOT LEHIGH  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ In six weeks, a central wrangling point of last week's
gubernatorial debate takes on a concrete reality, when as many as
6,000 of the state's welfare families hit the two-year aid limit.
</P>
<P>
   That adds urgency to a question that has bedeviled policy makers
for 25 years: What's the best way to move welfare recipients off
the rolls and into jobs that pay enough to support their families?
</P>
<P>
   Acting Governor Paul Cellucci, the Republican incumbent, accuses
Attorney General Scott Harshbarger, the Democratic nominee, of
wanting to weaken the state's law, which imposes a two-year time
limit on recipients and requires that some work 20 hours a week to
receive their benefits.
</P>
<P>
   Harshbarger says the law is overly rigid, and in the debate said
it reflected an ``anti-woman, anti-child'' bias by the acting
governor.
</P>
<P>
   Harshbarger would modify the law to let education and training
programs count toward the 20-hour-a-week requirement and to allow
more extensions beyond the two-year time limit.
</P>
<P>
   That difference reflects a longtime public-policy debate:
whether the best approach is to require recipients to work
immediately, even if in community service jobs, or to leave them
free to pursue education or training in the hope they will find
better jobs later.
</P>
<P>
   ``Education and training is important, but it is just no
substitute for a job,'' said Andy Antrobus, campaign spokesman for
Cellucci. ``Scott Harshbarger thinks it's OK for welfare recipients
to not have to work. Governor Cellucci thinks that welfare
recipients, just like everyone else, should have to work and seek
out that education and training in addition to their jobs, not
instead of their jobs.''
</P>
<P>
   Harshbarger says that Cellucci ignores the economic realities
facing welfare recipients. ``The fact that Paul Cellucci would turn
his back on women looking to learn new skills, provide for their
children, and move up the economic ladder _ and ignore the
recommendation of his hand-picked MassJobs Council _ speaks volumes
about his values and leadership,'' Harshbarger said.
</P>
<P>
   Results so far in other states suggest that a strong emphasis on
finding employment quickly has paid off _ but that rigid deadlines
can indeed be counterproductive.
</P>
<P>
   Cellucci and former governor William F. Weld made the work-first
approach the cornerstone of their welfare philosophy. And based on
raw numbers alone, that approach can claim some real successes.
</P>
<P>
   According to the Department of Transitional Assistance, the
number of families on Transitional Aid to Families with Dependent
Children, as AFDC is now called, has declined from 102,993 to
40,963 since the welfare reform law was passed in February 1995.
</P>
<P>
   About half of those who have left the rolls have found jobs, DTA
says.
</P>
<P>
   But at what level of pay?
</P>
<P>
   The average starting wage for welfare recipients who have
participated in some sort of education or training program is $7.77
an hour. That's $15,540 a year, assuming 50 40-hour work weeks. For
those who haven't gone through education and training, the average
falls to $7.10 an hour, or $14,200 per year.
</P>
<P>
   Those facts suggest education and training means a $1,340-a-year
boost, hiking average yearly wages by more than 9 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Deborah Harris, a staff attorney at the Massachusetts Law Reform
Institute, says a 35-hour week is more typical. If so, that means
education and training could make the difference between a yearly
wage of $12,425 _ more than $1,000 below the $13,650 poverty level
for a family of three _ and $13,597.
</P>
<P>
   Those are wages for people who have left the rolls before the
deadline.
</P>
<P>
   It remains to be seen what will happen with the members of the
time-limted group _ able-bodied recipients whose children are 2 or
older _ who have been unable to find work so far.
</P>
<P>
   Dick Powers, spokesman for DTA, says that based on the
experience in other states, DTA expects about half that group _
2,000 to 3,000 _ to apply for extensions. More will hit the
deadline each month thereafter.
</P>
<P>
   In a position paper released Thursday, Harshbarger said he would
``keep in place and enforce the two-year time limit for welfare.''
</P>
<P>
   But he also favors adding extensions, on a case-by-case basis,
for victims of domestic violence and recipients ``enrolled in
qualified education and training programs.''
</P>
<P>
   Although Cellucci blasted Harshbarger for favoring exceptions to
the two-year limit, last month DTA announced its own rules for
waiving the time limit.
</P>
<P>
   Those regulations allow extensions for six possible reasons,
including a recipient's recent work history, the availability of
job opportunities and child care, and their efforts to find work.
Harshbarger also backs those reasons for extensions, said spokesman
Dwight Robson.
</P>
<P>
   A second difference between the candidates is whether education
or training should count toward the 20-hour weekly work requirement
that able-bodied welfare recipients with school-age children must
comply with to receive benefits.
</P>
<P>
   There are 10,277 recipients covered by that requirement.
</P>
<P>
   Of that group, only 800 are also participating in any sort of
education or training program. With 44 percent of welfare
recipients lacking high school degrees, their champions say they
could significantly raise their earning potential through education
and training.
</P>
<P>
   DTA's own wage statistics support that contention.
</P>
<P>
   But Harris says that it can be just too difficult to fulfill the
weekly work requirement and also participate in a training program.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you are a low-income parent and you have school-age kids,
and you don't have a washer or a dryer, so you have to go to the
laundromat, and you have to spend time going to the food pantries
because your food stamps don't last the whole month, and you don't
have a car, so you have to spend a lot of time on public
transportation getting to and from work, there are just not enough
hours in the week to do both, unless you are a supermom,'' said
Harris.
</P>
<P>
   Oregon, whose welfare-to-work program has been hailed as one of
the nation's most successful by the widely respected Manpower
Demonstration Research Corp., doesn't have either a work
requirement or a hard deadline for recipients participating in the
job-search program.
</P>
<P>
   The philosophy there is that ``as long as people are doing what
we ask them to do, the state ought not to put an end to benefits,''
said James Neely, deputy administrator of Oregon's Adult and Family
Services Division.
</P>
<P>
   And though Oregon does put a priority on finding work, it offers
education and training to recipients who are having trouble finding
jobs.
</P>
<P>
   ``You really have to take an empirical approach, to look at why
people aren't being employed, and provide services to address it,''
said Neely.
</P>
<P>
   Nor has that program suffered as a result of its lack of rigid
deadlines. Neely says the welfare rolls have dropped from 44,000
families in March 1994 to about 17,500 today, a 60 percent
reduction that outstrips the decline of 40 percent under the
Massachusetts law.
</P>
<P>
   Last May, eight members of the MassJobs Council, noting that
only 2.8 percent of welfare recipients were taking adult education
classes, even though more than 40 percent lacked high school
educations, recommended counting education and training as part of
the work requirement.
</P>
<P>
   Cellucci responded by dismissing the advisory board members.
Harshbarger, by contrast, agreed with the recommendation.
</P>
<P>
   Each man can find some solace in the judgment of the leading
experts.
</P>
<P>
   In an August guest column in the Washington Post, Judith Gueron
and Amy Brown, president and senior operations associate at the
Manpower organization, which has studied welfare policy for 25
years, came down in favor of stressing that recipients find work
quickly _ but also allowing some flexibility for education and
training.
</P>
<P>
   ``The most successful programs our organization has studied have
used balanced approaches that emphasized the importance of getting
a job quickly but understood that some recipients need more than
just a resume and a push,'' they wrote.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
