<SLUG> BC-MIDEAST-INITIATIVE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BOGGED-DOWN PEACE TALKS EXTENDED INTO MONDAY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID L. MARCUS  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WYE MILLS, Md. _ President Clinton and Vice President Al Gore
ratcheted up the pressure on Israelis and Palestinians at a rural
Maryland retreat Sunday, but by nightfall the White House announced
that peace talks will have to be extended through Monday.
</P>
<P>
   In what was supposed to be the final day of a summit,
discussions bogged down over over a variety of security issues,
including whether Palestinians accused of terrorism will be
extradicted to Israel for trial.
</P>
<P>
   No agreements had been reached by nightfall, but the White House
hoped to avoid an embarrassing setback by forging an accord before
Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu and Palestinian leader
Yasser Arafat fly back to the Mideast.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton, who has already devoted the bulk of three days to the
summit, raised the stakes considerably by adding another day of
discussions.
</P>
<P>
   A blackout of details by the White House effectively kept the
most important parts of the negotiations secret. But officials
confirmed that Netanyahu and Arafat had not had a face-to-face
meeting or a phone conversation since Friday _ a sign that talks
were stagnating.
</P>
<P>
   On an afternoon when US aides asked to be informed periodically
of football scores, State Department spokesman James P. Rubin said
the discussions had entered the ``endgame.''
</P>
<P>
   The surreal day at the 1,000-acre conference center included
accounts of Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat taking a bicycle ride
in full military regalia.
</P>
<P>
   For his part, Clinton shuttled on foot between his two guests
and took a solitary 20-minute stroll by the Wye River.
</P>
<P>
   ``We believe it's in the best interest of the peace process to
continue the discussions,'' White House spokesman Joe Lockhart
said.
</P>
<P>
   He added that Clinton has not decided whether he will visit
Monday. ``The work is continuing at a good pace,'' Rubin said.
</P>
<P>
   The White House had announced last week that Clinton would be on
call over the weekend and had not mentioned the possibility of
Gore's involvement in the talks. Clinton's helicopter landed at the
retreat at 11:30 a.m., shortly after Gore arrived. Clinton and Gore
climbed into the back of a Chevy Suburban with National Security
Adviser Sandy Berger. All wore casual clothes.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton and Gore met with Israel Defense Minister Yitzhak
Mordechai and the new, hard-line foreign minister Ariel Sharon for
25 minutes, then met for lunch with Netanyahu and his top aides for
an hour and 40 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   After an hour meeting with Arafat, Clinton had dinner with his
staff, then met separately with Arafat and Netanyahu again.
</P>
<P>
   Secretary of State Madeleine K. Albright planned to stay over
last night at the Wye center, where Netanyahu and Arafat are
encamped just one-third of a mile apart from each other.
</P>
<P>
   The meetings might even be extended again. One of the
indications was a rumor that the caterers had been told to stay
until Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   The main subject of the talks _ an Israeli withdrawal from 13
percent more of the West Bank _ appears relatively simple, but it
goes to the heart of emotional issues for both sides. For
Palestinians, the point is getting land, and eventually an
independent state. For Israelis, the issue is security _ keeping
Palestinians to their promises to crack down on terrorists.
</P>
<P>
   Israeli officials have made clear that they will make
concessions to Arafat only after getting solid agreements that
Palestinians will cooperate with American and Israeli officials in
pursuing terrorists.
</P>
<P>
   These difficult talks are a prelude to ``permanent status''
negotiations over water rights, the boundaries of Jerusalem, and
other thorny issues.
</P>
<P>
   CIA director George Tenet and top US intelligence officials were
said to be at the compound over the weekend, along with Clinton's
Mideast negotiating team.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even if the president succeeds out at Wye, it doesn't mean the
Mideast policy is a success,'' said Richard Haass, director of
foreign policy studies at the Brookings Institution, a Washington
think tank. ``The big issues still remain.''
</P>
<P>
   The State Department continued to dampen expectations of a major
agreement. ``Wye is not Camp David,'' Rubin said in an allusion to
former President Jimmy Carter's breakthrough after 13 intensive
days of talks between Israelis and Egyptians.
</P>
<P>
   These talks, coming just 2 1/2 weeks before US congressional
elections, are giving Clinton a chance to showcase his diplomatic
skills. But he faces great obstacles, including an Israeli prime
minister and foreign minister who pride themselves on being tough
on terrorists.
</P>
<P>
   The talks also come amid conflicting reports about the health of
Jordan's King Hussein, who is being treated for cancer at the Mayo
Clinic in Minnesota. Hussein, who consults often with US officials,
has been a strong force in pushing Israelis and Palestinians to
meet.
</P>
<P>
   The State Department fanned the speculation about Hussein's
condition by issuing a statement that seemed to imply that his
death would not set back the peace process. The statement also
noted that Albright had called Hussein as well as his brother,
Crown Prince Hassan.
</P>
<P>
   ``King Hussein has been very open about his battle with
cancer,'' the statement said. ``The United States commitment to
Jordan is iron-clad, based on our deep, long-standing, shared
interest in regional peace and stability.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
