<HEADLINE>
JENNY, JENNY, WHO CAN I TURN TO?
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By TOM HOFFARTH  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Thrashing about, trying to catch a wave:
</P>
<P>
   __ The Unofficial Jenny McCarthy Website
(http://www.jenny-mccarthy.com/ ), one of dozens dedicated to the
former actress, will soon be able to keep you abreast of the ABL's
Chicago Condors by posting their schedule. Why? 'Cause Jenny's
younger sister, Joanne, is on the roster....
</P>
<P>
   __ If your local 7-Eleven has run out of the latest
crank-'em-out bios on Mark McGwire and Sammy Sosa ($4.99 each,
Archway Paperback, published by Pocket Books, a division of Simon &AMP;
Schuster), order them direct (soon, if not today) from the
company's Web site (http://www.simonsayskids.com).
</P>
<P>
   If the Sosa book seems twice as thick, it's because it is. Flip
it over, and the 141-page story is translated into Spanish _ muy
bueno for kids trying to learn a second language....
</P>
<P>
   __ Your pals at Broadcast.com have hooked up with a Las Vegas TV
station to deliver crisp, clear Internet access to today's Mike
Tyson relicensing hearing before the Nevada State Athletic
Commission. Starting at 9 a.m., go to either the Broadcast.com site
(http://www.broadcast.com/news/tysonhearings/) or the KLAS-TV site
(http://www.klas-tv.com) and turn the speakers down real low on
your PC. . . .
</P>
<P>
   __ Because the official World Series site just isn't enough, Fox
Sports Online has teamed up with Yahoo! Sports to offer its own
coverage (http://foxsports.yahoo.com).
</P>
<P>
   It has most of the standard pitch-by-pitch stuff that's on the
MLB site (http://www.worldseries.com) with a lot more opinion from
opinionated writers across the country. . . .
</P>
<P>
   __ The Series material on ESPN SportsZone
(http://espn.sportszone.com
</P>
<P>
   lb
</P>
<P>
   layoffs/index.html) is also pretty thorough with Peter Gammons,
Kevin Kennedy and Dave Campbell. . . .
</P>
<P>
   __ Yahoo! also recently signed for a reported $12 million with
Major League Soccer to be the ``Official Internet Navigational
Guide'' for the league through 2002. It is the first time the
phrase Yahoo! and MLS have appeared in the same sentence. . . .
</P>
<P>
   __ A couple of listings on the ``Cool Jobs'' site
(http://www.cooljobs.com &QL; 
ist) are how to apply for a non-factory-assembly-worker position at
Nike (http://www.NikeBiz.com/), what it takes to be a Dallas
Cowboys cheerleader
(http://www.dallascowboys.com/cheerleaders/auditions/audreq.html)
and where to go if your goal is to be a Zamboni driver
(http://www.geocities.com/Colosseum/Field/9043/).
</P>
</TEXT>
