</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NOBEL-ADAMS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SINN FEIN LEADER `DELIGHTED' OVER IRISH HONOR 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVEN WILMSEN  
 AND CAROLINE COLE  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ In one of his first public engagements since being
passed over for the Nobel Peace Prize, Sinn Fein leader Gerry Adams
said he is at least ``delighted the prize went to Ireland.''
</P>
<P>
   ``So many people have asked me if I'm disappointed that I'm
beginning to wonder if I ought to be,'' he said Sunday at a
breakfast gathering in downtown Boston.
</P>
<P>
   ``But the peace process isn't about any of the players,'' he
said. ``It's about our children. It's about new beginnings.''
</P>
<P>
   He praised two winners of the prize, who were announced Friday.
They were David Trimble, the one-time Protestant hard-liner who
refused to shake Adams's hand in public, and John Hume, the
Catholic leader of the Social Democratic and Labor Party who long
preached nonviolence and coaxed Adams into mainstream politics.
</P>
<P>
   Many had thought that if a Northern Ireland prize were shared,
it would be three ways, including Adams. Adams has come to reject
the use of force to achieve the Catholic nationalists' goal of a
united Ireland. But the Nobel committee evidently considered
Adams's history to be too contentious. Adams said not sharing the
prize is inconsequential to the larger goal of a ``just and lasting
peace'' forged with politics, not guns.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want to live in friendship and harmony with our unionist,
with our Protestant neighbors, one not better than the other,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   On the last day of a weeklong US speaking tour that also took
him to New York and Pennsylvania, Adams said he is trying to
reawaken American interest in completing the Good Friday political
settlement.
</P>
<P>
   The agreement, signed April 10, opened the possibility of
lasting stability in a province ravaged by sectarian violence for
30 years, he said at a second engagement in Lawrence. But it is
merely a beginning.
</P>
<P>
   ``The worst thing Irish Americans here could conclude is that
the struggle is over,'' he said. ``The awfulness of what happened
over the summer is a reminder to all that the difficulties
continue.''
</P>
<P>
   In August, 29 people were killed and 370 injured in a bombing in
Omagh for which Catholic extremists in a breakaway IRA faction
claimed responsibility. It was the deadliest terrorist attack in
Irish history. In July, three Catholic boys were killed in a
firebombing attributed to Protestant extremists in Ballymoney.
</P>
<P>
   Americans remain a crucial force in the ongoing process of
hammering out a new government, much of which must be completed by
Oct. 31 under the political settlement, and in establishing stable,
uncorrupt institutions such as a police force, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have been able to change US policy in the White House,''
he said, noting the importance individual Irish-Americans played in
lobbying to reverse government opposition to visas for Sinn Fein
members.
</P>
<P>
   Adams said his visa has allowed him to present the Sinn Fein
agenda to Americans in his own words.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
