u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MICROSOFT-SUIT-BOS &LR;      10-18 1715
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MICROSOFT-SUIT-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JUSTICE DEPARTMENT SET TO TAKE ON COMPUTER GIANT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By AARON ZITNER  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Computers have gotten less expensive and easier to
use. Software to browse the Internet is free. America is a
high-tech haven, with new products and new jobs created every day.
</P>
<P>
   And yet the Department of Justice is scheduled on Monday to
start presenting evidence in federal court that consumers would
have it even better were it not for illegal business practices of
the world's wealthiest man, Bill Gates, and his admired, feared,
and fabulously successful software company, Microsoft Corp.
</P>
<P>
   It is billed as the biggest antitrust case since the government
broke up AT&AMP;T Corp. in 1984, and some analysts say it could reshape
the economy as profoundly as the 1911 breakup of John D.
Rockefeller's Standard Oil Co. If the government wins a broad
victory, US v. Microsoft Corp. could do more than pare back the
Redmond, Wash., company's presence on the world's desktops. It
could limit the muscle that Microsoft is using to push its way into
the lucrative markets of the future: on-line banking, Internet
commerce, interactive television.
</P>
<P>
   The case will turn on technical questions about software
development, as well as interpretations of Microsoft memos and
business meetings in which, the government says, the company abused
its monopoly power when dealing with business partners and
competitors.
</P>
<P>
   But underlying the evidence will be a basic question of
philosophy: Given that the US software industry constantly makes
better products for less money, how much should the government
interfere?
</P>
<P>
   ``Supposing Microsoft does have market power, do you want to
give it a lot of freedom or have more government intervention?''
asked Eleanor Fox, an antitrust specialist at the New York
University School of Law. ``There is an argument that the best way
to advance technology is to leave highly progressive, inventive
companies alone.''
</P>
<P>
   ``You don't want attorneys and legislators trying to set
technical standards,'' said Donald DePalma, principal analyst at
Forrester Research Inc. in Cambridge.
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, trimming back Microsoft's power might allow
other companies to thrive and compete in parts of the technology
world that it now dominates. ``I believe Microsoft is too powerful
and should be broken up into separate businesses,'' said John
Cullinane, the Boston software marketing pioneer whose Cullinet
Software Inc. became the first software firm listed on the New York
Stock Exchange.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft's power comes from the popularity of its Windows
product, a type of software called an operating system. Operating
systems control the basic functions of computers, such as storing
data, retrieving files, and helping the computer run spreadsheets,
games, word processors, or other ``applications'' programs.
</P>
<P>
   Windows powers about 90 percent of all personal computers, and
nearly every company that makes PCs wants the right to sell
Windows. Nearly every company that develops games, spreadsheets, or
other applications wants access to the latest version of Windows,
before it hits the market, so it can get an early jump on designing
its products. For all of these companies, good relations with
Microsoft, which also has a significant presence in applications
software, are essential _ and often delicate.
</P>
<P>
   ``He who controls the operating system controls the world of
computing,'' said Cullinane.
</P>
<P>
   The government says Microsoft took advantage of this power to
bully other companies into helping it gain a leading position in
other businesses, such as the market for Internet browser software
used to view material on the World Wide Web. It is not illegal to
run a monopoly. It is illegal for a company to use its monopoly to
push its way into new businesses.
</P>
<P>
   One charge likely to arise is that Microsoft tried to coerce
Compaq Computer Corp. into abandoning a plan to load its computers
with a browser made by Netscape Communications Corp., the chief
competitor to Microsoft's own browser. Microsoft's alleged leverage
was a threat to withdraw Compaq's license to sell Windows with its
computers, which if carried out would have made Compaq PCs
unattractive to consumers.
</P>
<P>
   The trial may also raise claims that Microsoft illegally tried
to divide the browser market with Netscape, to induce Intel Corp.
to abandon a software project, and to persuade Apple Computer Co.
to change a business plan. Microsoft is vigorously contesting all
charges and says the government has taken internal memos and
descriptions of meetings out of context.
</P>
<P>
   The government faces significant hurdles in making its case. To
begin with, it must show that Windows gives Microsoft a monopoly
hold on the market for operating systems.
</P>
<P>
   That might seem easy. But Microsoft will argue that its 90
percent market share does not necessarily give it monopoly powers.
Consumers can choose computers powered by Apple's operating system,
or Unix and OS/2, among others. That they choose not to does not in
itself make Microsoft a monopolist, the company will say.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, economists hired by Microsoft argue that to have true
monopoly power, a company must be able to raise prices without fear
of backlash from consumers. A monopolist also has the luxury of
refusing to make the investment needed to improve its product. In a
true monopoly, consumers would not have the option of going
elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   But at about $50 per copy of Windows, Microsoft charges less
than 5 percent of what a firm with monopoly power would charge,
claim Bernard Reddy, Davis Evans, and Albert Nichols of National
Economic Research Associates Inc. in Cambridge. Moreover, they said
in a recent paper, Microsoft is under relentless pressure to
improve Windows.
</P>
<P>
   The reason, they said, is that Microsoft faces the threat of
competition, from giants like IBM Corp. and from unknown newcomers.
Fifteen-year-old boys have developed winning software using little
more than a single computer, and their products can be distributed
easily over the Internet. ``There are no high barriers to entry in
the PC software market,'' said David Mills, a University of
Virginia economist working on a Microsoft contract. ``You need only
smart people and venture capital.''
</P>
<P>
   If the government is able to prove that Microsoft is indeed a
monopoly, it faces the additional burden of showing that Microsoft
used its monopoly power illegally in inducing Apple, Intel,
Netscape, or others to take actions that benefited Microsoft.
</P>
<P>
   The government also faces a test in the court of public opinion.
Now 24 years old, Microsoft is among only a handful of companies to
have dominated a key industry so completely, and so quickly. For a
short while this year, it passed General Electric Co. to claim the
highest stock market value of any company in America, though
Microsoft has one-sixth the sales of GE and one-10th the employees.
</P>
<P>
   Americans seem to like this kind of success. One recent survey,
by US News &AMP; World Report, found that 80 percent of Americans have
a favorable impression of Microsoft and 73 percent have a favorable
impression of Bill Gates. The survey also found that more people
think the government's antitrust suit is a bad idea than a good
idea.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, the government faces a decidedly mixed history of
successful outcomes in technology antitrust cases. A suit 30 years
ago against IBM dragged on for nearly 13 years, including six years
of trial, before the government dropped it. It entailed 2,500
depositions, 66 million pages of evidence, and 974 trial witnesses,
according to the trade paper Computerworld.
</P>
<P>
   Judge Thomas Penfield Jackson has already set rules to make sure
the Microsoft case is no repeat of the IBM suit. Each side is
limited to 12 witnesses and several rebuttal witnesses, and all
direct testimony has been submitted in writing in advance of the
trial. In the courtroom, the lawyers will only cross-examine
witnesses. It could all be wrapped up within two months.
</P>
<P>
   Top officials from Microsoft, Netscape, Apple, Intel, America
Online Inc., and other leading high-tech firms are scheduled to
testify. Gates is not expected to appear, though his videotaped
deposition may be played.
</P>
<P>
   The government has not laid out all of the remedies it will seek
if it wins the case. It might try to force Microsoft to refashion
Windows so that it includes the browser made by its rival,
Netscape. On the more extreme end, it might try to break
Microsoft's operating system division into a separate company, the
way AT&AMP;T in 1984 split into a long-distance company and seven
regional Baby Bells. But a breakup effort is considered unlikely.
</P>
<P>
   Cullinane suggested another idea: ``From a practical viewpoint,
(Microsoft's) operating systems should be in the public domain,
thus making it possible for other companies to compete to make the
best Windows product,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Even if Microsoft wins, it may ultimately have a lot to lose.
The government case could make it easier for private firms to bring
their own antitrust actions. And Senator John F. Kerry has already
urged his colleagues to follow the suit with an eye toward passing
tougher antitrust laws.
</P>
<P>
   The trial ``may force Congress to examine whether existing
antitrust law sufficiently addresses market abuses in the new
digital age,'' Kerry said in a written statement last week. The
case may ``force Congress to consider new and important consumer
protection and market dominance issues.''
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft said Friday that there are no active settlement talks
under way, suggesting oral arguments will in fact begin  &UR; today &LR; , in
the same federal court building that housed the Monica Lewinsky
grand jury and where government antitrust lawyers recently blocked
a Massachusetts company, Staples Inc., from merging with Office
Depot Inc. of Delray Beach, Fla.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is just Chapter 1 of this case,'' said Brad Smith,
Microsoft's second-ranking lawyer. ``It's too early to know, but
it's certainly possible that we'll see this case go to the Court of
Appeals and possibly the Supreme Court. We're probably looking at a
case that has one year, or two or three years, to run before it
ends.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
