r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLINTON-POLLS-2TAKES-     10-18 0967
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-POLLS-2TAKES-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
POLLS SHOW AMERICA IS THE LAND OF THE GREAT DIVIDE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RICK MONTGOMERY  
 c. 1998 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ An uncommonly quiet week on the front lines
of the White House sex scandal left the media with little to report
but another round of polling. And the latest batch of numbers shows
what the last batch showed and the batch before that.
</P>
<P>
   Americans aren't budging. By some measures they haven't budged
in nine months.
</P>
<P>
   Roughly seven of 10 Republicans want President Clinton out of
office, the sooner the better, and seven of 10 Democrats won't
stand for it _ period, end of story. ``Independent'' voters say
they're fed up with the bickering, really fed up, but that's not
stopping Congress from grinding through the impeachment process.
</P>
<P>
   This is America, land of the Great Divide.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't think of a time when politics has been this
polarized,'' said Mike Lux, a lobbyist for People for the American
Way. The liberal organization has just released a TV commercial
urging Congress to ``Move On'' past Clinton's alleged obstruction
of justice in the Monica Lewinsky matter.
</P>
<P>
   ``It keeps building and building,'' Lux said of the chasm.
``It's unbelievable. Each side is as vehement as the other. The
whole thing makes you worry about the state of our democracy,
whether we can ever get together.''
</P>
<P>
   The cleaving of the public conscience can be painful, said Pete
Hutchison of the Kansas City-based Landmark Legal Foundation, which
has fought Clinton in court.
</P>
<P>
   ``No pain, no gain,'' he said, however. ``I think we come out of
these defining moments strengthened.''
</P>
<P>
   How divisive is this issue? Consumer activist Ralph Nader argues
that it can be settled only by a nationwide referendum for the
purpose of guiding Congress: Should Clinton stay or go?
</P>
<P>
   How inflammatory is this issue? More than 3,000 people at a
Christian Coalition convention last month sprung to their feet and
cheered lustily at coalition founder Pat Robertson's suggestion
that Clinton go directly to jail.
</P>
<P>
   How prickly is this issue? Many candidates for Congress are
trying their best to avoid it.
</P>
<P>
   At a luncheon Thursday in Kansas City, U.S. Sen. Kit Bond of
Missouri did not mention Clinton's problems, not even in jest,
during a 20-minute address before a friendly crowd. The Republican
took a halfhearted swing at the impeachment question only after an
audience member raised it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Where that goes, nobody knows,'' said Bond, who could be among
the 100 senators deciding the president's fate if Clinton is
impeached. ``That could be a long, long process.''
</P>
<P>
   Since news broke in January of Clinton's relationship with
Lewinsky, public opinion has remained fairly fixed.
</P>
<P>
   ``People have dug themselves in,'' said John Kohut, senior
editor of the ``Rothenberg Political Report,'' a Washington
newsletter.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's the 30 percent of people who always hated Clinton.
There's the 30 percent who always liked him and the remaining 40
percent who want this scandal to be over with,'' Kohut said. ``And
then you have this parallel universe in Congress, where the
ignition of impreachment has been started.
</P>
<P>
   ``This car's going to move. It's supposed to move, because this
is the constitutional process for judging impeachable offenses.
Nobody can stop this car.''
</P>
<P>
   If the ride is rough, the president's adversaries say, the
nation must hold on tight and adhere to the rule that no person _
not even the president _ is above the law.
</P>
<P>
   ``Here's the question that makes everything so heated,'' said
Hutchison. ``Where should our moral compass take us? That segment
of the baby-boom generation that Clinton embodies, morally _ is
that what we want to be as a nation?''
</P>
<P>
   Yet it's that wielding of some moral yardstick that makes so
many in the country seethe.
</P>
<P>
   ``Democrats, including myself, aren't happy with Bill Clinton,''
said lobbyist Lux, ``but we feel intensely the Republicans are
creating a constitutional crisis based on things that many great
presidents have done.''
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps this crisis must be played out, said Ellen Fitzpatrick,
associate professor of history at the University of New Hampshire.
For every issue that has driven a wedge through Washington _ from
slavery to McCarthyism to Watergate _ history has used the conflict
to define important changes in culture.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'd not be having this debate if the public wasn't fascinated
by this story,'' Fitzpatrick said. ``A kind of synergy has brought
us to this point. This conflict serves the needs of the political
parties, it serves the needs and interests of the mass media and,
in some ways, it serves the needs and interests of a divided
public.
</P>
<P>
   ``The argument that this will do irreparable damage to our
nation is nonsense.''
</P>
<P>
   If the bulk of America continues to argue that Clinton should
stay in office, Fitzpatrick predicted, ``this train ultimately will
lose its steam.''
</P>
<P>
   In contrast to the public's loyal _ stubborn? _ support for
Clinton, President Nixon's approval ratings steadily eroded as the
Watergate investigation and congressional hearings moved ahead.
</P>
<P>
   In June 1973, for example, a Gallup Poll found 44 percent of
Americans approving of Nixon's job performance. That fell to 31
percent by the end of the year and to 24 percent in the weeks
before Nixon resigned in the summer of 1974.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's job approval ratings so far have shown no such
slippage.
</P>
<P>
   ``In fact, these have been the best nine months of his
presidency,'' said poll-tracker Karlyn Bowman of the American
Enterprise Institute. ``Never has his rating been this high for
this long.''
</P>
<P>
   Below the surface, however, Americans appear to be increasingly
troubled by the character of their leader. MORE
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
