<HEADLINE>
FEARS HAVE OUTRUN THE FACTS OF E-COMMERCE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JERRY HEASTER  
 c. 1998 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNDATED: Numbers sometimes aren't what they seem, especially
when they're presented in the absence of any meaningful context.
</P>
<P>
   An example of this occurred in a recent Page One story in The
Kansas City Star exploring the relative merits of sales taxes
compared with property taxes as sources of money for local
governments. The point of the story was that excessive reliance on
sales taxes might prove chancy if the economy goes into recession.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, the story noted, the problem could be exacerbated if
Internet shopping continues to grow because Internet transactions
escape sales taxes. This point was buttressed by an estimate that
Internet shopping this year would total $6 billion and rise to $40
billion in a few years.
</P>
<P>
   Some readers no doubt considered these numbers a big deal, and
thus logically assigned the Internet a lot more significance than
it deserves as a domestic and global commercial hub. In the
process, the myth of the Internet's growing commercial effect got
another coat of luster it didn't deserve.
</P>
<P>
   Granted, any number with a billion behind it involves a huge
amount of money. Even so, in the context of total personal
consumption, $6 billion in sales is statistically irrelevant in the
U.S. economy. By extension, the Internet as a sales hub is also
irrelevant for purposes of trying to make a point about the
economy.
</P>
<P>
   Look at it this way: The personal consumption component of the
gross domestic product reached an annual rate of $5.13 trillion in
this year's second quarter. This is an inflation-adjusted number
measured in 1992 dollars. At this rate, even without adjusting for
inflation, $6 billion will represent only a smidgen more than
one-tenth of 1 percent of all U.S. consumer activity in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   In the unlikely event the economy fails to expand during the
next few years, the Internet's share of the personal consumption
GDP component still will remain well under 1 percent even if
on-line shopping expands as fast as anticipated.
</P>
<P>
   A recent story in The Wall Street Journal, in fact,
characterized the Internet as an ``economic pipsqueak.'' It noted
an estimate by the Organization for Economic Cooperation and
Development that put worldwide electronic commerce last year at $26
billion and expected it to reach $1 trillion by 2005. The story
cautioned, though, that such numbers also need to be put in
context, because $26 billion was only 0.5 percent of total retail
sales for the organization's seven biggest economies.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even at $1 trillion,'' the article said, ``e-commerce would
amount to less than the current annual sales that flow from direct
marketing in the United States using mail, telephone and
newspapers.''
</P>
<P>
   This prompted an economics professor at Maastricht University to
observe that ``there is no other area of technological change with
such a discrepancy between the actual phenomenon and what people,
policy-makers and businessmen believe and expect from the future.''
</P>
<P>
   While conceding that the Internet has transformed niche markets
such as book sales, many economists don't expect electronic
commerce to radically alter the way consumers buy ``the vast
majority of their goods and services.''
</P>
<P>
   The bottom line? All revenue streams are often unpredictable,
whether you're running a private or government enterprise.
Everybody knows that. Meanwhile, the Internet isn't all that big a
deal in the world of business and commerce. Not enough people know
that.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-18-98 2209EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
