<SLUG> BC-CAREERS-COLUMN-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JOB SEARCH GETS TOUGHER WITH AGE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DIANE STAFFORD  
 c. 1998 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNDATED: The most frustrated job hunters I see are middle-aged
to older professionals with strong work histories. At career fairs
and in personal contacts, they tell the same story:
</P>
<P>
   They were laid off. They have been out of work for months. They
sometimes have good interviews, but no job offers. They believe
they are victims of age discrimination.
</P>
<P>
   They probably are. I warn, though, it might be more than age
stopping job offers. They may be asking to earn more than hirers
want to pay.
</P>
<P>
   Two other reasons come from David Opton, executive director of
Exec-U-Net, an executive career information company.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a preconceived notion that an older candidate is not
active and up to date in skills enough,'' Opton said. He added that
younger managers ``also fear that an older employee will have a
hard time working for a boss younger than themselves.''
</P>
<P>
   His organization surveyed 400 executives about their recent job
searches and found _ no surprise _ the number of interviews
declined and job searches lengthened with age.
</P>
<P>
   Compared to 35- to 40-year old executives, it took 18 percent
longer for 41- to 45-year-olds to find new positions; 24 percent
longer for 46- to 50-year-olds; 44 percent longer for 51- to
55-year-olds, and 66 percent longer for 56- to 60-year-olds.
</P>
<P>
   Out-of-work executives took an average of 9.2 months and 10.5
interviews to be re-employed. Executives who searched while
employed took an average of 11.1 months and 9.1 interviews to land
new positions.
</P>
<P>
   I tell frustrated searchers that there are no guarantees, but
there seem to be a few things that will maximize their chances for
interviews and job offers:
</P>
<P>
   - Write a skill-based, rather than chronological, resume.
Emphasize areas of expertise and experience rather than
date-by-date employment.
</P>
<P>
   - Don't broadcast salary expectations. And _ ouch _ you may even
have to lower them.
</P>
<P>
   - Use your cover letter and interview time to project
enthusiasm, adaptability and acceptance of change. Don't whine or
rage about the past. Tell what you will do in the future.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-18-98 2211EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981018.0215 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-18 22:12 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3636 &Cx1f; kan-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CORN-PRICES-2NDTAKE-K     10-18 0239
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CORN-PRICES-2NDTAKE-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
   
 c. 1998 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   OREGON, Mo. _ leave,'' Fisher said.
</P>
<P>
   ``What city folks don't really home in on,'' Fink said, ``is
that when we stop spending, it eventually gets back to the city.
The first thing you'll see is us buying less iron (combines and
tractors). But it also means fewer trips to the city, fertilizer,
parts, all sorts of things.
</P>
<P>
   ``The other day I needed a machinery part,'' he said. ``I went
down to my implement dealer. He said it'd be $800 and they'd have
to get it out of Kansas City. Well, I thought about it and figured
this was no time to be spending that kind of money. So I did this
and that, cobbled together a part and ended up spending about $400,
all local.
</P>
<P>
   ``That may not seem like a lot _ $800. But multiply it by
hundreds, maybe thousands. And that $800 didn't go to Kansas City.
Meaning somebody there had less work to do. So it's not as far away
as it seems.''
</P>
<P>
   Utlaut said that with the government getting out of farming with
the passage last year the Freedom to Farm law, farmers would see
wilder swings in the prices.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the old days with price supports you'd see, say, corn in a
pretty narrow range _ $2.10 to $2.50, year in a year out. Now it
may be from $1.60 to $5.''
</P>
<P>
   Farmers, Utlaut said, are going to have to have sharp pencils.
Plus bountiful harvests like this year's.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
