<DOCNO> NYT19981018.0216 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-18 22:14 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3637 &Cx1f; kan-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CORN-PRICES-2TAKES-KA     10-18 0999
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CORN-PRICES-2TAKES-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FARMERS GATHER BOUNTIFUL CROP, SEE PRICES FALL TO DISTRESSING
LEVELS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JIM FISHER  
 c. 1998 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   OREGON, Mo. _ An autumnal ritual is under way across the Middle
West _ fall harvest.
</P>
<P>
   Soybean fields are swept bare enough to resemble tan carpets;
sorghum plants are whole one day, decapitated the next; and huge
cornfields are turned from upright rows into khaki-colored trash in
an eye blink.
</P>
<P>
   Two facts this year:
</P>
<P>
   The Corn Belt, including most of Kansas, Missouri, Iowa and
Nebraska, has been spared the scourging drought of the Dakotas,
Texas, Oklahoma and parts of the Southeast. For this region's
farmers, there is a bumper crop.
</P>
<P>
   The second fact is that prices are in the tank, among the lowest
in a generation. Cattle, hogs, wheat, sorghum, soybeans, and that
biggest of all American crops, the 9.7 billion-bushel corn harvest,
are all in the doldrums.
</P>
<P>
   Corn prices have fallen 31.5 percent in just the past year.
According to the National Corn Growers Association in St. Louis,
this is the equivalent of a wage earner making $45,000 in 1997 but
just $30,825 in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   The USDA recently estimated that lower commodity prices would
reduce this year's farm income by 16 percent, or $7 billion. Partly
because of this, and in response to the drought in various parts of
the country, Congress last week approved $6 billion in emergency
aid. The aid includes estimated payments that will ensure farmers
$2.44 a bushel for corn, well above current prices.
</P>
<P>
   Yet prices, oddly enough, are taking a back seat as the
combines, corn buggies and huge grain-hauling trucks make their way
through October.
</P>
<P>
   It's harvest. Good crops are in the field. Time to get them in.
</P>
<P>
   Which is what Byron Fink was doing northeast of Oregon, his
combine dancing a sort of agrarian ballet amid 250 acres of corn,
following the terraces and creating a landscape where vistas were
no longer hidden beyond a field's edge.
</P>
<P>
   ``I could have someone else run this combine,'' said Fink. ``But
it's harvest. And I'm a farmer.''
</P>
<P>
   The good harvest _ the 175-bushel yield per acre _ was the
result of the deep-loess soil in this part of Missouri, genetically
engineered seed, weed killers and fertilizer, and, most of all,
rains that came just at the right time all summer long.
</P>
<P>
   ``Perfect,'' Fink said of 1998's weather.
</P>
<P>
   For this crop, the price would be roughly $1.80 a bushel. Fink
is selling the crop for cash at the request of four elderly women,
and he will get a share.
</P>
<P>
   And that price was up _ given a slight bounce by recent bad
weather, a government report saying the 1998 corn crop wouldn't be
the second-biggest in history, and a hint that commodities might be
sent to Russia to help that country get through the winter.
</P>
<P>
   Even with the congressional help last week, some farmers will
barely cover their costs.
</P>
<P>
   Glen Riekoff, a corn grower near Concordia, said he needed $2.40
a bushel. And Riekoff has this perspective: Rummaging through old
family records, he found his wife's forbears had sold corn in 1889
for $1.25 a bushel, literally a king's ransom, he said, ``because
then a dollar was really a dollar.''
</P>
<P>
   As city dwellers and suburbanites have watched their stock
holdings drop, rally and then drop again in the past months,
farmers have spent more than a year witnessing a long slide in
prices, the result of high production, a strong dollar and
shriveling demand from Asian countries now mired in recession.
</P>
<P>
   Ryland Utlaut of Alma, immediate past president of the National
Corn Growers Association, predicts a ``winter of discontent'' for
the farm community.
</P>
<P>
   Fink used another phrase.
</P>
<P>
   ``I call it the full-bin syndrome,'' he said. ``Right now,
farmers are in the midst of harvest and not thinking about much
else.
</P>
<P>
   ``But get down the road a few months and those bins will still
be full and the farmer is going to have bills and expenses. Then
he'll figure up how much he's got out back, what it'll bring at
market and what he owes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Then farmers are going to know what they're up against.''
</P>
<P>
   Ron Mcneall, who farms 1,250 acres near Keytesville, calls
himself an optimist.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are farmers down in west Texas and up in the Dakotas
getting zero yields or close to that. Which means we'll lose some
farmers.
</P>
<P>
   ``But here we're at least making a crop.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, Mcneall is ``watching the pennies.'' His pickup has
140,000 miles on it; a meter on his tractor reads 7,000 hours. Plus
he, similar to a lot of farmers, has a side business. In Mcneall's
case, this means selling seed.
</P>
<P>
   Don Fisher, a farmer near Corder, said he had sold cash corn
this year for $1.60 to $1.62 a bushel. Two years ago he was getting
$2.75, and he can recall the top price he ever received for corn _
$5.13 a bushel in the early 1990s.
</P>
<P>
   ``That seems like a million years ago,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Already, Fisher said, farmers are tightening down, deferring
purchases, figuring they can make do with what they have.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think this is going to be anything like the early
1980s,'' he said, referring to a shakeout of farmers and the
media-savvy American Agricultural Movement. That group organized
``tractorcades'' to state capitols and Washington, disrupted forced
farm sales, seized grain and generally raised Cain.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of those farmers are gone,'' said Fisher. ``The
difference now is simple. Go into town on any morning and you'll
have a hard time scaring up a farmer sitting around in a coffee
shop.... They're too busy doing what they have to do to keep going.
</P>
<P>
   ``What's happened in 20 years is that farming has become a
13-month-a-year job. Sure we're going through a bad time. But if
you thought it'd last forever, you wouldn't get up in the
morning.''
</P>
<P>
   Both Fisher and Fink agree that when farmers have money the one
thing they do is put it back in the economy. ``We're like sailors
on leave,'' Fisher said. MORE
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
