<HEADER>
A3639 &Cx1f; kan-z
r w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLINTON-POLLS-2NDTAKE     10-18 0488
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-POLLS-2NDTAKE-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
   
 c. 1998 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ of their leader.
</P>
<P>
   Only 30 percent of respondents in a recent USA Today//Gallup
poll said the words ``honest'' and ``trustworthy'' applied to
Clinton. That's down from 37 percent in January. It's even a few
percentage points lower than the ``integrity'' scores given to
Nixon in the waning days of his presidency.
</P>
<P>
   At a Capitol Hill watering hole called Bullfeathers, arguments
have erupted all summer. Many have lasted until closing time, said
Stratton Liapis, owner of the hangout for congressional staffers.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's party line all the way, whether people admit it or not,''
he said. ``The hard-core Republicans are the most passionate; throw
the book at Clinton, they say. The people you could label as
ultraliberal _ they're very uptight. Private matter, they say. The
people in the middle, they get off work and come in here and they
don't want to hear about it anymore. They really don't.''
</P>
<P>
   Amid spreading anxiety over how those middle people will vote in
November, third parties are keeping their fingers crossed for a
wave of new support, said George Getz, a Libertarian Party
spokesman.
</P>
<P>
   But even Libertarians, boasting 166 candidates for Congress,
felt compelled to enlist in the impeachment wars. The party in July
passed a resolution that Clinton be impeached not because of the
sex scandal but because Libertarians believe his efforts to
regulate handguns and to censor the Internet are unconstitutional.
</P>
<P>
   What's happening inside the Beltway, says University of
California Professor Charles M. Price, is the two-party system in
overdrive. If Capitol Hill's interest in the scandal does not
reflect the public interest as measured in polls, it's because
Capitol Hill is composed almost entirely of Republicans and
Democrats. (Only one member of Congress is an independent _ Vermont
Rep. Bernard Sanders, who voted against the House impeachment
inquiry.)
</P>
<P>
   Half of Americans, by contrast, call themselves ``independent''
when pollsters call. And for nine months running, the opinions of
Clinton expressed by these independent voters have reflected the
overall national mood almost to the decimal point.
</P>
<P>
   Consider this question from CBS News pollsters earlier this
month: ``Do you believe Bill Clinton is still an effective
president?''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, the gap between Republicans and Democrats was
immense. Only four in 10 Republicans said Clinton was still
effective, compared with nearly nine in 10 Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   The ``independent'' response: 68 percent said yes, Clinton was
effective, and 29 percent said no. Remarkably that mirrored the
sentiments of the nation as a whole: 69 percent yes, 29 percent no.
</P>
<P>
   ``Keep watching those independents,'' said poll-tracker Bowman.
``The president's future may hinge on if and when their opinions
change.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
