<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TWA-BASE-2NDTAKE-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
   
 c. 1998 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ TWA continues operating.
</P>
<P>
   Nelson said TWA wanted to eliminate provisions in the previous
agreement that required TWA to keep the Kansas City overhaul base
and have TWA mechanics do all its maintenance work.
</P>
<P>
   The Machinists union has asked the National Mediation Board to
begin a 30-day countdown, after which workers would be free to
strike. The mediator is meeting with company and union officials
this week.
</P>
<P>
   City officials hope a contract resolution with TWA's workers
will lead to a renewal of the overhaul base's lease. Anderson
agreed that the base's long-term prospects remained uncertain.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're comfortable that TWA will be here after the year 2000,
but it's unclear as to how long,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   TWA's union leaders in Kansas City are urging City Council
members to push for the renewal of the lease.
</P>
<P>
   ``Without a commitment from the city, we may not be able to get
a (union) contract to lock them in to the Kansas City facility,''
Nelson said.
</P>
<P>
   The two issues are not connected, Abels said. TWA's maintenance
system ``is driven by the size of our fleet, not by any collective
bargaining agreement,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Councilwoman Teresa Loar, chairwoman of the City Operations
Committee, said the city would examine what financial assistance
could be provided.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want to do everything we can to keep TWA in Kansas City,''
she said. ``We're talking about thousands of jobs, so we would take
a hard look at ways of subsidizing costs for the company.''
</P>
<P>
   Nelson said Cleaver had expressed his support to keep TWA's
maintenance jobs in Kansas City.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's solidly committed to helping us,'' Nelson said. ``He'd
like to get a lease locked up before he leaves office.''
</P>
</TEXT>
