<SLUG> BC-TWA-BASE-2TAKES-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CITY OFFICIALS NEGOTIATE PLAN TO KEEP TWA MAINTENANCE FACILITY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RANDOLPH HEASTER  
 c. 1998 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ Kansas City is considering options to
renovate or rebuild its jet maintenance base as part of efforts to
persuade Trans World Airlines Inc. to keep its maintenance
operation _ and about 2,200 jobs _ here.
</P>
<P>
   Renovation would cost at least $240 million, according to a
report by Burns &AMP; McDonnell Engineers-Architects-Consultants. The
report was submitted earlier this year to the city Aviation
Department, which is negotiating with TWA to renew its lease on the
overhaul base.
</P>
<P>
   That lease expires in May 2000, and city officials and union
leaders are concerned that the airline may abandon the maintenance
operation at Kansas City International Airport. In union
negotiations, TWA is pushing to eliminate contract provisions
requiring the airline to keep the base open.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a concern that TWA management wants to close the
overhaul base and outsource all their maintenance work,'' said
Councilman Ed Ford.
</P>
<P>
   The airline is in early negotiations with the city, said Mark
Abels, TWA vice president of corporate communications. TWA is
evaluating its entire maintenance system, including sites in Kansas
City, St. Louis, New York and Los Angeles, he said.
</P>
<P>
   The future of the Kansas City overhaul base is being discussed
while TWA negotiates with the Machinists union on a new contract.
The Machinists, who represent about 75 percent of TWA's employees,
have worked under an old contract since September 1997.
</P>
<P>
   ``They have proposed the unlimited outsourcing of our work,''
said Keith Nelson, president of Local 1650. ``If they get that in
the contract, the chances become greater that TWA would phase out
the Kansas City overhaul base at the end of the lease in May
2000.''
</P>
<P>
   Abels declined to comment on outsourcing, but he confirmed that
TWA's bargaining position is to not protect any company facility
from the prospect of downsizing or closing.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can't give that assurance,'' he said. ``We can't manage a
business that way. Some people think a building creates jobs. We
tend to think a successful business creates jobs.''
</P>
<P>
   Ray Anderson, city aviation director, said his department and
TWA had exchanged information about the overhaul base for more than
a year. In addition, Mayor Emanuel Cleaver has met with TWA
executives at its St. Louis corporate headquarters.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's fair to say the discussions taking place are
about a (lease) extension of some form,'' Anderson said. ``We still
have a good 18 months before it expires, and we're hoping to have
another meeting with TWA well before the end of the year.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite those negotiations, questions linger about whether TWA
intends to continue its Kansas City maintenance operation. TWA has
struggled through two bankruptcies, though its finances have
improved recently, and the size of its work force here has
declined.
</P>
<P>
   The airline no longer does much contract work on aircraft of
other carriers at the overhaul base. In addition, TWA has
eliminated older planes from its fleet, such as the jumbo Boeing
747, whose size required it to be serviced at Kansas City's
maintenance center.
</P>
<P>
   As it continues to strengthen its operations, TWA has
reconfigured its fleet to become less of an international carrier
and more of an airline for business travelers. The company has
bought newer planes that require less overall maintenance.
</P>
<P>
   Furthermore, Lambert-St. Louis International Airport recently
received approval for a $2.6 billion expansion, and union officials
in Kansas City wonder whether that might include shifting more
maintenance work there.
</P>
<P>
   TWA plans to replace the maintenance facility at Lambert but has
not made any decisions regarding the new base to be built there,
Abels said.
</P>
<P>
   As for the overhaul base in Kansas City, less than 60 percent of
it is being used, according to Burns &AMP; McDonnell.
</P>
<P>
   The study examined three possibilities: renovate the existing
facility; build a maintenance base that would include an
administrative office; and build a maintenance facility that would
be surrounded by smaller administrative buildings.
</P>
<P>
   The study indicated that renovation would include consolidating
some operations into one building and demolishing the superhangars
at the base, which would leave a second existing building available
for another tenant.
</P>
<P>
   The overhaul base is not obsolete, but some changes are needed
to make it more attractive, including making it more
energy-efficient, according to Burns &AMP; McDonnell.
</P>
<P>
   One problem with the overhaul base is that most airlines,
including TWA, are using more narrow-bodied planes. If the base
were reconfigured, the airline could service more planes in less
space.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd say there would be a limited number of potential tenants''
in the facility's current form, said Randy Pope of Burns &AMP;
McDonnell. ``But there's a lot of flexibility there, also.''
</P>
<P>
   TWA's maintenance operations are too large, given the size of
the airline, Abels said.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's probably too much (maintenance) capacity in our system
right now,'' he said. ``The Kansas City facility, along with St.
Louis, Los Angeles and New York, offers more hangar space than we
really need.''
</P>
<P>
   That does not necessarily mean the Kansas City overhaul base,
TWA's largest, is too big, Abels said. For example, he said TWA
could decide to shift more of its work to that facility. The
airline is studying its needs and has not made any firm decisions
regarding any maintenance facilities, he said.
</P>
<P>
   What TWA decides to do with its Kansas City operations may
depend on the outcome of talks with the Machinists.
</P>
<P>
   The union has said that it wants wages comparable with those of
other airlines. In addition, Nelson said, the union wants
contractual assurances that the overhaul base will remain a part of
the airline as long as TWA continues operating. MORE
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
