<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RIVERBOAT-CASINOS-2TAKES-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MISSOURI CASINO REFERENDUM CAMPAIGN FOUGHT ON MANY FRONTS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RICK ALM  
 c. 1998 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ Lapel buttons urging passage of the casino
``boats in moats'' amendment Nov. 3 are the real McCoy _ metal
disc, tricolor printing, safety pin and a politically correct union
manufacturing mark.
</P>
<P>
   The anti-casino crowd, on the other hand, is distributing
peel-away paper `stickies' in just one economical color that
feature the ``no'' slash through the word ``slots.''
</P>
<P>
   The contrast is telling.
</P>
<P>
   When it comes to money, the Amendment 9 campaign is a contest of
David-and- Goliath proportions. By the end of last month, Missouri
casinos had reported spending $5.5 million. The other side was
nursing a $34,000 war chest that has since grown to about $100,000.
</P>
<P>
   Voters face a difficult choice.
</P>
<P>
   On paper, the election is about amending the Missouri
Constitution to retroactively legalize nine of the state's 15
riverboat casinos that the General Assembly and Missouri Gaming
Commission allowed to operate as far as 1,000 feet off river.
</P>
<P>
   In reality, voters will decide Nov. 3 whether those casinos
survive.
</P>
<P>
   A yes vote would, in effect, overturn a decision last year by
the Missouri Supreme Court that outlawed games of chance, including
slot machines, aboard those boats in moats.
</P>
<P>
   A no vote would set in motion a series of events that probably
would result _ although not immediately _ in a Gaming Commission
order to the affected casinos to unplug their slots, which generate
up to two-thirds of their gross revenue.
</P>
<P>
   If that happens, Missouri would become the first state to
effectively un-legalize casino gambling. And a victory here would
fuel similar fights elsewhere, including Mississippi, where a
debate is under way on whether to outlaw that state's 30 casinos.
</P>
<P>
   Casino operators, such as Las Vegas-based Station Casinos Inc.,
which invested $300 million in its Kansas City operation, are
understandably nervous. So are the estimated 10,000 Missourians who
work in the affected casinos.
</P>
<P>
   And so is Wall Street, where the fiscal health of Missouri's
publicly traded gambling companies hangs in the balance.
</P>
<P>
   ``Investors are concerned,'' said Harry Curtis, who analyzes
gambling- industry stocks for BancBoston Robertson Stephens. ``I'm
hoping for some objective treatment for an industry that was
maligned early on.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some of these companies are facing extinction,'' Curtis said.
``I ask myself, `Is this right?' ''
</P>
<P>
   Shutting down casinos is absolutely the right thing to do, says
St. Louis Republican Rep. Todd Akin, whose 1996 lawsuit triggered
the boats-in-moats mess.
</P>
<P>
   ``This isn't just about boats in moats,'' he said. ``This
election is a turning point in what happens with gambling in our
state.''
</P>
<P>
   If the casinos win Nov. 3, Akin says, legislative opposition to
gambling in Jefferson City probably will soften, and gambling will
expand.
</P>
<P>
   ``If this thing passes,'' Akin said, ``I would predict within
three or four years you'd see slots and video poker machines
proliferating in bars around the state.''
</P>
<P>
   If the election in Missouri is a David-and-Goliath struggle, the
casino industry wants voters to think of it as David.
</P>
<P>
   Noting the broad spectrum of mainline religious groups in
Missouri working against Amendment 9, American Gaming Association
President Frank J. Fahrenkopf Jr. said: ``They're Goliath. Every
community has a Methodist church and a Baptist church.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's what America is all about,'' he added. ``Since the
republic began, people with strong moral and religious views have
opposed gambling.''
</P>
<P>
   But after a 10-year run of casino gambling that has spread to 26
states, it's clear the moral argument hasn't worked, Fahrenkopf
said. ``We're not suddenly seeing people not going to casinos.''
</P>
<P>
   That's certainly true in Missouri. According to the state's
latest fiscal year accounting, casinos entertained a record 39.5
million visitors who left behind more than $802 million.
</P>
<P>
   Many Missourians, in essence, are voting for the casinos with
their feet and their pocketbooks.
</P>
<P>
   That's why the casinos all summer aided patrons in registering
to vote. The question now for casino executives is whether those
gamblers will show up at the polls Election Day.
</P>
<P>
   The morality card isn't the only one gambling foes are playing.
</P>
<P>
   Opponents are using many of the same economic arguments they
used at the polls in 1992 and 1994.
</P>
<P>
   Again this year, for instance, they quote University of Illinois
Professor John W. Kindt, who has advanced a theory for years that
``for every $1 in tax revenue that gambling raises, it creates $3
in costs to handle economic disruption, compulsive gambling and
crime.''
</P>
<P>
   If Kindt is right _ he has plenty of detractors _ federal, state
and local government coffers in Missouri would have been drained of
at least $481 million in the last fiscal year to salve society's
gambling-induced wounds.
</P>
<P>
   That number is not implausible, but there is no evidence such
government spending has approached that level. The problem with
such theories is that they are all but impossible to prove, or
disprove.
</P>
<P>
   Little unbiased economic research has been done, especially in
Missouri. And even if it had been, the statistics necessary for
such definitive research are slippery at best.
</P>
<P>
   For instance: How many people chose to dine out at casino
restaurants instead of their favorite Main Street eateries last
year? How many compulsive gamblers embezzled from their workplaces?
And just how many compulsive gamblers are there in Missouri,
anyway?
</P>
<P>
   The best research to date estimates that about 5 percent of the
adult U.S. population is at risk to experience some level of
gambling-related financial or emotional problem. That leaves 95
percent who aren't at risk.
</P>
<P>
   Another longstanding Kindt theory argues that for every casino
job created, one is lost elsewhere in the economy. MORE
</P>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ in the economy.
</P>
<P>
   But even Akin acknowledged last week that that had not been the
case _ at least so far _ in Missouri, where the economy has been
booming most of the decade.
</P>
<P>
   ``The effect may not be instantaneous,'' he said. ``It's a
long-term effect.''
</P>
<P>
   Even though the industry calls it gaming, it's still gambling to
most people. The mathematical odds against rolling a 7 or drawing
to an inside straight haven't changed in the gaming '90s.
</P>
<P>
   Every night a relative handful of lucky gamblers do win
jackpots. That's what keeps players coming back for more.
</P>
<P>
   But also every night, the house doesn't lose.
</P>
<P>
   Casinos are cash-generating machines. They remain so despite
restrictive boarding rules and betting limits in Missouri that were
designed to protect problem gamblers from themselves _ but which
also hold down the house take.
</P>
<P>
   Gambling foes admit that a defeat in Missouri would be a setback
to their argument that entertainment-fickle Americans, if nothing
else, are souring on the idea of neighborhood casino gambling.
</P>
<P>
   There's not much evidence of that as the industry continues to
log record revenue every year.
</P>
<P>
   Missouri's casino industry is trying to tighten the focus of the
campaign and not allow Nov. 3 to become a shouting match and
referendum on the political and moral correctness of casino
gambling.
</P>
<P>
   For that reason, riverboat executives refuse to debate their
foes in public and decline most interview requests on the election.
</P>
<P>
   ``We believe the people of Missouri care about fairness and care
about jobs,'' said Richard J. Haskins, Midwest general counsel for
Station Casinos.
</P>
<P>
   ``The simple fact of the matter is that boats in moats were
authorized by the General Assembly, the Missouri Gaming Commission
and the local communities.
</P>
<P>
   ``To come back now and threaten over 10,000 good-paying jobs is
simply not right,'' Haskins said. ``It is extremely important to
separate fact from fiction, and we believe the facts speak for
themselves _ 10,000 jobs, $90 million a year in revenue to
education and over $1 billion in private capital investment in the
state.''
</P>
<P>
   Mark Andrews, chairman of the anti-gambling campaign group Show
Me the River, insists that the industry brought its troubles on
itself.
</P>
<P>
   Voters were lulled in 1992 into voting for a nostalgic image of
riverboat gambling, he said, but wound up with sprawling,
land-based complexes, such as Station Casino Kansas City.
</P>
<P>
   ``Boats in moats are victims of their own bait and switch,''
Andrews said.
</P>
<P>
   Whether the casinos are on dry land or floating in Missouri's
muddy rivers, however, opponents say the economic and human price
society must pay for gambling isn't worth it.
</P>
<P>
   They said the same things in 1992 and again in 1994, and voters
didn't buy it.
</P>
<P>
   This year, with four years of casino experience under Kansas
City's belt, some of those concerns can now be measured.
</P>
<P>
   National researchers have come to widely divergent conclusions
on whether the presence of legalized gambling tends to increase
suicide rates and personal bankruptcies, as foes claim.
</P>
<P>
   The trends in Kansas City are mixed.
</P>
<P>
   The Jackson County medical examiner's office, for example,
reports that the county's suicide rate has been stable for a
decade.
</P>
<P>
   In the three years before the first riverboats opened in 1994,
Jackson County averaged 106 suicides per year. In the three years
after 1994, the average was 101.
</P>
<P>
   A widely quoted new study by SMR Research Corp. of Hackettstown,
N.J., says there is a strong statistical link between the proximity
of casinos and increases in personal bankruptcy filings _ as much
as 35 percent higher.
</P>
<P>
   Those findings come, however, at a time when similarly huge
increases are being reported nationwide as a result, in part, of
easy bank credit, consumer credit abuse and the erasure of much
consumer debt by liberal bankruptcy laws.
</P>
<P>
   In this region, the U.S. Bankruptcy Court for the Western
District of Missouri reported a record number of nonbusiness
Chapter 7 bankruptcy filings last year _ 9,294. The figure was
7,685 in 1996 and had averaged 3,281 in the three years before
1994.
</P>
<P>
   Congress is grappling with reform legislation now to toughen
bankruptcy rules so consumers cannot so easily evade their debts _
which increasingly include credit card cash advances used for
gambling.
</P>
<P>
   Several state legislatures, Missouri among them, are debating
whether to bar credit card cash and automated teller machines from
casino properties.
</P>
<P>
   Missouri also is one of the few gambling states that prohibit
casinos from extending house credit _ ``markers'' _ to tapped-out
gamblers.
</P>
<P>
   Last week two of the few researchers who have studied
post-casino Missouri to any degree squared off on whether the
experience has been a net plus or minus for the state's economy.
The result: a draw.
</P>
<P>
   Neither study was conclusive, and each acknowledged it.
</P>
<P>
   Here is what's known: The Kansas City area's five threatened
boats in moats employ more than 5,000 people with a combined annual
payroll of nearly $100 million. They pay an additional $100 million
a year in state and local gaming taxes alone.
</P>
<P>
   But there are hidden facets to the economic question.
</P>
<P>
   The anti-gambling side contends that every dollar spent in a
casino is a dollar not spent at a local business, costing jobs and
marketplace diversity in the long run.
</P>
<P>
   Pro-gambling economists counter that Americans' income rises
every year while family entertainment budgets, as a percentage of
personal spending, have been expanding for years, putting many more
dollars into the equation.
</P>
<P>
   The academic studies of Missouri estimate the effect of gambling
in a range from more than $500 million a year to the good, to
nearly $200 million a year in negative effect in a comprehensive
weighing of new taxes, jobs and economic development against the
costs of problem gambling and economic disruption.
</P>
<P>
   The truth probably will never be known.
</P>
<P>
   But the argument will continue to rage.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
