<HEADLINE>
MIGHTY DUCKS NOTEBOOK
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By GREG CHRISTENSEN  
 c.1998 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANAHEIM, Calif. _ It took four games, but Anaheim Mighty Ducks
coach Craig Hartsburg finally got a good look at what his top line
could do when Paul Kariya, Steve Rucchin and Teemu Selanne combined
for three goals and eight points in Anaheim's 5-3 win over Chicago
on Thursday night.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I could see that every night that would great,'' said
Hartsburg. ``They turned up their game a notch, brought their ``A''
game. The momentum they brought to the game was great.''
</P>
<P>
   Hartsburg was especially impressed by Kariya's shorthanded goal.
The Anaheim winger blocked a shot, got up quickly after being
tripped, got up and had his first shot stopped by goalie Jeff
Hackett. But without breaking stride Kariya got his own rebound and
lifted it over Hackett.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know many ... I don't know if there are any,'' said
Hartsburg when asked how many players in the league could make such
a play. ``The scary thing was that he made it look pretty easy.
Ninty-five percent of the guys in the league might not even be able
to get up to try and make the play.''
</P>
<P>
   However, Hartsburg wasn't so happy with Sunday's practice,
especially the team's worth ethic.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not very happy at all,'' he said. ``We've got come ready
to work everyday and when we practice like we did today it shows
that we aren't there yet.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a fine line between winning and losing and those who
pay the price usually get on the right side of the line.''
</P>
<P>
   In particular, Hartsburg was upset by the work, or lack of it,
on the power play.
</P>
<P>
   And Selanne certainly wasn't about debate the issure.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was right, on the power play we were just floating, said
Selanne. ``Our minds weren't there, we thought we were working but
we weren't.
</P>
<P>
   ``We should feel ashamed, you can't get better if you're not
honest with yourself.''
</P>
<P>
   Kariya gave the trainers a little scare on Sunday when he fell
to the ice and started vomiting.
</P>
<P>
   After practice, Kariya, who is wearing a mouth guard for first
time this time, didn't really want to talk about the incident. He
did said he was not ill and just gagged.
</P>
<P>
   Selanne who scored his first two goals of the season against
Chicago said Hartsburg and the Ducks remained calm despite losing
the first three games of the season-opening trip.
</P>
<P>
   ``Harts went through a 0-7 start (with Chicago) last year, but
he wasn't panicking,'' Selanne said. ``After Montreal we had a
meeting on the plane and said we had to stay positive ... we knew
we were going in the right direction.''
</P>
<P>
   But after the Ducks relaxed with a team outing to see the movie
Roxbury, Selanne said Anaheim knew a win in Chicago would give it a
much needed boost.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was big,'' he said. ``It was lets win or be miserable for
five days (until they would play again).''
</P>
<P>
   Goalie Guy Hebert, despite suffering a Grade I shoulder
separation late in the exhibition season, played the final three
games of the road trip after missing the season opener in
Washington. He is expected to start the home opener against Boston
on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``The shoulder is fine,'' said Hebert. ``I don't think it (the
injury) is all gone, but I'm very happy with the way it held up.''
</P>
<P>
   Josef Marha, sideline since the opening game of the season with
a sprained right ankle, skated briefly on Saturday and Sunday. But
the Ducks forward is not expected back in the lineup anytime soon.
</P>
</TEXT>
