<HEADLINE>
TYSON TO PLEAD CASE AGAIN
</HEADLINE>
   (nk) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LAS VEGAS _ For the second time in 30 days, Mike Tyson will
appear before the Nevada State Athletic Commission here Monday and
try to convince its five members that he should be given back his
boxing license.
</P>
<P>
   The commission revoked Tyson's license on July 9, 1997, after he
bit Evander Holyfield's ears during their heavyweight championship
bout on June 28, 1997. The commission is trying to determine
whether Tyson is prone to snap again if he gets back into the ring.
If Tyson, 32, is denied a license, he can't apply again until Oct.
19, 1999.
</P>
<P>
   Tyson was expected to answer the commission's questions
regarding his mental fitness and their questions regarding an Aug.
31 incident in Gaithersburg, Md., where he allegedly assaulted two
men following a traffic mishap involving him and his wife.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's open to whatever the commission wants to know,'' said
Shelly Finkel, Tyson's boxing adviser.
</P>
</TEXT>
