<DOCNO> NYT19981018.0232 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-18 23:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3797 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBC-USC-LADN     10-18 0627
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-USC-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
QB ILLS DETRACT FROM PROGRESS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By SCOTT WOLF  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ USC starting quarterback Mike Van Raaphorst's
nausea attacks are causing enough concern that he will undergo
medical tests today as the Trojans attempt to figure out why he
became ill during their 42-14 victory over Washington State.
</P>
<P>
   The tests might also determine if there is any connection
between this latest incident and the fact Van Raaphorst became ill
before two other games this season.
</P>
<P>
   As for growing suspicions that Van Raaphorst is suffering from
nerves or stress, the sophomore quarterback steadfastly denied
those rumors.
</P>
<P>
   ``No. Definitely not,'' he said. ``I don't think I would get
nervous after throwing a touchdown pass (in the first quarter).''
</P>
<P>
   Van Raaphorst received a flu shot earlier in the week, but he
didn't know if that _ or a hit he took in the stomach Saturday
night _ contributed to his nausea.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just felt terrible,'' Van Raaphorst said. ``They're going to
do some stuff and see what's wrong.''
</P>
<P>
   USC officials said two other players _ tight ends Antoine Harris
and Lonnie Ford _ also experienced nausea during the game. But Van
Raaphorst also suffered food poisoning before the season-opener
against Purdue and stomach flu before Florida State.
</P>
<P>
   Van Raaphorst's mystery illness was the only setback the Trojans
suffered against the Cougars, and he was impressively replaced by
freshman Carson Palmer, who demonstrated he has the charisma and
skill to lead the Trojans.
</P>
<P>
   After its most resounding victory of the season, it's ironic
that USC's quarterback questions continue to overshadow much of
what the Trojans accomplished at Washington State. USC (5-2, 3-1)
had its year teetering toward disaster after last week's horrible
loss to California, but the Trojans regrouped with perhaps their
best effort of the season.
</P>
<P>
   Look no further than middle linebacker Chris Claiborne, who
clearly stepped up his play following the loss to Cal.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're in a portion of the season where it can go either way.
We can't lose another game,'' Claiborne said. ``Last week we didn't
have that thought and it burned us. I just want us as a team to
work on our killer instinct and finish people. I'm going to stay on
guys for the rest of the season.''
</P>
<P>
   Claiborne certainly did his part, with two interceptions,
including a 25-yard touchdown return.
</P>
<P>
   ``What can you say?'' USC coach Paul Hackett said. ``If he's not
the best linebacker in the country, I don't know who is. The guy,
he's unbelievable.''
</P>
<P>
   Claiborne has ways of turning games around, much like wide
receiver R. Jay Soward, who scored two touchdowns. But even the
loquacious Soward couldn't keep mum about the influence Palmer
sometimes has on the offense. Whether or not Palmer was
responsible, USC outscored Washington State 28-0 as soon as he
entered the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``I love Carson. I got excited (when he came),'' Soward said.
``Mike's good, too, but I love to see Carson come into a game. He's
a playmaker.''
</P>
<P>
   Palmer's status this week against Oregon probably depends more
on Van Raaphorst's health, but Palmer is saying all the right
things while continuing to make a bid for the starting position.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a coaches decision. (Mike) played great. It's still
Mike's job,'' Palmer said.
</P>
<P>
   Hackett was more pleased that USC survived its trip to Pullman
without committing a single turnover.
</P>
<P>
   ``The offense came up into the Northwest on a rainy evening and
did not turn the ball over,'' Hackett said. ``... We're playing in
their backyard, they play in this junk all the time, we have a wet
ball, we have a rainy day and we don't turn the ball over.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
