<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-SERIES-TUCKER19-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    'Raft to riches' Hernandez turns in outstanding performance
 &HT;    By Tim Tucker
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   New York _ A year ago, when his half-brother struck out 15
Atlanta Braves in the playoffs, then was MVP of the World Series,
Orlando Hernandez watched the games at the CNN studio in Havana.
Two months later, he fled Cuba in a makeshift raft, seeking freedom
and baseball.
</P>
<P>
   Sunday night, Orlando (El Duque) Hernandez landed in the World
Series.
</P>
<P>
   Raft to riches, someone called it.
</P>
<P>
   And despite the efforts of the Yankees' hitters to steal the
show, Hernandez was the best story of World Series Game 2. Heck, he
would have been the best story even if he hadn't pitched well and
gotten the win over San Diego.
</P>
<P>
   It is a mind-boggling journey, through shark-infested waters,
from an $8.75-a-month job as a physical therapist in a Cuban
psychiatric hospital to starting a World Series game. Not
surprisingly, a movie is in the works.
</P>
<P>
   On the day after Christmas, Hernandez and seven others snuck out
of Cuba. Three days later, they made it to the Caribbean island of
Anguilla Cay. And about two months later, Orlando Hernandez, who
had been banned from baseball in Cuba because he was suspected of
aiding half-brother Livan Hernandez's defection, got his first
benefit of capitalism: a three-year, $6.6-million contract with the
Yankees.
</P>
<P>
   And still he might not have been on the mound in this World
Series if David Cone hadn't been bitten on his pitching hand by his
mother's dog. . . .
</P>
<P>
   That part of this stranger-than-fiction story happened in June,
and Hernandez, who began the season in the minors, was called upon
to make one start for the Yankees. He pitched so well that he made
20 more regular-season starts, then pitched so well in the ALCS
that he got a World Series start ahead of Cone, who'll work Game 3.
</P>
<P>
   ''He seems to pitch his best when more things are at stake,''
Yankees manager Joe Torre says of Hernandez, and why does that not
surprise us? Torre again: ''After all he's been through the last 12
months, this is just a game.''
</P>
<P>
   Sunday's wasn't much of a game. The Yankees' hitters found Andy
Ashby a lot less troubling than Braves' hitters did, pounding him
for 10 hits and seven runs in 2 2/3 innings. Hernandez worked seven
innings, allowing six hits and one run, the only run he has allowed
in 14 innings this postseason.
</P>
<P>
   It would seem at the moment that this Series will be won easily
by the Yankees. But remember: The Braves won the first two games of
the '96 Series more handily (a combined 16-1) than the Yankees have
won the first two games this time. And you know how '96 turned out.
</P>
<P>
   Hernandez has declined during this Series to discuss his
defection from Cuba, but clearly he marvels at his ride of the past
year. As his team celebrated the American League pennant last week,
he sat alone. ''My mind was racing back with thoughts of the past
year,'' he said later. ''Although at times I've felt this is a
dream, I am certain now that it is real.''
</P>
<P>
   And did he dare dream, while watching his brother beat the
Braves and Indians, that a year later he would find himself in the
same spotlight? ''No, I didn't think I would be here today,''
Orlando Hernandez said, ''but yes, I did think of finding a way to
one day be here.''
</P>
<P>
   Tim Tucker writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution, Atlanta,
Ga. E-mail: tim(at)ajc.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
