<P>
   MICROSOFT-ANTITRUST (Undated) _ The antitrust laws at the core
of the Department of Justice's suit against the Microsoft Corp.
have been around for over a hundred years. Yet their broad
formulation and decades of ambiguous court decisions have produced
what many antitrust experts regard as an intellectual muddle _
confusing interpretations that leave the basic purpose and concepts
of the antitrust laws largely unresolved. That confusion nearly
guarantees that any jury verdict in this case will be appealed.
That could put the current Supreme Court in the position of bring
intellectual order to a century of clashing legal and economic
doctrines.
</P>
