r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SCHOOLS-ZACARIAS-2tak     10-18 0744
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCHOOLS-ZACARIAS-2takes-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
L.A. SCHOOL SUPERINTENDENT HAS PLAN FOR IMPROVING PERFORMANCE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By TERRI HARDY  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES -- Dismal test scores. Poor student attendance. A
high dropout rate. Crowded classrooms. And too many uncredentialed
teachers.
</P>
<P>
   When Ruben Zacarias was named superintendent of the LAUSD a year
ago, he recognized the tremendous challenge of fixing one of the
most troubled school districts in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Now, in fits and starts, Zacarias is carrying out an
unprecedented plan to reform the beleaguered Los Angeles Unified
School District.
</P>
<P>
   He faces pressure from many sides: The mayor has vowed to unseat
the school board, the governor wants to establish penalties for
failing California schools and activists are seeking legislation to
split the district of 760 schools and centers.
</P>
<P>
   After a full year of sketchy details, the superintendent in
August finally mapped out clearer plans for the district's 100
lowest-performing schools. It stands as the only recent concrete
effort made by the system to reform itself. His obstacles include
opposition from the district's powerful unions and a resistance to
reform.
</P>
<P>
   Central to Zacarias' effort is a new word on the LAUSD's
vocabulary list: accountability.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's by far my biggest challenge,'' Zacarias said. ``The
culture of the public school system nationally, not just in Los
Angeles, has never included a sense of rewards or consequences
based on performance criteria.''
</P>
<P>
   ``As long as people feel the status quo is OK, what incentive do
they have to improve?'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Here is what he has done so far:
</P>
<P>
   -- Zacarias has identified the 100 worst-performing schools and
required them to devise an achievement plan. Support came through
tutoring and special after-school programs. Budgets at the schools
were reconfigured so a total of $10 million would be spent on the
extra programs at the 100 schools.
</P>
<P>
   -- A year later, schools that did not improve were put on
probation, and principals and teachers were told their jobs are in
jeopardy unless students do better.
</P>
<P>
   -- Zacarias plans to expand the accountability requirements to
all schools in the district. Without improvement, they would lose
local decision-making authority on budget, hiring and curriculum
matters. Further penalties include total reorganization, including
personnel changes.
</P>
<P>
   Zacarias' mantra is, ``Reform isn't about 100 schools, it's
about all schools.''
</P>
<P>
   State Superintendent Delaine Eastin said Zacarias is taking an
important first step, although she noted he has no choice but to
revamp the district.
</P>
<P>
   ``The district is in trouble, there's talk of breaking it up,''
Eastin said. ``Reform takes a while, but if you don't start, you'll
never get anywhere. I just hope he puts some real muscle behind
it.''
</P>
<P>
   Second-grader Gustavo Felix is at ground zero of the
superintendent's primary reform plan.
</P>
<P>
   About the time Zacarias took the helm of LAUSD, Gustavo's family
had arrived from Mexico and enrolled their son in second grade at
Cohasset Elementary School in Van Nuys. Gustavo couldn't draw with
the skill of a preschooler _ let alone read or write.
</P>
<P>
   ``He never had any regular education in Mexico,'' his
second-grade teacher explained.
</P>
<P>
   Gustavo, who will remain in second grade this year, isn't
unique. Cohasset teems with children who have difficulty reading
and writing in any language.
</P>
<P>
   This summer, teachers responded by providing intensive literacy
training to students like Gustavo, a strategy that educators hope
will jump-start children who come to Los Angeles schools ill
equipped to tackle basic subject matter.
</P>
<P>
   Zacarias contends that these schools, with enough motivation and
resources, can pull themselves out of their academic quagmire and
be a model for the rest of the district.
</P>
<P>
   The LAUSD consistently placed in the bottom third of the nation
on the recent Stanford 9 achievement test subjects including
reading, math and language.
</P>
<P>
   But in the year since Zacarias arrived, 68 schools, including
Cohasset, showed improvement on the exam.
</P>
<P>
   Still, movement forward comes slowly _ sometimes very slowly _
at the nation's second-largest school district.
</P>
<P>
   ``Change is crucial,'' Zacarias said. ``It isn't going to come
overnight, but I do believe we're pointed in the right direction.''
</P>
<P>
   (2nd take to follow)
</P>
<P>
   After identifying the 100 lowest-performing campuses, it took
Zacarias months to meet with the staff from the schools and
evaluate their achievement plans. Those talks finally ended in
December.
</P>
<P>
   Then, funds for tutoring and other remedial classes got to the
schools very late _ some campuses didn't get money until the
summer. That meant that the schools took the Stanford 9
standardized test _ the exam that serves as their chief measure of
improvement _ before they received extra support.
</P>
<P>
   And even despite the improvements shown at Cohasset and many of
the 100 schools, the superintendent will be the first to say that
the job is far from over.
</P>
<P>
   Cohasset students who took the Stanford 9 lagged behind 84
percent of their peers in the nation. Most schools are still
performing below the district's dismal reading averages.
</P>
<P>
   Teachers and administrators bridled at being among the very
publicly announced 100 schools. But some campuses are shrugging off
the stigma and instead are using the superintendent's edict as a
motivating force.
</P>
<P>
   And so it is in a gritty section of Van Nuys, where Cohasset
Elementary School stands cheerlessly, with an overgrown lawn and
drab exterior.
</P>
<P>
   But things inside a back bungalow are anything but drab, as
traditional music from Southwest American Indians drifts through a
classroom as two teachers in English direct eight children how to
make a model pueblo out of clay.
</P>
<P>
   Gustavo, that once-shy youngster with so few skills, leads the
group.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's made tremendous progress with this program. His motor
skills and verbal skills are already improving,'' said teacher
Lilly Valdivia. ``He was the first to attack this project, and now
he's teaching the others.''
</P>
<P>
   Earlier in the summer, the school enrolled 150 more of its 750
students in a literacy and study skills course done largely on
computers. More than $43,000 was spent to train teachers by Kaplan
Learning Services. Also as part of its improvement plan, the school
launched an after-school effort that offered enrichment programs in
such subjects as art history, math and science.
</P>
<P>
   Something worked at the school. Test scores rose an impressive 9
percentile points.
</P>
<P>
   On the district's northeastern edge, Glenwood Elementary
</P>
<P>
   _ which saw an amazing 12 percentile increase in students' test
scores _ rearranged its budget to finance an intensive reading
tutoring program for 40 struggling third-graders, said Principal
Diane Agliam.
</P>
<P>
   The school has been promised more funds for this school year,
but so far, no check has been received. Even more doubtful is
whether there will be an expansion of the tutoring program.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've never been able to afford anything like this before, and
we have a sense that it's really working,'' Agliam said. ``We just
regret we can't provide it to more children.''
</P>
<P>
   The road to reform has been fraught with potholes. The teachers
union denounced Zacarias' plan as shallow and spur-of-the moment,
created without its input and without regard to its own desire for
an accountability plan that would have teachers review other
teachers at poor performing schools.
</P>
<P>
   Day Higuchi, president of United Teachers Los Angeles, warned
that Zacarias' plan would have to be negotiated with the union.
</P>
<P>
   And the leader of the Associated Administrators of Los Angeles
was upset that the plan seemed to focus sanctions on principals and
not teachers.
</P>
<P>
   It remains to be seen if the districtwide plan could proceed
without their support, although Zacarias has shrugged off that
notion, saying the school board is behind his efforts.
</P>
<P>
   In an endorsement of other reform movements already under way in
the district, Zacarias has called for all schools to adopt some
form of local decision-making that relies on teachers, parents and
principals.
</P>
<P>
   Schools would have more authority over budgets, hiring and
curriculum. But that power comes with a price _ schools will also
be held responsible for their students' performance.
</P>
<P>
   By Oct. 30, schools must declare which decision-making plan they
intend to adopt. However, training won't be fully implemented at
all schools until 2001.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-18-98 2332EDT &QL; 
