<SLUG> BC-ADVERTISING-NOTES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ACCOUNTS AND PEOPLE IN THE ADVERTISING WORLD 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: CANADA, Ill., N.Y.)  (js) 
 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Hampel/Stefanides To Be Acquired
</P>
<P>
   The agency world is getting smaller again as another independent
shop is being acquired.
</P>
<P>
   Envoy Communications Group &UR;  &LR;  in Toronto, which owns the Canadian
agency Communique, is expanding to the United States by buying
Hampel/Stefanides &UR;  &LR;  in New York. Financial terms of the deal, to be
formally announced Monday, were not disclosed.
</P>
<P>
   Hampel/Stefanides, founded in 1993, will continue to operate as
an autonomous agency under that name. The present management team _
Larry Hampel, 39, president; and Dean Stefanides, 43, and Brian
Goodall, 50, co-creative directors _ will continue in those roles.
</P>
<P>
   Hampel/Stefanides has had ``many opportunities to do a deal,''
Goodall said, but selected Envoy because it offered clients access
to integrated marketing services like Web-site design.
</P>
<P>
   Hampel/Stefanides, which also has an office in San Francisco,
has 60 employees and billings estimated at $110 million from
clients like Aer Lingus. Envoy agencies have 175 employees and
billings estimated at $75 million (United States) from clients like
Adidas.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Heinz Chooses Burnett For Ketchup Account
</P>
<P>
   H.J. Heinz Co., as part of a renewed commitment to advertise its
grocery products, has selected Leo Burnett  &UR;  &LR; Co. in Chicago to
handle the consolidated worldwide brand duties for Heinz ketchup
and other condiments and sauces. Though billings on the account,
which had been divided among a dozen shops, were not disclosed,
they were estimated at $50 million.
</P>
<P>
   Casey Keller, vice president for meal enhancement at Heinz in
Pittsburgh, said the decision came after a five-week review that
had been narrowed to Burnett and one other finalist, the TBWA
Worldwide unit of Omnicom Group &UR;  &LR;  in New York.
</P>
<P>
   The victory is important for Burnett as the agency seeks to
regain momentum after some large account losses. Burnett had long
been Heinz's primary U.S. agency for brands like ketchup and
Star-Kist tuna, but resigned in 1994 after Heinz drastically cut
back ad spending.
</P>
<P>
   The Burnett teams handling the account will be based in Chicago
and London. Burnett adds the new assignment to Heinz accounts in
Europe and Latin America for products like seafood.  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
