<HEADER>
A3848 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBC-UCLA-LADN     10-18 0615
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-UCLA-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GIVEN A CHANCE, BROWN RUNS WELL
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JON WILNER  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Every week the UCLA coaches announce an offensive,
defensive and special-teams player of the game. Last week, one
choice appeared obvious: Freshman tailback DeShaun Foster had
powered for 118 yards and singlehandedly halted Arizona's
first-half momentum.
</P>
<P>
   Yet Bruins coach Bob Toledo named junior Keith Brown offensive
player of the game. Sure, Brown had gained 91 yards and scored two
fourth-quarter touchdowns. But they came after Foster had softened
the defense, after UCLA had taken command. Clearly, it was not a
performance-based decision. Toledo was more concerned with Brown's
head than his yards.
</P>
<P>
   ``The coaches have faith in me,'' Brown said. ``(Being player of
the game) was a great feeling. It made me think the coaches have
confidence in me. I've never had the feeling before.''
</P>
<P>
   So inspired, Brown rushed for a career-high 101 yards Saturday
against Oregon, 66 percent of UCLA's total. He did not run with his
usual shiftiness but with previously unseen determination and
power. ``He ran violently,'' offensive coordinator Al Borges said.
``And I don't know that he's done that before.''
</P>
<P>
   Brown has no choice, really. The competition is fierce, what
with Foster and Jermaine Lewis in his shadow. But Toledo knows
three tailbacks can dwindle to one with the twist of a knee _ or a
punch thrown at an off-campus party _ and catapult a role player
like Brown into the starting lineup.
</P>
<P>
   Like USC quarterback Carson Palmer, Foster has 3{ years (if he
stays in school) to earn every accolade imaginable. Why rush him
into the spotlight? Why not remain loyal to the veterans?
</P>
<P>
   As soon as Brown and Lewis believe the coaches have handed the
present to Foster, they'll disappear. They'll lose focus and
motivation. They'll become dead weight, and dead weigh won't run
for 101 yards against Oregon with Foster nursing a sprained knee
that might keep him out 2-3 weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, Brown wasn't No. 2 UCLA's only hero Saturday in the
41-38 overtime victory, just one of the most visible.
</P>
<P>
   Receiver Danny Farmer had 40 percent of the Bruins' receptions
and two touchdowns. Linebacker Brendan Ayabadejo had two sacks in
overtime. (One UCLA observer called it a well-timed impersonation
of Junior Seau.) Defensive end Kenyon Coleman returned from a
2{-game absence to recover two fumbles. And quarterback Cade McNown
fought off the flu to further his Heisman Trophy candidacy with 395
yards and three touchdowns.
</P>
<P>
   Brown's contributions might have been the most surprising
considering past performance. He rushed for 6 yards against Texas,
did not play against Houston (turf toe) and had 31 yards against
Washington State. But in UCLA's most important games, Arizona and
Oregon, he gained 192 yards.
</P>
<P>
   The Phoenix native credits his improvement to good health and
maternal advice. Until this season, Brown had suffered one injury
after another: knees, ankles, shoulder, even stomach. He missed the
Cotton Bowl with a bad knee and part of spring practice with food
poisoning.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was starting to look like I was injury-prone,'' he said. ``I
didn't want that to happen.''
</P>
<P>
   His mother, Joyce, suggested a diet based on juices and herbs,
which she said would strengthen his ligaments and tendons. So Brown
inhaled all the kale and collard greens he could find, beat the
turf toe in one week, and has prospered since.
</P>
<P>
   ``My mom knew. She just knew exactly what I needed to do,''
Brown said, smiling.
</P>
<P>
   Sound mind, sound body, and now the starting tailback job is his
to lose.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-18-98 2344EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
