<HEADLINE>
`MAGIC' CHARMS WAY INTO TOP SPOT IN OPENING WEEKEND
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By TERRI HARDY  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES -- ``Practical Magic'' cast a winning spell at the
nation's box office with an estimated $13.6 &UR;  &LR; million at 2,652
theaters from Friday through Sunday, studio sources said.
</P>
<P>
   The Warner Bros. release, with Sandra Bullock and Nicole Kidman
as New England sisters who inherit magical powers, performed in
line with industry expectations. The marketing took advantage of
Halloween's approach to lure customers during what is traditionally
a slow movie-going period.
</P>
<P>
   ``Warner Bros. has to be pleased because this was something of a
high-risk picture,'' said analyst Arthur Rockwell of Drake &AMP; Co.
``I think its star power and theme were enough to give it a
respectable opening.''
</P>
<P>
   `` &UR;  &LR; `Practical Magic' was able to draw in women and the date
crowd,'' said Robert Bucksbaum, president of the Reel Source
forecasting service.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; Universal's ``Bride of Chucky'' finished a strong second with
an estimated $11.8 &UR;  &LR; million at 2,411 theaters as the horror-comedy,
the fourth in the Chucky series, benefited from a memorable
``Chucky gets lucky'' ad campaign, as well as the tie-in to the
Halloween season and the genre's ongoing appeal to teens and young
adults.
</P>
<P>
   ``Halloween is definitely on people's minds at this time of
year,'' Bucksbaum said.
</P>
<P>
   Moviegoers continued marching to see ``Antz.'' The
computer-animated comedy came in a close third with $11.3 &UR;  &LR; million
at 2,903 sites in its third weekend, dropping only 23 percent from
its previous Friday through Sunday. The DreamWorks SKG release has
drawn $51.6 &UR;  &LR; million in 17 days after setting a record for an
October debut and soon will top the $63 &UR;  &LR; million record set by
``Beavis and Butt-head'' as the top non-Disney animated film.
</P>
<P>
   The success of ``Antz'' may wind up helping Disney's ``A Bug's
Life,'' another computer-animated comedy, scheduled for release
Nov. 20. Audiences appear to be responding well to trailers for ``A
Bug's Life'' when they run before screenings of ``Antz.''
</P>
<P>
   The weekend's other major opening, Disney's much-anticipated
roll-out of ``Beloved,'' finished fourth with a less-than-expected
$8.2 &UR;  &LR; million at 1,501 theaters. Bucksbaum pointed out that the
drama, starring Oprah Winfrey as a runaway slave, was unable to
draw a broad-based audience beyond women, despite strong reviews
and an extensive marketing campaign.
</P>
<P>
   `` &UR;  &LR; `Beloved' was not able to cross over to men,'' the analyst
said, also noting that the film's running time of nearly three
hours limits the number of daily showings. ``We still think it's
such a strong film that it will get an Academy Award Best Picture
nomination and it will take in about $80 &UR;  &LR; million. It's going to
take awhile, though.''
</P>
<P>
   Winfrey, one of the producers on the film, acquired the rights
to Toni Morrison's novel and made many appearances to promote the
movie.
</P>
<P>
   Holdover films took the remaining top 10 slots, led by New
Line's fifth weekend of ``Rush Hour'' with $7.8 &UR;  &LR; million at 2,724
theaters to eclipse the $109 &UR;  &LR; million mark and underscore the hit
comedy's profitability, given its $35 &UR;  &LR; million price tag.
PolyGram's third weekend of ``What Dreams May Come'' was next with
$6.5 &UR;  &LR; million at 2,506 sites to push its 24-day take to
$41.2 &UR;  &LR; million _ far short of the spiritual drama's $90 &UR;  &LR; million
budget.
</P>
<P>
   Paramount's third weekend of ``A Night at the Roxbury'' finished
seventh with $3.9 &UR;  &LR; million at 2,169 theaters. Next came Sony's
fourth weekend of ``Urban Legend'' with $2.9 &UR;  &LR; million at 2,063
screens, MGM's fourth weekend of ``Ronin'' with $2.7 &UR;  &LR; million at
1,982 locations and Disney's second weekend of Eddie Murphy's
``Holy Man'' with a disappointing $2.4 &UR;  &LR; million at 2,013 theaters.
``Holy Man'' generated less than half its opening weekend audience,
and the $60 &UR;  &LR; million project is certain to generate hefty amounts
of red ink.
</P>
<P>
   Coming in a still-strong 11th was ``There's Something About
Mary'' with $2.9 &UR;  &LR; million at 1,405 theaters in its first finish
outside the top 10 after 14 weekends. The comedy's 96-day total has
hit $164.8 &UR;  &LR; million for 20th Century Fox, making it the
48th-highest domestic grosser ever, placing just after ``The
Exorcist.''
</P>
<P>
   DreamWorks' 12th weekend of ``Saving Private Ryan'' drew
$1 &UR;  &LR; million at 851 screens, raising its total to $187.8 &UR;  &LR; million,
28th-highest domestic gross after ``Toy Story.''
</P>
<P>
   Overall, business continued to defy the season's traditional
slowdown in moviegoing. The three-day gross of about $80 &UR;  &LR; million
was up 10 percent from the same weekend last year. Year-to-date
business has reached $5.3 &UR;  &LR; billion, 12 percent ahead of the same
period last year.
</P>
<P>
   Studios will release more high-profile movies next weekend,
including New Line's comedy ``Pleasantville,'' Warner's Kurt
Russell action-drama ``Soldier'' and Sony's thriller ``Apt Pupil.''
Bucksbaum said ``Pleasantville,'' in which two modern-day teens
wind up in a 1950s sitcom, has the strongest prospects.
</P>
<P>
   Additionally, Miramax will go nationwide with ``The Mighty,''
and the family drama could break out because of high
audience-approval ratings. Second-weekend grosses were moderate
with $370,000 at 129 sites.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
