<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BESTDRESSED-COPS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LAPD RANKS NO. 1 WITH FASHION POLICE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By LEE CONDON  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES -- Hollywood celebrities typically top the lists of
the best dressed, but the Los Angeles police proved Sunday that
their officers also set national fashion trends.
</P>
<P>
   Police Chief Bernard C. Parks, included earlier this year on
People magazine's most-beautiful people list, accepted an award
from the National Association of Uniform Manufacturers for having
the best-dressed force in the country among law enforcement
agencies with more than 200 members.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our uniforms project the legendary image of our department,''
said Parks in a written statement.
</P>
<P>
   ``No one can appreciate the pride we feel when we wear the
uniform of the Los Angeles Police Department,'' said Parks, who
received the award while attending a national conference of police
chiefs in Salt Lake City.
</P>
<P>
   Mayor Richard Riordan applauded the LAPD's accomplishment,
saying, ``It gives people confidence and pride in themselves.''
</P>
<P>
   But Riordan also joked that LAPD officers certainly must stand
out in Los Angeles, a city that he contends needs some fashion
tutoring.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's ironic because we are one of the worst-dressed cities in
the world. People are so casual,'' Riordan said. ``Los Angeles
probably has the worst-dressed people in the world, starting with
their mayor.''
</P>
<P>
   The purpose of the award is to honor police departments that
have gone ``above and beyond the call of duty'' in uniform
standards, said Bernard J. Lepper, executive director of the
association. Entrants are judged on neatness, projection of
authority, practicality and adherence to uniform regulations.
</P>
<P>
   ``A uniform is the first thing people notice about a police
officer,'' Lepper said in a written statement. ``A clean, neat and
well-tailored uniform not only looks better but also commands
respect and encourages public confidence in law enforcement.''
</P>
<P>
   Sgt. Dan Mastro said officers are strongly encouraged to look
their best while on the job and are even told their shoes need to
be ``spit-shine'' clean.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you have someone who looks like a slob, how impressive is
that going to be if we handle your radio call?'' Mastro said.
</P>
<P>
   Mastro actually investigated the issue of uniforms a few years
back when he worked as a department representative advising Mattel,
when the toy giant was considering how to design clothes for a
police version of Barbie and Ken.
</P>
<P>
   Mastro said he found out that about 75 percent of the police
departments in the nation wear an outfit quite similar to the
simple dark blue uniforms worn by the LAPD.
</P>
<P>
   He also pointed out that like celebrities, LAPD officers have to
look their best since they are frequently on television because of
all the police-related reality shows.
</P>
<P>
   ``The LAPD television show is one of the most popular shows in
the world,'' Mastro said. ``What we do goes everywhere. We're it.
We're state of the art.''
</P>
<P>
   Sgt. Roger Archambault said Parks has had an impact on uniform
policy since becoming chief, asking that police in administrative
jobs, especially those working at Parker Center, wear uniforms
rather than business attire.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's easier than having to go out and buy a bunch of suits
anyhow,'' Archambault said.
</P>
<P>
   LAPD has won uniform awards before, and Archambault said he
believes it is because the clothes are so simple.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our uniforms look a little better. In Chicago, they have these
funny checkerboard hats. They look like cab drivers,'' Archambault
said.
</P>
<P>
   Sgt. Frank Sobisky of the Los Angeles County Sheriff's
Department acknowledged that the LAPD's dark uniforms look sharp
but said he likes the Sheriff's Department's khaki shirt and olive
green pants just as much, if not more.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to love the Marines to love our uniform, because it
looks so much like a Marine uniform,'' Sobisky said.
</P>
<P>
   He also likes simplicity in a police officer's uniform.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you watch some of those `Cops' shows, some of them are
god-awful ugly. I don't like it when they start putting stripes all
over them,'' Sobisky said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
