<DOCNO> NYT19981018.0260 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-18 23:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3857 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-LOPEZCOLUMN-HNS &LR;      10-18 0924
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-LOPEZCOLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
John P.Lopez
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; c. 1998, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
CHICAGO _ Richie Cunningham accounted for most of the offense. It
looked like Potsie accounted for everything else.
</P>
<P>
   Oh, how the Dallas Cowboys long for the happy days of showing up
for games like Sunday's against the pitifully poor Chicago Bears
and knowing that somehow, some way they would find a way to stomp
the meek pretenders.
</P>
<P>
   But those days are gone. The meek inherited a 13-12 win at
Soldier Field. The Cowboys celebrated their upcoming ``open date''
one week early.
</P>
<P>
   ``In my mind, I think we're still the better team,'' Cowboys
running back Emmitt Smith said afterward. ``It just didn't show.''
</P>
<P>
   That might be the whole problem. The Cowboys still think they
are the Cowboys. You could see it in their strut. You could hear it
in their words, even after the loss.
</P>
<P>
   ``We played to the level of our opponent,'' cornerback Deion
Sanders said.
</P>
<P>
   But maybe they didn't play down. Maybe this is where the 'Boys
belonged. Clearly, it was a game that left the Cowboys wind-whipped
and shaken. It was bad professional football virtually from the
start, with so many mental mistakes, bobbles, turnovers, missed
assignments and silly penalties.
</P>
<P>
   It raised several questions, but none more obvious than this
one: Exactly which one of these teams has been a pretender through
the first seven weeks of the season?
</P>
<P>
   After all, the Bears, a meager 1-5 coming in, willingly admitted
to their shortcomings since the preseason. They knew they were bad
and tried to make the most of it, which in its own way seems
dignified.
</P>
<P>
   But until an eight-turnover debacle last weekend against the
Cardinals, the Very Bad Bears played the way very bad teams should
play _ with heart and determination, making the most out of a
little.
</P>
<P>
   They lost a one-point heartbreaker to Jacksonville. They lost by
four points to Pittsburgh, three to mighty Minnesota, and even beat
the Detroit Lions 31-27.
</P>
<P>
   ``We know we have a lot to work on, but it's so much fun to
coach a team that wants to come out and play hard every week,''
Chicago coach Dave Wannstedt said.
</P>
<P>
   The Cowboys, on the other hand, pretended to be close to the
same squad that dominated the league back in the happy days, not
the 6-10 team of a year ago. Until Sunday, they nearly had us all
convinced.
</P>
<P>
   The 4-2 record Dallas carried into Sunday's game looked certain
to be on its way to 5-2 against the Very Bad Bears. People actually
were talking about the Cowboys going 11-5 or even 12-4.
</P>
<P>
   But Sunday's effort only showed that the days of banking on
Smith's blasting through defenses when the game is on the line are
numbered. The days of Michael Irvin snagging everything in sight _
especially crucial third-down tosses right between his hands _
suddenly seem to be fading.
</P>
<P>
   The days of Troy Aikman wearing something other than civilian
clothes cannot come soon enough. And more than anything, the
Cowboys' secondary is either in big trouble or Wannstedt's new
nickname soon will be ``Air Dave.''
</P>
<P>
   If Bears quarterback Erik Kramer can hit seven receivers and
blister the Cowboys for 233 yards _ 116 on the Bears' final two
decisive drives _ imagine what the Vikings, Cris Carter and Randy
Moss and Co., will do in a few weeks.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have not arrived, which is obvious,'' Cowboys coach Chan
Gailey said.
</P>
<P>
   A week ago, the Cowboys talked about having lots of heart in
pulling out a close game against winless Carolina. And indeed,
there was no denying big contributions from several veterans,
especially Sanders.
</P>
<P>
   But it might all have been a case of the Cowboys playing
pretend, or at least relying heavily on the incomparable Sanders
pulling them to victory.
</P>
<P>
   A week ago, Sanders saved the game with a late interception.
Before that, he almost single-handedly won a Monday-night game
against the Giants.
</P>
<P>
   But on Sunday, the Bears successfully took Sanders out of the
game. He touched the ball only twice on punt returns for one yard.
When he played on offense, the Cowboys threw in Sanders' direction
just twice, unsuccessfully both times. And when Sanders was on
defense, Kramer threw only token short routes in front of him.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's probably the best cornerback there's ever been,'' Kramer
said. ``We weren't going to test him.''
</P>
<P>
   The Very Bad Bears at least were smart. It only led to the
Cowboys' performance looking more dismal.
</P>
<P>
   Smith was still solid, sure. He slipped through cracks in the
line for 78 yards. But when a win was a mere clock-killing drive
away, Smith was slammed back, and Gailey turned to the passing
game.
</P>
<P>
   Which only brought to light a more vital question: Is something
wrong with Irvin?
</P>
<P>
   Like Smith, Irvin is having a good season statistically _ 33
catches for 516 yards going into Sunday. But Ernie Mills and even
Billy Davis have higher per-catch averages than Irvin's 15.6, and
Irvin still is looking to score his first touchdown of the year.
</P>
<P>
   Sunday, when the Cowboys faced third-and-nine with the game on
the line late in the fourth quarter, quarterback Jason Garrett hit
Irvin on a crossing route. The ball slipped through Irvin's hands.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Kevin Smith, the embattled cornerback opposite
Sanders, was consistently scorched, giving up eight of the 18
completions Kramer had.
</P>
<P>
   This Cowboys team entered the day with a familiar strut but
ended it with Gailey proclaiming, ``I don't know where we are right
now.''
</P>
<P>
   It's certainly not happy days.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-18-98 2358EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
